<FIRST>r w AM-Soviets-Threat     05-24 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviets-Threat,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Soviets Pulling Back From Threat to Stop Destroying SS-23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviets have pulled back from a recent
threat to stop destroying a missile covered by last year's treaty
covering medium-range nuclear missiles, The Washington Post
reported in its Thursday editions.
   The missile is the SS-23, one of the weapons that will be taken
apart under the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces pact that went
into effect last year.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze had told journalists
in Bonn recently that Soviet destruction of the SS-23s might be
halted if NATO deployed a similar type of missile.
   The SS-23 has a range of slightly more than 300 miles, the
minimum distance set by the INF treaty. The United States and its
western allies are considering deployment of a new Lance missile
with a range just under the limit set by the treaty.
   The Soviets have gone ahead and moved almost two dozen SS-23s
from a storage site to an elimination site, the Post reported,
quoting unnamed U.S. and Soviet sources.
   All the SS-23s must be destroyed by Dec. 31, but ample time
remains to meet the deadline, the officials said. While the Soviets
haven't yet destroyed any of the 239 SS-23s deployed before the
pact took effect, they have destroyed training missiles and
launchers, the Post said.
</TEXT>
