<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina 2ndLd-Writethru   05-24 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0755,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alfonsin to Stay Til Dec. 10; Economic Plan by Sunday</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with protest at congress, Menem
comments. Pickup 7th pvs, `The mood...' DELETES 13th pvs, `Menem said...'
which moved up.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raul Alfonsin said
Tuesday he won't leave office early because President-elect Carlos
Menem will not agree on policies to stabilize the economy during a
transfer of power.
   ``We will get to the 10th of December with the extraordinary
effort of the Argentine people,'' Alfonsin said in a 14-minute
speech broadcast nationwide.
   His six-year term expires Dec. 10. Alfonsin's Radical Civic
Union and Menem's Peronist Party had been holding talks on the
possibility of an early transition because of the economic crisis.
   After Alfonsin's speech his Cabinet members submitted their
resignations. Press secretary Jose Ignacio Lopez said Alfonsin will
decide Wednesday whether to accept them.
   Menem told the independent news agency Diarios y Noticias
Tuesday night that his party did not break off the transition
negotiations that were initiated by Alfonsin last weekend. ``We
simply were not in agreement with the (economic) proposals of the
ruling party,'' he said.
   ``As I said before, I want the president to depart with every
honor, without resigning, as befits a man who has struggled for
democracy.''
   About 3,000 people gathered outside Congress Tuesday night for
what they called a ``hunger march.'' The demonstration was
organized by the United Left alliance to protest inflation and
increased utility rates approved last week by the government.
   ``There will be no pact or social peace arranged from above,
because now begins the struggle and mobilization of those from
below,'' Patricio Echegaray, secretary-general of the Communist
Party, told the crowd.
   Alfonsin said his Radical Civic Union will unveil its own
economic program by Sunday. ``It will be as hard as you can
imagine,'' he said, and suitable for ``an economy of war ... a
government in crisis.''
   The mood in Buenos Aires was somber as teachers and other public
employees planned strikes for higher wages, stores in the capital
marked up prices and some supermarkets rationed purchases.
   Menem, 58, defeated presidential nominee Eduardo Angeloz of the
Radical Civic Union in national elections on May 14. The Peronists
won virtual control of both houses of Congress.
   Instead of giving the economy a boost of confidence, the
election was followed by a plunge in value of the austral against
the dollar. Interest rates soared to record highs and other key
economic indicators grew worse.
   Inflation is projected at 50 percent this month. Wages are
shrinking, unemployment and public anger are rising, the national
budget is in deficit, reserves in the Central Bank are low and no
payments are being made on the foreign debt.
   Banks and foreign exchange houses were closed Monday and Tuesday
as the government increased public utility rates and raised taxes
to help balance the budget. Banks will resume restricted operations
Wednesday, but exchange houses will remain closed until Monday.
   Peronists rejected the tariff increases and insisted that the
national minimum wage be raised substantially and the federal
government bail out provinces _ almost all Peronist-governed _ that
could not meet their payrolls.
   Menem earlier indicated he might be willing to take office
early. Analysts said he backed out because he counted on the
seven-month transition to prepare his own economic program.
   ``He doesn't want to take over in the middle of a crisis he
didn't cause,'' said Angel Pena, chief economist at the
Mediterranean Foundation think tank. ``It could be worse in
December, but not necessarily.''
</TEXT>
