<HEAD>School Officials Worry About Foreign Trips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School board members have decided not to
sponsor any more foreign-exchange programs because of fears of
terrorism.
   The decision was made because rioting and looting in the streets
of Caracas, Venezuela, coincided with a trip by Hempfield Area High
School students to a neighboring town this spring.
   ``We tried calling the State Department, but it's impossible to
make a determination (about instability). Venezuela has been stable
for so many years. It's so unpredictable,'' Superintendent Margaret
Smith said.
   Students in the Hempfield Area School District who want to
travel abroad still can do so by making their own arrangements,
officials said.
