<FIRST>u a AM-CompanyTrial     05-24 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Company Trial,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>65 Guilty Verdicts at End of Nevada's Longest Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury convicted 12 people Tuesday on
charges they operated an interstate drug ring that called itself
``The Company.'' The trial lasted 16 months.
   The U.S. District Court jury found all the defendants in the
case guilty of 65 of the 71 counts against them.
   Members of the ring were accused of making and selling
methamphetamines and operating a marijuana plantation and other
drug operations in northern California. They allegedly distributed
the drugs from northern Califorian through western Nevada and south
to San Diego.
   Richard Rupley Sr., the ringleader of the cartel based in nearby
Sparks, was convicted on all 15 counts.
   Rupley, John Bonnenfant and Dwain and Eddie Baker were found
guilty of conducting a continuing criminal enterprise, which
carries a maximum penalty of life imprisonment.
   The jury acquitted the defendants on three counts, and said they
could not agree on a verdict on three other charges after 10 days
of deliberations.
   The defendants appeared undaunted by the trial's outcome,
chatting with each other as the verdicts were read and chuckling as
Judge Edward C. Reed Jr. mispronounced one defendant's name.
Bonnenfant and another defendant winked and waved at girlfriends in
the audience.
   Reed ordered the jurors, who first entered the courtroom on Jan.
19, 1988, to return Wednesday afternoon for the trial's final phase.
   They will determine whether the defendants should forfeit about
$2 million to $3 million worth of possessions seized during their
arrests.
   Prosecutors hope to get the cars, weapons and other items to
help defray the huge cost of trying the case, estimated at $8
million to $10 million.
   Twenty-four people originally were indicted in the case, but
half were removed before it went to trial after pleading guilty to
reduced charges in exchange for cooperating with the government.
   The charges against the defendants convicted Tuesday included
manufacture, possession and possesion for sale of methamphetamines
and marijuana; interstate transportation in aid of racketeering;
wiretapping, and unlawful use of a firearm.
   Except for the continuing criminal enterprise charge, most of
the counts carry a maximum sentence of 5 years in prison and some
permit a maximum sentence of 20 years.
</TEXT>
