<FIRST>r a AM-Fire-Crafts     05-24 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fire-Crafts,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Destroys Princeton Home With Collection Of Crafts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire started accidentally by a plumber
Tuesday destroyed a Princeton home housing a large collection of
works by famed furniture maker and craftsman George Nakashima,
officials said.
   More than 100 pieces of woodwork and furniture by Nakashima were
destroyed, the New York Times reported Wednesday.
   Nakashima, 83, is considered by many to be the elder statesman
of American crafts.
   Only two pieces of the collection, owned by Dr. Arthur and
Evelyn Krosnick, survived. A picture frame and a boardroom table
were on loan for an exhibit of Nakashima's work at the American
Craft Museum in New York City.
   ``It is a great loss _ for them and for us,'' Nakashima told the
Times in an interview from his studio in New Hope, Pa. ``Some of
the pieces can be replaced, but many cannot. They are precise
pieces _ one of a kind, many of them.''
   The blaze began about 11:20 a.m. when an acetylene torch being
used by the plumber caught fire, said Princeton Township Police Lt.
Mario Musso. The plumber set the torch on the floor while he looked
for something to extinguish the flames, and while he was gone the
fire engulfed the basement and spread to the rest of the house,
Musso said.
   Princeton Fire Chief Mark Freda estimated damages to the home
and its contents at about $1 million. The house was in a secluded,
wooded area.
   Mrs. Krosnick and her housekeeper escaped without injury,
officials said. The plumber was treated for minor burns to his
hands and hair at a hospital and released.
</TEXT>
