<FIRST>u w AM-Noriega-Mentors     05-24 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Noriega-Mentors,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to correct cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Manuel's Manual Praises Genghis Khan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mongolian marauder Genghis Khan should be
praised as the father of psychological warfare, Panamanian leader
Manuel Antonio Noriega wrote in a 1975 primer on techniques of
manipulating the masses.
   ``He, better than anyone, employed the technique of the rumor
.... and with it assured the conquest of half the world with only a
handful of men,'' Noriega wrote about the 12th century warrior in
an 80-page treatise called ``Psychological Operations.''
   The manual, obtained by the Panama City bureau of The Washington
Post, was the subject of a story in the newspaper's Wednesday
editions.
   Panama's de facto ruler wrote the book while he was a lieutenant
colonel in charge of Panama's military intelligence service. The
book quotes such diverse thinkers as Aristotle and Sigmund Freud,
and expresses admiration for such figures as Mao Zedong, Ho Chi
Minh and Fidel Castro.
   The manual, according to the Post, develops Noriega's theory of
a malleable and easily exploited ``mass man.''
</TEXT>
