<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SirhanParole 4thLd-Writethru a0779 05-24 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sirhan Parole, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0779,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sirhan Sirhan Denied Parole in Kennedy Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: UPDATES throughout with quotes, details on hearing, Sirhan eligible
for another hearing in one year; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOLEDAD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sirhan Sirhan, serving life in prison for
assassinating Sen. Robert F. Kennedy, was denied parole for the
10th time Tuesday despite saying he felt ``very remorseful'' about
the slaying.
   The state Board of Prison Terms made its decision after
deliberating for nearly an hour, saying Sirhan was unsuitable for
parole and calling Kennedy's 1968 murder one of the most shocking
crimes in U.S. history.
   ``You still constitute a danger to society,'' David Brown,
chairman of the three-member panel, told Sirhan, who will be
eligible for parole again in a year.
   In denying Sirhan's release, the board cited his unstable social
history and ``selective memory'' of the June 5, 1968 slaying and
events leading to it. The board also told Sirhan they wanted him to
complete a more extensive psychiatric evaluation.
   Sirhan, 45, showed no visible reaction to the decision, but
expressed his frustration at a news conference after the hearing.
   ``Oftentimes I feel like a dog at the dog races. When the race
is on, he's always chasing the rabbit ... whatever I do is not
enough,'' said Sirhan, who called the panel's reasons for denying
parole ``specious at best.''
   During the four-hour hearing at the State Correctional Training
Facility in this small community about 180 miles south of San
Francisco, Sirhan told the prison board he was sorry for Kennedy's
death.
   The senator from New York was shot with a .22-caliber pistol as
he walked through the kitchen of the Ambassador Hotel in Los
Angeles shortly after winning the California Democratic
presidential primary.
   ``I feel very sad, very sorry, very remorseful ... that a human
life was taken,'' Sirhan, dressed in prison-issue blue denim shirt
and jeans, told the board. ``After 21 years .... I have become
quite convinced that my act was very wrong, morally and humanly,
toward Robert Kennedy, and especially toward his family and his
loved ones and his suporters.
   ``I realize the mistake of it and I wish from the bottom of my
heart ... that this crime, this horrible event, never occurred.
   ``I feel 21 years of this type of prison has been plenty of
punishment,'' he said. ``I wish I could reverse it and undo it but
I can't.''
   Sirhan, a Jerusalem-born Christian Arab, was sentenced to death
for Kennedy's murder but was spared the San Quentin gas chamber
after California's death penalty law was overturned in 1972 by the
state Supreme Court.
   His sentence was changed to life in prison with possibility of
parole, and Sirhan faced his first parole hearing in 1975.
   He is imprisoned at the State Correctional Training Facility.
   Sirhan last came before the board two years ago. At the time,
the panel recommended he undergo extensive psychiatric evaluation,
pursue vocational training, attend Alcoholics Anonymous sessions,
remain free of disciplinary problems, earn an associate's degree
and provide documentation of job offers.
   ``The American system of justice is going to let me go home in a
coffin,'' an angry Sirhan said then.
   On Tuesday, Sirhan and his attorney, Luke McKissack, asked that
the hearing be postponed so Sirhan could complete the psychiatric
evaluation, which began in March.
   McKissack, who engaged in frequent shouting matches with board
members, argued they should disqualify themselves as prejudiced
against Sirhan because they had taken part in a previous hearing.
   The board, however, denied his requests to postpone the hearing
and disqualify themselves.
   Sirhan, who cried out, ``I did it for my country'' seconds after
the shooting, told television interviewer David Frost in February
that he acted not ``out of personal malice towards the man but out
of concern for other people.''
   He compared his act to a Jew killing Adolf Hitler.
   Sirhan apparently was angered after Kennedy, a staunch supporter
of Israel, repeated his proposal that 50 Phantom jets be shipped to
the Jewish state.
   During the interview, Sirhan repeatedly apologized for the
killing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
