<DOCNO> AP890524-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CathedralStones     05-24 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cathedral Stones,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Great Gothic Church Finally Nearing Completion</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington Cathedral, the ``great church for
national purposes'' that Pierre L'Enfant dreamed of as part of his
plan for the nation's capital, is at last nearing completion.
   Signaling the beginning of the final phase of construction, a
flatbed truck pulled up in front of the 14th century Gothic-style
structure Tuesday with one last load of Indiana limestone.
   The first load was delivered in 1910.
   The ceremonial placing of the final stone is scheduled for Sept.
29, 1990 - 83 years to the day from the laying of the cornerstone
in 1907.
   But most of the heavy work will have been completed by this
fall, said Dick Feller, canon clerk of the works, or head of
construction for the cathedral.
   ``This is a great day,'' said the Rt. Rev. John T. Walker,
Episcopal bishop of Washington.
   ``It's been a labor of love,'' said Peter Cleland, master mason,
who has worked on the project since 1953.
   L'Enfant, the man commissioned by George Washington to lay out
the capital on the Potomac, included the church in his plans, but
no steps were taken to build it until a group of citizens took up
the project in the 1890s.
   Work has continued with few interruptions since 1907.
Construction was halted during World War I and World War II and
because of a shortage of funds in the 1970s.
   But 83 years is by no means a long time for building such an
edifice, said the Rev. Leonard Freeman, communications director at
the cathedral.
   ``This is about middle range for building a cathedral,'' Freeman
said. ``A shorty might take 50 or 60 years. Some of them go 150
years or more without having been finished.''
   ``A modern building, you put up a steel frame and put things
around it, but that's not the way this was built,'' he said. ``This
was built physically in the same manner that they were built in the
Middle Ages.''
   That is, he said, ``stone on stone.''
   Anthony J. Segreti, president of Segreti Tepper Architects, the
Washington firm overseeing the job, said, ``There's quite a
difference working on this project and on a specification office
building downtown. This type of construction you don't see in this
day and age.''
   The first section, Bethlehem Chapel, was completed in 1912; the
central tower was finished in 1964, and the nave was ready for the
nation's bicentennial in 1976.
   The cathedral was the setting for the funeral of President
Eisenhower in 1969 and a national memorial service for President
Truman in 1972. It is the final resting place of Woodrow Wilson.
Martin Luther King Jr. preached his last Sunday sermon there, three
days before he was murdered.
   Each year, about 350,000 people visit the unfinished house of
worship, the sixth largest cathedral in the world. It is a tenth of
a mile long and 289 feet wide at its widest point.
   The stones from Bybee Stone Co. of Bloomington, Ind., which has
supplied the cathedral for about 10 years, weigh from 150 to 450
pounds. There were other suppliers before Bybee, but all the
limestone has come from Indiana.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
