<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NRC-LowPower     05-24 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NRC-Low Power,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC To Study Concerns About Low-Power Nuclear Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nuclear power plants aren't designed for
low-power operation and could be strained by running at lower
levels, a panel of scientists warns.
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission said Tuesday its staff will
review concerns by NRC's Advisory Committee on Reactor Safeguards
about low-power operation. The panel counsels the NRC on potential
industry hazards.
   As a safety precaution, nuclear power plants normally operate at
low power, or 5 percent of generating capacity, before they are
permitted to increase operation and begin generating electricity.
   In a May 11 letter to NRC Chairman Lando Zech, the panel said it
has no evidence that extended low-power operation is unsafe.
   But it said it knows of ``instances in which operation at low
flow has produced excessive wear in check valves and in which
operation at low power has produced excessive vibration in a
feedwater pump not designed for extended operation at low flow.
   ``Our principal concern stems from the memory that the operators
of the Chernobyl plant, Unit 4, were unaware of the dangers of
operation at low power, whereas a careful analysis would have
convinced them that this was undesirable,'' the panel said.
   The Soviet Union plant at Chernobyl was operating at low power
when an April 1986 accident killed at least 31 people and released
a radioactive cloud that spread over a wide area.
   Eleven American nuclear power plants now have construction
permits. Among the closest to receiving low-power licenses are
Limerick in Pennsylvania, Comanche Peak in Texas, Watts Bar in
Tennessee, and Seabrook in New Hampshire.
   Low-power testing can take several months, ``but it's not a
standard time period. It's a case-by-case thing,'' said NRC
spokesman John Kopeck.
   A utility official recently said he was ``uneasy'' about
operating at 5 percent power, ``although he did not believe there
was anything unsafe about it,'' the committee said in its report.
The panel did not disclose the name of the official, or of plants
where problems occurred.
   Robert Pollard, a nuclear safety engineer for the Union of
Concerned Scientists, said in an interview Tuesday that he was
familiar with the low-power problem. The UCS is a private,
non-profit group which has been critical of some nuclear power
plants.
   ``I've certainly heard of some of the types of problems the
letter mentions, particularly when you take the large centrifugal
pumps cooled by water flowing through them,'' Pollard said.
   When there is a slower flow through the system, the pumps and
some other parts ``don't get cooled as well,'' he said.
   But Pollard said he was miffed at the reference to Chernobyl
because the reactor was unstable at low power to the point that ``I
don't know of a similar parallel in the United States.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0028 </DOCNO>
