<HEAD>Baazar Destroyed In Spectacular Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEASDS with four grafs to UPDATE with $1.5 million damage, 4
firefighters treated; picks up 4th graf, `The fire...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flames swept through a downtown produce market
and mall Tuesday, chasing scores of people into the street and
darkening the city skyline with smoke.
   There were no reports of injuries from the blaze that destroyed
the Farmer's Market Produce Bazaar and damaged an adjacent
five-story building housing the Western Metal Supply Co., Fire
Department spokesman Larry Stewart said.
   Four of the 120 firefighters who battled the fire were treated
at the scene for minor injuries and heat exhaustion, Stewart said.
   The Metro Arson Strike Team estimated damage at more than $1.5
million.
   The fire was expected to burn for hours, but was contained, Fire
Capt Bob Landis said Tuesday evening.
   The fire broke out around 2:45 p.m., said the bazaar's building
manager, George May.
   May said blaze started at the top of a second-floor stairwell
and that he tried to put it out with a fire extinguisher but it was
out of control.
   The building was full of employees and shoppers when the fire
broke out, but was speedily evacuated, May said.
   The bazaar housed 30 shops, including two wholesale produce
markets, said May, declaring the building a total loss.
   The fire's cause was unknown, and arson investigators were
called in.
