<FIRST>r w PM-IndonesiaResources     05-24 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indonesia Resources,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Distortion Seen in Countries' Reports on Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a farmer cuts down his wood lot and uses
the money for a trip to Florida, he knows he's used up an asset.
When Indonesia cuts down its tropical timber and consumes the
proceeds, that counts as national income.
   ``Our current measures of economic success are misleading,''
Robert Repetto, director of research for the World Resources
Institute, said Tuesday.
   ``A country could exhaust its mineral resources, cut down its
forests, erode its soils, pollute its aquifers, and hunt its
wildlife and fisheries to extinction but measured income would not
be affected,'' said Repetto.
   ``No business would last very long selling off its assets to
meet the current payroll,'' he pointed out, ``but many countries
are doing just that behind a screen of misleading statistics.''
   The institute is a private study group funded by foundations,
the United Nations, government agencies, corporations and
individuals.
   Repetto and four co-authors have written ``Wasting Assets:
Natural Resources in the National Income Accounts,'' which
concentrates on Indonesia. Repetto is now working on figures for
Costa Rica and China.
   Officially, Indonesia's production grew by 7 percent a year
between 1970 and 1984. Repetto says that when loss of forests, soil
and oil is taken into account, that figure falls to 4 percent.
According to the World Bank, Indonesia's population is growing at a
rate of more than 2 percent a year, so the average citizen would
see little improvement in living standards.
   Conditions have grown worse since 1984 with the drop in the
price of oil, Indonesia's major export. The bank calculates that in
1987 the average Indonesian earned $450, down from $500 the year
before.
   Repetto wants to make it clear that he is not just quarrelling
with other statisticians. The failure to take account of
disappearing resources also distorts calculations about the growth
of assets on which governments lay their plans for the future, he
said.
   ``It's a kind of deficit financing, too important to be left to
statisticians,'' he added in an interview. ``This is like the
lawyer in the depression who told his wife at dinner that he'd had
a pretty good day _ no clients, but he managed to sell his desk.''
   Repetto said he had presented his work to the United Nations,
which is revising its method of calculating a country's growth. The
U.N. method is the standard method in use. He reported that U.N.
officials were sympathetic but do not have the money to make as
complete a revision as he's seeking.
   Repetto suggested that the cost would not be high, pointing out
that he did the present study in six months with the help of four
graduate students. The calculations need not be made for all
countries, only those where natural resources are a major part of
total resources, he said.
   ``That would have been true of the United States in 1850,'' he
explained. ``Now our big resource is a skilled and educated
population. We maintain our forest and soil, so taking depletion of
natural resources into account would not change our figures that
much, or the figures of other highly developed countries.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Maine     05-24 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Maine,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: An Army of Journalists Tracks The President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The picturesque southern Maine resort town of
Kennebunkport reverberated with eerie squeals, squawks and beeps
last weekend.
   It wasn't the sound of waterfowl or other wildlife. It was part
of a paging system used by the White House to alert reporters on
the Bush watch of impending presidential activities.
   An army of nearly 500 reporters, both American and French,
overtook Bush's vacation home for his meeting with French President
Francois Mitterrand.
   Now that the weather has turned warmer, Bush is expected to
return quite frequently to his family house on a point jutting into
the Atlantic Ocean.
   During his most recent visit, the U.S. press corps set up work
quarters at a Lithuanian Franciscan monastery in town and rented
electronic pagers from the White House.
   With a single phone call, White House official Bruce Zanca could
activate all the voice-alert pagers at once to let news people who
had strayed from the monastery know an event was about to take
place.
   Then they would all converge at the monastery at once. And that
always meant a chaotic arrival scene since few journalists hung
around the monastery when nothing was going on.
   Every time Bush would leave his compound _ to jog, to play golf,
to go to a restaurant _ there would be an announcement over the
paging system.
   Since reporters almost outnumbered locals in town, each time the
pagers went off simultaneously, there was an enormous cacophony
throughout town. Entire restaurants would erupt in the strange
noise. Tourists would pause on the sidewalk and gawk. Hotel lobbies
would buzz with the crackling announcements.
   One time, the pagers even went off _ dozens of them at once _ in
the middle of a press briefing at the monastery by press secretary
Marlin Fitzwater, who first looked perplexed, then bemused.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   There are now bumper stickers on cars in the Maine resort town
that proclaim: ``KenneBushport.'' A helipad has been added to the
Bush compound where a parking lot used to be. And there is a police
checkpoint on the road overlooking Bush's house.
   Traffic is directed to stop at a partial barricade so an officer
can tell motorists to go ahead. The road is only closed at night
and when Bush is leaving the compound.
   Bush was born in Massachusetts, grew up in Connecticut and
usually claims Texas as his home state.
   But that doesn't stop Maine from claiming him as a native son.
Bush has been vacationing there all his life.
   A packet of tourist information put out by the state of Maine
includes a ``Dear Friends'' cover letter that says, ``It is my
great pleasure to welcome you to the home state of the president of
the United States.''
   The letter was penned by Doro Bush LeBlond, Bush's daughter, who
recently went to work for the Maine Office of Tourism.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Bush has been heeding his self-imposed rule against answering
reporters' questions at picture-taking sessions _ but with some
flexibility.
   Bush, meeting with the president of Iceland, Vigdis
Finnbogadottir, in the Oval Office earlier this week, ignored
reporters' first two questions. A radio reporter tried a final
shot: ``Any word from (Chancellor) Kohl yet?''
   At the time, there was considerable interest in whether the West
German leader had contacted Bush to discuss the latest in a round
of proposed compromises to ease a U.S.-West German split on the
future role of short-range nuclear weapons in western Europe.
   Bush, never taking his eyes off the Icelandic president, said,
``This is a photo opportunity, therefore I don't tell them, yes,
I've heard from Chancellor Kohl, because otherwise it would ruin
the discipline.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Banking-Securities     05-24 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Banking-Securities,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Plans to Expand Commercial Bank Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will try to jump start
last year's failed campaign by the Reagan administration to expand
commercial bank powers, a senior Treasury official says.
   Robert R. Glauber, Treasury undersecretary for finance, told a
financial services lobby group Tuesday that the Bush
administration, like the Reagan administration before it, believes
banks can compete against their foreign competitors only by
offering currently forbidden services, such as securities
underwriting.
   Glauber's speech to the Financial Services Council was the first
substantive statement on the subject by a senior Bush
administration official. And in later remarks to reporters, Glauber
said he hoped the restructuring could be addressed next year once
Bush's plan to rescue the savings and loan industry is passed.
   Glauber, the top administration policymaker for banking and
financial issues, noted that banks in France, West Germany and
Great Britain are permitted to underwrite, buy and sell securities,
offer insurance, develop real estate and invest in industrial
companies.
   Partly as a result of that, foreign banks have outgrown U.S.
institutions, he said, noting that in 1970 seven U.S. banks ranked
among the world's largest. That share slipped to three in 1980 and
none currently, he said.
   ``Permitting ... a broad array of financial services and
products ... can only help U.S. firms stem the loss of customers to
less regulated foreign firms,'' he said.
   However, U.S. banks have been barred from securities
underwriting since 1933, when Congress passed the Glass-Steagall
Act separating commercial and investment banking.
   Opponents of repealing Glass-Steagall argue that investment
banking is too risky for institutions with federally insured
deposits. But Glauber said: ``Securities underwriting is no more
risky _ and probably less risky _ than commercial lending.''
   He did not specify exactly how the administration would extend
new powers to banks, but he spoke favorably of a bill passed by the
Senate last year. Similar legislation foundered in the House,
caught in a jurisdictional dispute between two committee chairmen.
   The Senate bill, versions of which have been reintroduced this
year in both chambers of Congress, permitted bank holding
companies, through subsidiaries and with certain safeguards, to
underwrite corporate bonds and most other securities except
corporate stock.
   In remarks to reporters following his speech, Glauber said he
believed Congress would pause this year after passing Bush's
savings and loan plan and then tackle proposals for restructuring
of the financial system next year.
   The legislation's prospects could be hurt because some members
of Congress are blaming ill-advised deregulation for the S&amp;L
industry's problems.
   But, Glauber said, ``it is ... clear that the model of the
thrift industry in the early 1980s _ with its lack of private,
up-front capital and ill-supervised reform _ is not the model to be
followed as we move forward.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     05-24 0905</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Eases Drought, No Help For Wheat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain has helped take the edge off persistent
drought conditions in the central and southern Great Plains and has
slowed field work in the eastern Corn Belt and the Delta region,
say government crop watchers.
   But despite the rain, the outlook for winter wheat in much of
the plains continues to be poor. Harvest is under way in several
states, including Texas and Oklahoma.
   On Capitol Hill, lawmakers are putting together a 1989 version
of last year's huge $3.9 billion drought aid package. Although no
firm cost estimate has been tied to the current package, it would
contain many of the financial aid features of last year's measure.
   The latest report by the Joint Agricultural Weather Facility
said corn planting nationally was 84 percent complete by the end of
the May 15-21 survey week, lagging the normal pace by only two
percentage points. However, in the wetter areas of the eastern Corn
Belt, planting of the new crop lagged far behind.
   ``Planting was complete in Texas and nearly complete in Georgia,
Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Missouri and Nebraska,'' the report said.
   But in Ohio, where 85 percent of the corn acreage is usually
planted by now, only 24 percent was seeded, the report said. In
Pennsylvania, 19 percent of the corn was planted by May 21,
compared with 62 percent in normal years.
   The weather facility, operated by the Agriculture and Commerce
departments, said the 1989 soybean crop was about 39 percent
planted, only two percentage points behind normal. However,
plantings lagged sharply in some areas, including Ohio, where only
6 percent of the estimated soybean acreage had been planted,
compared with a normal 56 percent.
   Cotton plantings, at 60 percent, were nine points behind the
usual rate. Although planting was complete in California, it lagged
in the Delta and Southeast.
   A related report by the USDA's 1989 drought task force headed by
Undersecretary Richard Crowder said that ``timely rains in the Corn
Belt are promoting rapid germination and establishment of this
year's crop.''
   But the report added that the impact of recent rain in winter
wheat areas will depend, in part, on future weather.
   ``If another (weather) front brings more rain as predicted,
moderate improvement in crop conditions could occur,'' the task
force said.
   The National Weather Service calls for ``moderate to heavy rain
in the Great Plains and Corn Belt in the next 5 to 10 days,'' it
added. ``The outlook through mid-June still calls for cool, wet
weather in the South and East, and warm, dry weather from the
eastern Dakotas into the central Corn Belt.''
   A new 30- and 90-day weather outlook is scheduled to be issued
by the Weather Service next week.
   Meanwhile, leaders of the House Agriculture Committee agreed
Tuesday to push through a broad package of assistance this week for
farmers suffering crop losses from continuing drought.
   The committee, under the agreement worked out by Democrats and
Republicans, will act on the legislation at a session Thursday. The
relief package will be brought before the House at an undetermined
date after lawmakers return from a Memorial Day recess.
   ``I think the chances that a bill will be passed and signed into
law by the president ... have dramatically improved,'' Rep. Pat
Roberts, R-Kan., said after the meeting of committee leaders,
including the panel's chairman, Rep. Kika de la Garza, D-Texas.
   The aid package will mirror relief programs enacted by Congress
last year to aid producers in the Midwest and northern Great Plains.
   In general, federal payments would be made to farmers who suffer
losses of more than 35 percent on their crops.
   The relief would be available for all crops _ not just specific
hard-hit ones like wheat _ because of damages from drought,
freezing temperatures, hail, excessive moisture and other problems,
according to Scott Swenson, a spokesman for Rep. Dan Glickman,
D-Kan., chairman of the Agriculture subcomittee on wheat, soybeans
and feed grains.
   Lawmakers are considering the new drought package because the
Agriculture Department has said the 1989 winter wheat crop doesn't
qualify for any of the $3.9 billion in assistance approved in 1988.
   A group of senators last week introduced drought relief
legislation to extend last year's assistance programs to the winter
wheat crop. Similar proposals had been offered in the House.
   But Roberts said House committee leaders decided to go with a
``generic bill'' as a way of broadening support as well as ensuring
that adequate aid is available to spring-planted crops if the
drought worsens or spreads to other regions.
   According to USDA's current estimate, the 1989 winter wheat
harvest may hit an 11-year low of 1.43 billion bushels, including a
drop of more than one-third in Kansas, traditionally the nation's
leading producer.
   Under last year's relief program, farmers received federal
payments covering 65 percent of income lost from the crop damages
exceeding 35 percent, and 90 percent of income lost from damages to
that portion of the crop exceeding 75 percent losses.
   Swenson said a similar formula is planned in the House bill
although that could be changed later.
   Roberts said recent crop estimates by USDA made it clear that
the costs of any drought relief program shouldn't pose a budget
problem. The federal wheat subsidy program is expected to cost much
less this year because of higher market prices stemming from the
drought.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
