<FIRST>u a AM-PrisonDisturbance 2ndLd-Writethru a0401 05-24 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Disturbance, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0401,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>330 Inmates Refuse To Return To Cells at Texas Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with most prisoners' return to
cells; quote, minor editing; picks up 13th graf pvs, `A fire...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 federal prisoners at a
privately operated detention center refused to return to their
cells to protest living conditions and food quality, authorities
said.
   Law enforcement officers from 12 federal, state and local
agencies were dispatched to the Eden Detention Center in central
Texas to quell the disturbance, officials said.
   The inmates were upset with prison conditions and food and
refused to return to their dormitories, Concho County Sheriff Bill
Fiveash said. He said a few mattresses were burned, but the protest
was generally non-violent.
   The disturbance was reported shortly after 5 p.m., and appeared
to involve most of the 330 inmates. By 11:30 p.m., fewer than 100
inmates remained in the yard.
   ``We will not take any steps. We will let them sit in the yard
and wait,'' Jim Eyskens, a federal Bureau of Prisons officer based
in San Antonio, said of those inmates. ``I'm certain this will be
resolved without force.''
   Roy Burnes, the owner of the detention center, denied that
inmates burned mattresses. ``Nothing was burned,'' Burnes told The
Associated Press. He then said he didn't have time to talk and hung
up.
   Some civilian employees who had locked themselves inside were
escorted out.
   A prison official who refused to identify herself said no one
was in immediate danger.
   A fire in December caused more than $1 million in damage to the
prison. The detention center closed for 35 days afterward until a
new 60,000-square-foot addition could be built.
   Before the fire, the prison held 200 prisoners. The addition was
designed to hold 365 inmates, but the number of inmates was not
immediately known.
   Most of the prisoners the government has contracted with the
facility to hold are illegal aliens who are serving sentences of 18
months or fewer for federal crimes, said Greg Bogdan, a spokesman
for the Federal Bureau of Prisons in Washington.
   The 203 prisoners at the detention center at the time of the
fire had to be transferred to other centers in Texas. The section
destroyed by fire is being renovated and, when it is completed, the
prison will hold 500.
   In July 1987, prisoners at the facility signed a letter
complaining of violations of civil rights, Bureau of Prison
standards and sanitation. Prisoners said in the letter that they
were offered real meat only once a week. They later complained of a
lack of recreation facilities.
   A federal prison inspector recommended improvements in prison
employee training.
   Burnes later in 1987 said he planned to change the prison
population makeup from illegal aliens to white-collar, short-term
federal prisoners.
</TEXT>
