<FIRST>u a AM-McCoyExecution 3rdLd-Writethru a0453 05-24 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McCoy Execution, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0453, a0452, a0742,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Texas Inmate Executed for 1981 Abduction-Rape Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: combines pvs; includes brief description in death chamber in
3rd and 4th grafs; Note contents of 8th graf, `According to ...'; SUBS
next-to-last graf to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted murderer was executed by
injection early Wednesday for the 1981 slaying of a woman who was
abducted and raped after her car broke down on a freeway.
   Stephen McCoy, whose final appeal was rejected by the U.S.
Supreme Court late Tuesday, was executed at 12:25 a.m. at the state
Department of Corrections' Walls Unit here.
   He gave no final statement. He coughed five times after the
injection was made about 12:15 a.m. and groaned twice.
   His brother-in-law, two friends and his attorney, Karen Zellars,
were among the witnesses.
   The nation's highest court denied him a stay by a 5-4 vote
without comment.
   The 40-year-old Houston electrician was the 31st Texas convict
and the 110th in the nation executed since the 1976 U.S. Supreme
Court ruling allowing states to resume capital punishment.
   McCoy was convicted in the slaying of Cynthia Johnson, 18, who
was abducted as she was returning home from a New Year's Eve party
on Jan. 1, 1981.
   According to trial testimony, McCoy and two other men abducted
the woman. McCoy raped her, then held her legs down while James
Paster and Gary LeBlanc strangled her with an electrical cord.
   Paster then drove a nail up the woman's nose to make certain she
was dead, said the man who prosecuted the case.
   ``The death penalty was made for people like Stephen Albert
McCoy to protect society from people like him and from people like
James Paster,'' said prosecutor George Lambright. ``It was the
cold-bloodedness of the acts.''
   McCoy insisted he was in another room when the woman was slain.
   ``I knew what was going on,'' he said in a death row interview.
``I just couldn't do anything about it.''
   Paster, awaiting death for another slaying, received a life
sentence for the Johnson killing. Last month, he was caught with
another death row inmate in an unsuccessful escape attempt.
   LeBlanc, who testified for the state, received a 35-year prison
sentence.
   McCoy was in prison serving five years for burglary when he was
charged with the Johnson slaying. McCoy, Paster and LeBlanc also
were linked to a 1980 murder-for-hire in Houston and the rape and
stabbing of a woman.
   Attorneys for McCoy raised nine issues in their appeal,
including objections to jury selection, McCoy's competence to stand
trial and ineffective legal assistance. There also was no evidence
presented at his trial to show McCoy was a continued threat to
society, according to Zellars.
   State attorneys called the appeal arguments frivolous.
</TEXT>
