<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Photographers     05-24 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Photographers,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Thanks Photographers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, himself an avid picture-taker,
jokes that the press photographers who cover him helped get him
good publicity during the first part of his administration by
focusing on the family dogs.
   Bush personally presented the annual awards of the White House
News Photographers' Association Tuesday.
   The president told the black-tie dinner attended by more than
1,000 persons, ``Actually, I dropped in to see if my prints were
ready.''
   ``It's no secret that I am a great fan of White House
photographers. After all, those first 100 days were saved by those
puppy pictures,'' said Bush, referring to the puppies produced by
Millie, the family dog.
   The association selected Bruce Dale of National Geographic as
still photographer of the year and Steven C. Affens of WJLA-TV in
Washington as cameraman of the year. Affens has won that honor four
times in a row.
   The photographers gave Bush a framed copy of the Life Magazine
that ran 10 of his Polaroid shots of friends seated on the bed in
the Lincoln Room, and a new Polaroid camera so he can shoot away in
the Oval Office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
