<FIRST>r w PM-HHS-Fulton     05-24 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HHS-Fulton,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Pressured to Drop Appointment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pressure is building on Health and Human
Services Secretary Louis Sullivan to abandon his support for an
Oklahoma state official whom conservative, pro-life advocates
oppose for a top job in the department.
   But Sullivan continues to support Robert Fulton to head the
Family Services Administration at HHS, which manages the
government's major welfare programs, a spokesman for the secretary
said.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, suggested Tuesday that the secretary
stop pushing the White House to nominate Fulton, who is under fire
for his handling of the deaths of two dozen babies with the
crippling deformity spina bifida. The incidents occurred at an
Oklahoma state hospital while he headed the state's human services
department.
   Hatch said that while he is still looking into the allegations
against Fulton, ``I think there's lots of indication he might want
to put this in abeyance and back off.''
   ``I think it's going to be a cause celebre if he (Sullivan)
continues with it,'' Hatch said. ``I'm not sure he needs to get in
the middle of a great big fight over it right now.''
   Sullivan has run afoul of right-to-life advocates before with
comments that appeared to support abortion rights. To mollify his
critics, he agreed to recommend for nomination to several top jobs
at the agency people acceptable to pro-life groups.
   The welfare job was not among the jobs mentioned at the time and
its duties do not have much to do with abortion. However, a group
of conservative Republican senators say Fulton's actions in the
spina bifida matter show him to be too insensitive to the
right-to-life views.
   Fulton, who is now Oklahoma secretary of social services, is
criticized for failing to act promptly to end the Oklahoma state
hospital policy of withholding life-saving care from spina bifida
babies.
   Fulton says that shortly after he became director of the state
human services department, he learned of the policy and put into
effect regulations and policies designed to assure such denial of
treatment would not recurr.
   But critics say the protections he instituted were required by
federal law and they note that the doctors involved were never
sanctioned.
   Fulton and Sullivan met with half a dozen senators on Capitol
Hill earlier this month to try to allay their concerns. However,
following the meeting, Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., and five other
senators signed a letter to President Bush expressing their
continued opposition to Fulton.
   Hatch was not among them, but he said the spina bifida
allegations ``disturb me'' and need further review, as do new
concerns that are being raised.
   Among the new charges is one that Fulton lobbied against
requirements in a bill in Congress last year that required welfare
recipients to work for their benefits. That requirement is part of
the new welfare reform law HHS must put into effect.
   Fulton said the provision he lobbied for on behalf of his boss,
Oklahoma Gov. Henry Bellmon, is similar to the provision that
appeared in the final version of the bill and is now law. ``I've
been a supporter of workfare for a long, long time,'' he said.
   Hatch also said he is looking into a lawsuit filed against
Fulton for a policy he established as human services director that
allegedly discriminated against women. The case was referred by the
state Supreme Court to the State Merit Protection Commission, where
it is pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
