<DOCNO> AP890524-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0340EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TritiumMoratorium     05-24 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tritium Moratorium,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prominent Scientists Oppose Administration Plan to Produce Tritium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prominent scientists are blasting as wasteful
and premature a Bush administration plan to expand production of a
key material for nuclear warheads.
   Carson Mark, a former designer of atomic weapons, and George
Rathjens, a former chief scientist in the Defense Advanced Research
Projects Agency, told Congress on Tuesday that the United States
has more than enough tritium to sustain its nuclear arsenal for
several years.
   Tritium is a radioactive gas used to boost the explosive power
of nuclear warheads.
   The two scientists were testifying before a special House panel
investigating the nation's tritium needs and the administration's
plans for modernizing its weapons facilities.
   Senior officials from the Pentagon and the State Department also
testified publicly, and intelligence agency officials later
appeared before the panel in a closed session.
   The only three U.S. reactors capable of producing tritium,
located at the Savannah River Site in South Carolina, have been
shut down for safety reasons since last spring. The administration
has cited an urgent need to get them running by early next year.
   President Bush also has endorsed a plan developed by the Reagan
administration to build by 1998 two new tritium-producing reactors,
one at Savannah River and the other in Idaho, at a cost of
approximately $7.5 billion.
   Both Rathjens and Mark said it's not necessary to rush a restart
of the Savannah River reactors, which have been plagued by
structural and operator problems in recent years. The pair also
advised postponing the decision on whether to spend the huge sums
needed to build the two new-generation reactors.
   ``Until well into the next century, I don't believe we need to
worry about production'' of tritium, Rathjens said. ``We're not
balancing on a knife's edge.''
   Rathjens suggested the administration propose to the Soviet
Union a mutual moratorium on tritium production as a means of
advancing arms control. To forge ahead with construction of two new
tritium-producing reactors would ``send the wrong signal'' to the
Soviets and U.S. allies about American interest in disarmament, he
said.
   A new construction plan might lead the Soviets to think ``we are
contemplating at least a doubling of our weapons stockpile'' or
planning to produce a large number of neutron weapons, which
require more tritium per weapon, Rathjens said.
   He and Mark support House and Senate bills introduced last week
that call on the administration to negotiate a U.S.-Soviet ban on
the production of plutonium, also needed to make nuclear warheads.
The administration opposes the bills.
   ``We need to have those Savannah River reactors restarted as
soon as we can,'' Robert Barker, the defense secretary's top
adviser on atomic energy, told the panel. He submitted a written
statement, dated April 26, that said, ``We are near the point where
this tritium will be exhausted'' unless production is resumed.
   U.S. supplies of both weapons-grade plutonium and tritium are
classified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
