<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     05-24 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Sharply Higher Against Yen, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended sharply higher against the
Japanese yen Wednesday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange reversed an earlier downward trend in the afternoon and
inched up.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
251.25 points the previous day, slightly rebounded to gain 35.21
points, or 0.10 percent, and finish the day's trading at 33,851.82
points.
   The dollar closed at 143.00 yen, up 1.05 yen from Tuesday's
close of 141.95 yen. The currency started trading at 143.15 yen and
moved between 142.45 yen and 143.70 yen.
   The dollar's strength continued in Tokyo following a similar
dollar-buying trend Tuesday in New York, where comments by Federal
Reserve Board Governor Robert Heller ignited the currency's
uptrend. The U.S. currency ended trading at 142.33 yen in New York.
   Heller, speaking at the National Economists Club, said
``inflation is not dead. You don't want to declare victory too
early.''
   The Fed should ``proceed in a prudednt fashion'' to continue to
observe inflation trends before making a monetary policy shift, he
said.
   Minori Takeuchi, a dealer with Chemical Bank in Tokyo, said the
Bank of Japan intervened in the market, selling the dollar
intermittently in the morning session, but the amount it sold was
unknown. The central bank does not comment on its monetary
activities.
   ``The dollar's surge never stops unless the United States shows
us its monetary policy because the market's demand for the dollar
is still so strong,'' she said.
   On the stock exchange, trading was thin mainly due to the yen's
weakness against the dollar and uncertainties over the possible
discount rate hike, said a dealer with Nomura Securities, Japan's
largest brokerage.
   ``The majority of market players think a 0.5 percent hike would
not be effective to stabilize the markets,'' he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Market sources have expected the central bank to raise its
official discount rate by at least 0.5 percent from its current 2.5
percent. Neither the bank nor the Finance Ministry has officially
commented on a rate hike.
   The dollar's recent surge and speculation for a substantial
discount rate increase have already discouraged investors'
stock-buying interest, the dealer added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
