<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0414EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos     05-24 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Call Marcos' Survival Surprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos'
condition is not improving and his doctors say it's a miracle he's
still alive.
   ``He's the sickest I've ever seen him,'' Dr. Steven Berman, an
infectious disease specialist, told a news conference Tuesday.
   Doctors said Marcos is dependent on life-support equipment and
the prospects for his survival are slim. Marcos is unable to
breathe on his own and is undergoing constant kidney dialysis, they
said.
   ``He would die if he was off the ventilator. He would die if he
wasn't going to get dialysis. He would probably die if his cardiac
medicines were removed,'' Berman said. ``This is a multi-factoral
problem.''
   The 71-year-old Marcos, who has been hospitalized at St. Francis
Medical Center since Jan. 15, is suffering from massive bacterial
infection, kidney failure, cardiac failure, pulmonary failure and
pneumonia, the doctors said.
   ``It's a miracle he's survived so far,'' said Dr. Calvin Wong,
Marcos' cardiologist.
   Marcos' condition has been unstable and very critical since he
suffered kidney failure and underwent a surgical procedure Thursday
to prepare his veins for extended kidney dialysis.
   Dr. Roland Ng, a kidney specialist, said a kidney transplanted
into Marcos in 1984 stopped functioning because of the infection.
   Marcos has been on a respirator for three months.
   Transplant surgeon Dr. Livingston Wong would not specify how
long Marcos might live, but said it probably would not be long.
   ``I think if you asked any one of us we'd all say he has a low
probability of long-term survival,'' Livingston Wong said.
   Marcos' fever was 101 degrees Tuesday, but had climbed as high
as 104 degrees during the past few days, Berman said.
   Although the prognosis for Marcos remained poor, the doctors
would not rule out the possibility of recovery.
   The former leader's illness has prevented him from traveling to
New York City to face racketeering charges alleging he plundered
his homeland of more than $100 million and used the money to buy
real estate and art in the United States.
   His wife, Imelda, who also is charged, last week appealed to
Philippine President Corazon Aquino to allow her husband to die in
his homeland. The request was denied.
   The Marcoses have lived in Hawaii since February 1986, when they
were ousted in a civilian-military revolt that brought Mrs. Aquino
to power.
</TEXT>
