<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0451EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TexasExecution     05-24 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Execution,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmate Executed for Rape-Slaying of Woman Abducted From Stranded
Auto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents of 8th graf, `Testimony also ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was executed by injection early
today for helping to rape and strangle a woman who was abducted as
she awaited help in her disabled car following a New Year's Eve
party in 1981.
   Stephen McCoy gave no final tatement, although he smiled briefly
to four friends he had invited as witnesses. He coughed and his
chest heaved five times as the drugs began to take effect, then
uttered two low and long groans before he stopped breathing at
12:25 a.m.
   The 40-year-old Houston electrician was the 31st Texas convict
and the 110th in the nation executed since the 1976 U.S. Supreme
Court ruling allowing states to resume capital punishment.
   McCoy lost a final appeal late Tuesday when the court voted 5-4
against a stay. The action, which came without comment, was unusual
since the appeal was McCoy's first to reach the high court. It has
been routine for initial appeals to merit at least one reprieve.
   ``The significance of this is the courts very clearly are
indicating impatience with dilatory tactics within the process and
they intend to expedite the process,'' said state Attorney General
Jim Mattox.
   McCoy was convicted in the murder of Cynthia Johnson. The
18-year-old Conroe woman was abducted by McCoy and two other men
from her car, which had broke down on a Houston freeway as she was
returning home from a New Year's Eve party.
   According to trial testimony, McCoy raped the woman and then
held her legs down while James Paster and Gary LeBlanc strangled
her with an electrical cord. Testimony also showed Paster hammered
a nail up the woman's nostril to make certain she was dead.
   Miss Johnson would have turned 27 on Monday.
   Paster, awaiting death for another slaying, received a life
sentence for the Johnson murder. Last month, he was caught with
another death-row inmate in an unsuccessful escape attempt.
LeBlanc, who testified for the state, received a 35-year term.
   ``The death penalty was made for people like Stephen Albert
McCoy to protect society from people like him and from people like
James Paster,'' said George Lambright, who prosecuted the case.
   ``There was no remorse, no drugs, no alcohol, no real
explanation for the violence except they were just mean,'' Mattox
said.
   McCoy had insisted he was in another room when the woman was
slain.
   ``I knew what was going on,'' he said in an interview last week.
``I just couldn't do anything about it. ...
   ``I'm right with the man upstairs. I know this. He knows I'm
innocent. It's not that that bothers me about dying. It's to die
for something I didn't do and to look like a sicko doing it.
   ``Sometimes you make the wrong decisions. That's just the way it
goes. I'm happy with myself, happy with the Lord. I'm at peace with
myself. I know I didn't do it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0501EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Riot     05-24 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Riot,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youths Riot, Attack Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOLVERHAMPTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 youths hurled gasoline
bombs at police in a racially mixed district of the central England
town of Wolverhampton following a drug raid in a tavern, police
said.
   The rioters Tuesday night also threw up a makeshift barricade
across a street, looted at least one store and set a local council
office on fire, said Deputy Chief Constable Paul Leopold of the
West Midlands police.
   In 1985, predominantly black and racially mixed areas of British
towns and cities including Wolverhampton were swept by a wave of
protests of police harassment. In the worst incident, a policeman
was hacked to death in the Tottenham district of north London.
   Social workers said the underlying cause of those riots included
high unemployment among young people, especially young blacks, and
poor housing in inner-city areas.
   Leopold told a news conference that the trouble began in Tuesday
night when police raiding the pub made 20 arrests, 12 for drug
offenses, and seized marijuana and crack cocaine.
   He said 250 officers _ members of the police drug squad and a
police support unit _ were attacked by the mob.
   The officers dispersed the mob in about two hours, he said.
   ``The conduct of these youths reacting to legitimate police
action in making a serious drugs raid is totally reprehensible and
inexcusable,'' Leopold said.
   In February 1987, 13 people were arrested, shops were looted and
windows smashed in rioting in the area following the death of a
local black man.
   The black man had collapsed after a struggle with two policemen
who were called to a shop when a clerk became suspicious that the
credit card the man was carrying might have been stolen.
   An inquest returned a verdict of accidental death.
   Last year, parcel bombs were mailed to two senior police
officers and to a former police official. Police said the bombs
were believed to be the work of a group calling itself the Black
Liberation Front.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
