<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-24 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Climbs Against Yen in Tokyo, Stocks Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar climbed further against the yen today,
while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index erased early losses and
finished slightly higher.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at 33,851.82, up 35.21
points, or 0.1 percent, from Tuesday, when it lost 251.25 points.
   The Nikkei lost another 34.12 points this morning, but then
investors reacted positively to the yen's apparent stabilizing
against the dollar, said Yoshio Shimoyama, a dealer with Nikko
Securities.
   But most market players stayed on the sidelines because of
lingering uncertainties over the currency market, a possible
central bank discount rate increase and Japan's political
situation, Shimoyama said.
   Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 650
million shares, down from Tuesday's 700 million.
   The dollar closed at 143 yen, up 1.05 yen from Tuesday's
141.95-yen finish. The dollar, at a 19-month high, now has gained
8.56 yen since May 11.
   It opened today at 143.15 yen and fluctuated between 142.45 yen
and 143.70 yen.
   The dollar's strong opening in Tokyo followed its rise in New
York overnight, triggered by comments by the U.S. Federal Reserve
Board's Robert Heller, traders said.
   Heller told the National Economists Club that ``inflation is not
dead. You don't want to declare victory too early.''
   Masafumi Koyama of the Bank of Tokyo said, ``Japanese investors
concertedly bought the dollar early in the morning. ... But the
dollar slipped (later) as some market players sold it for
profit-taking and position adjustments.''
   The Bank of Japan sold dollars intermittently in efforts to
check the dollar's rise, but it was not central bank intervention
that led the currency lower toward the end of trading, he said. The
central bank does not comment on its activities on exchange markets.
   ``Investors kept buying and selling the dollar as the rate
moved, trying not to keep much money in their hands,'' Koyama added.
   ``Still, the market has a strong demand for the U.S. money,'' he
said.
   Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama told the House of
Representatives today that credit policy should be considered on
the basis of various indicators, but declined to comment on an
expected increase of the official discount rate, Kyodo News Service
reported.
</TEXT>
