<FIRST>u i PM-China-Provinces 1stLd-Writethru a0450 05-24 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Provinces, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Government Demonstrations Spread Throughout Nation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 18th graf, `Demonstrations have...' to UPDATE with other
cities reporting demonstrations; Picks up 19th graf, `Official newspapers...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students and workers demanding democratic reform
are taking to the streets throughout China, from dusty Lanzhou in
the west to Harbin in the distant northeast.
   While the world focuses its attention on the student uprising in
Beijing, the upheaval is rapidly spreading in areas of the country
beyond the international eye and not normally associated with
political activism.
   Sources contacted at several provincial capitals say workers are
supporting the student demonstrations and sit-ins. They say the
rallies demand Premier Li Peng's resignation for declaring martial
law in Beijing.
   In China's largest city, Shanghai, up to 500,000 people have
paralyzed traffic in marches to the waterfront business district
and the People's Square.
   About 100,000 marched Tuesday night in the southern city of
Canton, a business center normally known for its lack of interest
in political matters.
   In Canton and the inland city of Changsha, people set off
firecrackers and cheered when they learned of a Hong Kong radio
broadcast that claimed Li had been forced out. The report not be
immediately confirmed.
   John Lowry, a teacher from Cincinnati, said 100,000 people were
on the streets in Changsha Tuesday night. He said sit-ins have been
going on continually in front of the railroad station and the party
and government headquarters.
   Residents are bringing the students hot food and medicine, he
said by telephone. ``Support from the workers is really quite
amazing.''
   Among the many people marching in support of the students was a
group of 20 blind people, Lowry said.
   In the Yellow River city of Lanzhou, people placed wreaths on a
central square for a woman student who reportedly died during a
hunger strike. An American source said students were going to
factories to talk to workers about their cause and workers were
leaving their jobs to meet them.
   All major universities in China's northeastern cities of Harbin,
Shenyang, Changchun and Dalian have been shut down by strikes, said
a Western source in the area.
   ``There's an atmosphere of tension which we didn't have a week
ago,'' the source said on condition of anonymity. ``Everyone is
sitting very, very tight'' waiting to hear what will happen in
Beijing.
   Class boycotts also continued in Nanjing, and at least 20,000
people have been on that city's streets every night since martial
law was declared in Beijing on May 20, an American there said.
   She said that since the government began jamming
Chinese-language broadcasts of the Voice of America on Sunday,
students frequently try to glean information from foreigners about
activities in Beijing.
   In Shenyang, handouts of the latest VOA reports are pasted on
walls, and students in Changsha said VOA and the British
Broadcasting Corp. are the only reliable sources of news.
   Sources said students have streamed back and forth to Beijing to
keep their colleagues in the provinces abreast of what students in
the capital are doing.
   In Shenyang, however, authorities have stopped selling train
tickets to Beijing to halt the flow of student supporters.
   Demonstrations have also been reported in Xian, Shenzhen,
Suzhou, Tianjin, Hefei, Guiyang, Urumqi, Hainan, Hangzhou, Hohhot
and dozens of other cities. In Ningbo, students broke into the city
government compound, and in Wuhan students last week stopped all
traffic on a bridge crossing the Yangtze River.
   Official newspapers in Beijing say little about disturbances
outside Beijing, Shanghai and a few other cities, but it appears
certain that few places have escaped the student-led upheaval.
</TEXT>
