<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceStandoff     05-24 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Standoff,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Die in Fiery End to Standoff</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Dennerll cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers who kept police at bay for seven
hours burned to death in a blaze apparently started by the
firebombs they were tossing at officers, authorities said.
   Autopsies showed John Limoli, 63, and his 62-year-old brother,
David, died of smoke inhalation, said Cuyahoga County Coroner
Elizabeth K. Balraj.
   There was no other evidence of injuries to the men, Ms. Balraj
said.
   The trouble began Monday night when neighbor Wayne Ramsdell
called police to report that John Limoli had threatened him.
   Mike Mills, 24, who lives with Ramsdell, said: ``The guy was
just flipping out. One second he was talking about the Jews getting
killed in World War II; one second he was asking if Wayne was a
Democrat or a Republican; and then he kept going on about the Bible
and God.''
   Several shots were fired from the house at police officers, but
no injuries were reported among police and officers did not return
the fire, a police spokesman said.
   ``Members of our SWAT team tried talking to John, but got no
response,'' police spokesman Lt. Al Jezior said. ``But we saw a
person we perceived to be John throwing makeshift firebombs out of
several windows, and also inside the house.''
   One of the bombs apparently ignited the house, authorities said.
   ``The fire was started by liquid that he had filled up in
bottles,'' said police Sgt. Roger Dennerll. ``He had approximately
six of them that he threw out the windows of the house.''
   According to Dennerll, some of the firebombs apparently bounced
off windows back into the house.
   Special Weapons and Tactics team officers later fired tear gas
into the house but were unable to drive the men out.
   A neighbor, Valerie Rice, said the two men complained frequently
and weren't well liked by neighbors.
   ``The most I knew about them really was they weren't easy to get
along with. They were lousy neighbors,'' Ms. Rice said. ``They
complained about a lot of different things about the neighborhood.''
   Neighbor Carolyn Hendrock said John Limoli had been upset for
three weeks because a neighbor had complained about a garage the
brothers had built. The neighbor had wanted the land surveyed, she
said.
</TEXT>
