<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GottiTrial     05-24 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gotti Trial,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reputed Mobster's Brother, Associate, Guilty in Drug Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother of reputed mob boss John Gotti was
convicted of managing a multimillion-dollar heroin ring, ending a
six-year legal battle that included two mistrials.
   The jury returned its verdict against Gene Gotti on Tuesday
night, seven days after deliberations began and about three hours
after a federal judge dismissed a holdout juror who said he feared
for his family's safety.
   Gotti and co-defendant John Carneglia showed no emotion as the
jury pronounced them guilty of racketeering, possession with intent
to distribute heroin and conspiracy with intent to distribute
heroin.
   Carneglia also was convicted of an interstate travel violation.
Both men face up to 50 years in prison.
   Jurors were polled and then asked by U.S. District Judge John
Bartels whether anything the dismissed juror told them affected
their verdict, or whether the dismissal itself affected their
decision. All answered no.
   Bartels allowed the two to remain free on $1 million bonds
pending a full bail hearing June 20. No sentencing date was set.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert LaRusso said he was happy with
the verdict.
   ``The evidence was clear,'' he said. ``It was a matter of
putting the pieces together.''
   Ronald Fischetti, Gotti's attorney, said he was confident the
verdict would be reversed on appeal.
   The verdicts came three hours after Bartels dismissed the juror.
The juror, referred to only as juror No. 9, told the judge he was
scared by a visit last week from two men who asked if he was on the
Gotti jury.
   The juror said there were no explicit or implied threats from
the men. Bartels dismissed the juror and told the remaining 11 to
resume deliberations.
   When they came back 15 minutes later with a verdict, the judge
sent them back, saying, ``I don't think that you have had enough
time to deliberate without juror No. 9. I ask you to lay aside what
you might have heard from juror No. 9.''
   The jury earlier had sent a note to the judge saying all but
juror No. 9 had reached informal agreement on a verdict.
   Juror No. 9 was an alternate until just before deliberations
started, replacing one who was dismissed last Wednesday after it
was revealed that he lived in the same neighborhood as an FBI agent
assigned to the case.
   At the first trial, prosecutors alleged jury tampering by some
of the defendants, prompting an unusual proceeding involving nine
federal judges and ultimately a mistrial in January 1988.
   The second trial was declared a mistrial in July after a juror
was dismissed when cocaine was found in clothing brought to him
during deliberations and the 11 remaining jurors announced they
were hopelessly deadlocked.
   The third trial was reassigned to Bartels, who at 91 is one of
the oldest federal judges.
   The defense requested a mistrial this time after it was revealed
that one of the jurors was the cousin of a federal prosecutor who
worked at the courthouse. A second request involved accusations in
the news media that Bartels had fallen asleep during the
prosecutor's opening statements.
   Bartels rejected all mistrial motions.
   The case stems from a 1983 indictment.
   John Gotti is reputedly the boss of the Gambino organization,
the nation's most powerful Mafia family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
