<FIRST>r a PM-Fire-Crafts     05-24 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fire-Crafts,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Destroys Princeton Home With Collection of Crafts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 pieces of woodwork and
furniture made by craftsman George Nakashima were destroyed in a
house fire, authorities said.
   ``Everything's gone, a total loss,'' said Fire Chief Mark Freda.
`The house and everything in it was destroyed.''
   Nakashima, 83, is considered by many to be the elder statesman
of American crafts. Only two pieces of the collection, owned by Dr.
Arthur and Evelyn Krosnick, survived, The New York Times reported
today. A picture frame and a boardroom table were on loan for an
exhibit of Nakashima's work at the American Craft Museum in New
York.
   The blaze began Tuesday morning when an acetylene torch being
used by a plumber caught fire, said Township Police Lt. Mario Musso.
   He said the plumber set the torch on the floor and went to find
something to extinguish the fire. While he was gone, flames
engulfed the basement and spread to the rest of the house.
   Freda said damages to the home and the contents amounted to
about $1 million, but added ``estimates at this point are very
unreliable. No one I've talked to really knows what the contents
were worth.''
   Mrs. Krosnick and her housekeeper escaped without injury,
officials said. The plumber was treated at a hospital for minor
burns to his hands and hair and released.
   ``It is a great loss _ for them and for us,'' Nakashima said
from his studio in New Hope, Pa. ``Some of the pieces can be
replaced, but many cannot. They are precise pieces _ one of a kind,
many of them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
