<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SirhanParole     05-24 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sirhan Parole,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robert Kennedy's Assassin Denied Parole 10th Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOLEDAD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Robert F. Kennedy's assassin, Sirhan
B. Sirhan, has an unpredictable capacity for violence and remains a
threat to society, a state prison board ruled in denying him parole
for the 10th time.
   Sirhan, 45, who is serving a life sentence for the 1968 shooting
of the Democratic presidential candidate, is not eligible for
parole again until next year.
   Board chairman David Brown on Tuesday called the shooting ``one
of the most shocking criminal assassinations in the history of the
United States.''
   It was ``an attack not merely on an individual's life but on the
political life of the country,'' he said.
   In his arguments to the panel, Sirhan apologized for the
slaying, said he was no longer a threat to society and that he
hasn't given up hope for freedom.
   ``I feel very sad, very sorry, very remorseful ... that a human
life was taken,'' the Jordanian-born Sirhan said. ``After 21 years
... I have become quite convinced that my act was very wrong,
morally and humanly, toward Robert Kennedy, and especially toward
his family and his loved ones and his supporters.''
   ``I realize the mistake of it and I wish from the bottom of my
heart ... that this crime, this horrible event, never occurred,''
he said.
   After the board turned him down, Sirhan accused it of prejudice,
saying the three panelists used ``specious'' arguments.
   The board told Sirhan it wanted him to complete a psychiatric
evaluation program he began in March.
   The board also rejected claims by Sirhan and his attorney, Luke
McKissack, that it was not impartial because its members had been
involved in a previous hearing at which they deliberated only three
minutes. This time the panel deliberated nearly an hour.
   Sirhan argued that he has done everything officials have asked
of him, has been a model prisoner, but is serving more time than
most prisoners with first-degree murder convictions.
   Sirhan's older brother, Adel, watched the hearing along with
reporters via closed circuit television at the State Correctional
Training Facility in this small community 180 miles south of San
Francisco.
   ``We were hoping for more lenient consideration this time,'' he
said glumly. ``Hopefully, next time will be better.''
   Kennedy, a U.S. senator from New York, was shot with a
.22-caliber pistol as he walked through the kitchen of the
Ambassador Hotel in Los Angeles after winning the California
presidential primary.
   Sirhan, a Christian Arab, was sentenced to death for Kennedy's
murder but was spared from gas chamber after California's death
penalty law was overturned in 1972.
   His sentence was changed to life in prison with possibility of
parole, and Sirhan faced his first parole hearing in 1975.
   For the past six years, Sirhan has been in a maximum-security
section at the Soledad prison. His release has been blocked
repeatedly by parole panels that have cited reasons ranging from
the effect the crime had on the U.S. political system to Sirhan's
potential for future violence.
   Sirhan last came before the board two years ago. At that time,
the panel recommended that he undergo extensive psychiatric
evaluation, pursue vocational training, attend Alcoholics Anonymous
sessions, remain free of disciplinary problems, earn an associate's
degree and provide documentation of job offers.
   Sirhan told the panel he was not a man of violence. He blamed
the shooting on a volatile mixture of politics, youth, and alcohol.
   ``A lot of people don't realize Robert Kennedy was my hero,''
Sirhan said. He said he turned against Kennedy because of his
support of the sale of 50 fighter jets to Israel, then drank too
much, got a gun and shot him.
   Sirhan said he doesn't hate any politicians now and isn't a
threat to supporters of Israel. He said he understands Jews better
now because, like the victims of Adolf Hitler, ``I've been exposed
to gas chambers.''
</TEXT>
