<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern-Pilots     05-24 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Pilots,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Graduates Pilots; Union Attacks Training</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines has graduated its first class of
new pilots since the carrier's crippling strike began March 4.
   Attorneys for Eastern's pilots union, however, told U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in New York City that the pilot training raised
serious safety issues.
   ``Our pilot training is going very smoothly,'' company spokesman
Robin Matell said in Miami. ``This is a very heavily experienced
group.''
   Two new pilots are already flying and about 20 more completed
training this week, Matell said. Eastern said 452 new pilots have
begun training during the past two months, joining nearly 250
Eastern pilots who are crossing picket lines.
   Also Tuesday, Eastern gave American West Airlines until 5 p.m.
today to line up financing for its proposed $415 million purchase
of Eastern's lucrative Boston-New York-Washington shuttle.
   Under a rebuilding plan submitted to federal bankruptcy court,
Eastern says it needs about 1,700 pilots to return to about
two-thirds of its prestrike operations. Eastern has been flying
about 10 percent of its prestrike schedule of nearly 1,100 daily
flights that used 3,600 pilots.
   Eastern, which filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection and
reorganization on March 9, says it can rebuild a smaller,
profitable carrier without its unions and after selling $1.8
billion in assets.
   Eastern unions want the parent Texas Air Corp. to sell the
airline. Attorneys for the pilots union, which has joined the
flight attendants in honoring the striking Machinists union picket
lines, filed a detailed attack Tuesday on Eastern's rebuilding plan.
   The airline can't possibly train enough new pilots to meet its
rebuilding goals, the union said.
   ``The training of these new pilots also raises certain serious
safety issues regarding the lack of experience among the pilot
crew,'' the union said.
   Union spokesman Hank Weber said the Eastern training has been
marred by a high dropout and failure rate, that training has taken
longer than usual, that Eastern is using instructors from sister
airline Continental and that training has been chaotic.
   Matell said the failure and dropout rate has been running at
normal levels.
   The first group of graduates averages 5,782 hours of flying
experience, compared with the prestrike average of 4,000 hours for
recruits, Matell said. The average age of the recruits is 38.3
years, with most coming from corporate duty or commuter airlines.
   During a brief hearing Tuesday in bankruptcy court, Eastern said
it would consider American West Airlines' offer for the shuttle
withdrawn if it could not meet today's deadline. Eastern already
has agreed to a $365 million offer for the shuttle from developer
Donald Trump.
   If America West arranges the financing, Judge Burton R. Lifland
must determine whether it is satisfactory before both offers for
the shuttle are considered further. Lifland must approve any sale
of Eastern assets.
</TEXT>
