<SECOND>PM-Miss Universe,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newly Crowned Dutchwoman Hopes New-Found Fame Will Be Enduring</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CAN1, LaserColor CAN8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Miss Universe, Angela Visser of
the Netherlands, says she hopes her stay in the limelight will
stretch beyond her one-year reign.
   Miss Visser, 22, a beautician from Rotterdam, today said she
plans to use the title to advance a modeling career.
   ``The most important thing is for people to remember me after
this year is over,'' she told The Associated Press in a telephone
interview after she was chosen Tuesday night from among 76
contestants.
   Miss Universe 1988, Porntip Nakhirunkanok of Bangkok, Thailand,
presented the crown to the winner after swimsuit and evening gown
competitions and personal interviews.
   First runner-up was Miss Sweden, Louise Drerenstam, 19; second
runner-up, Miss U.S.A., Gretchen Polhemus, 24, of Fort Worth,
Texas; third runner-up, Miss Poland, Joanna Gapinsak, 21, and
fourth runner-up, Miss Mexico, Ardiana Abascal, 18.
   The other five finalists were: Miss Chile, Macarena Mina, 20;
Miss Venezuela, Lisa Ljung, 18; Miss Germany, Andrea Stelzer, 24;
Miss Jamaica, Sandra Foster, 19, and Miss Finland, Aasa Maria
Loewdahl, 20.
   Miss Visser, who wore a white gown with silver sequins, was
considered one of the top contenders at the competition, held at
the Fiesta Americana Condesa Hotel. She speaks five languages and
has studied piano and classical ballet.
   She says she enjoys writing poetry, listening to classical music
and playing tennis.
   Miss Visser has blond hair, green eyes and is 5-foot-9. She
aspires to a television or film career.
   She wins $300,000 in prizes and will spend the next year
traveling around the world.
   On Thursday, she is to travel to Mexico City to meet President
Carlos Salinas de Gortari. The next day, she moves into an
apartment in Los Angeles, where she will live during her one-year
reign.
   Miss U.S.A., Gretchen Polhemus, will be her roommate.
   ``Oh, it's great, you'll love it,'' Miss Polhemus reportedly
told her. ``I'll take you shopping.''
   Asked about the reaction of her parents, who attended the event,
Miss Visser said, ``We didn't cry. We just sat and talked about
normal things.''
   Hosts of the event included John Forsythe and Emma Samms of the
``Dynasty'' television program. It was beamed by satellite to more
than 60 countries and an estimated 600 million viewers.
   Rehearsals and taping began two weeks earlier in this Yucatan
resort.
</TEXT>
