<FIRST>r a PM-RadnerInterview     05-24 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Radner Interview,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gilda Praised Husband for His Support</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Gilda Radner said in an interview weeks
before her death that husband Gene Wilder always believed she would
be well and never displayed fear of the ovarian cancer that killed
her.
   ``I'm lucky I'm with a man who isn't superficial,'' she said in
the interview in June's Glamour magazine.
   ``I think he was really put to the test. But he loves and cares
about what's inside me _ who I am, rather than if I have hair.''
   She said in the March 31 interview she told Wilder, ``You have
handled this about the best that anyone could. After I finish this
every woman in the world will be after you. The trouble is, they're
all gonna have some major illness.''
   She said Wilder never broke down and cried or seemed afraid that
she might not recover.
   ``He's always had this total confidence that I would be well.
I've never seen any fear in his eyes. And I would be the first one
to pick up on it. Now he says back in the early days that he did
feel fear. You know what? He may just be a great actor!''
   Wilder ``always treated me normally. If he was mad at me, he was
mad at me. I don't think I could have stood it if anybody had
treated me as fragile or as though I had a limited time on earth,''
Radner said.
   Radner died Saturday.
   A book about her illness, ``It's Always Something,'' will soon
be published.
</TEXT>
