<FIRST>r a PM-Lewis'Degree     05-24 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lewis' Degree,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman to Get Honorary Degree from School That Once Turned Him
Away</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMILY BENTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Georgia congressman is to receive an honorary
degree from an Alabama college that he says turned him away 31
years ago because of his race.
   Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., is a native of Troy, Ala., and in 1958,
he applied to what was then Troy State College. In a statement from
his Washington, D.C., office, Lewis said Tuesday that his
application to the college was denied because he is black.
   Troy State University plans to present Lewis with an honorary
doctorate of law degree at its commencement June 2.
   ``I have received several degrees in the past few years, but
this degree is very special because it comes from the university in
my hometown and the school I always wanted to attend,'' said Lewis,
who also has honorary degrees from Princeton and other colleges.
   Bill Buchannon, public relations director for Troy State, said
in a telephone interview Tuesday night that university officials
did not know about the school's rejection of Lewis when it voted in
March to give him an honorary doctorate of laws.
   ``They're awarding it to him for being a Pike County, Ala.,
native from a basically outlying area of this town, who obviously
has made good in his state and on the national level,'' Buchannon
said. ``For that reason, our board thought he was deserving.''
   The board's resolution commending Lewis lists some of the
congressman's accomplishments, including his role in civil-rights
organizations and his former position on the Atlanta City Council.
It also outlines his education, which includes a bachelor's degree
from Fisk University, where Lewis went after being turned down in
Troy.
   He said it was the school's refusal to accept him that led him
to Montgomery, Ala., and to the civil-rights movement.
   After Troy State rejected him, Lewis wrote Dr. Martin Luther
King Jr. in Montgomery, requesting help in getting into Troy State.
King replied with a bus ticket to Montgomery and an invitation to
come to talk about filing a lawsuit against the school.
   Soon after his talk with King, Lewis joined others pushing for
civil rights. Lewis decided not to sue Troy State and later went to
school in Nashville, Tenn., where he led sit-ins and demonstrations
calling for an end to racial discrimination.
   ``This honorary degree represents many of the advancements we
have made in the areas of education and civil rights in the past 30
years,'' Lewis said.
   Buchannon said he realizes the degree illustrates how far the
university and society have come in civil rights, but he emphasized
that the school chose to honor Lewis ``for his exemplar life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
