<SECOND>PM-Khomeini,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Says Khomeini Feeling Well, Cheerful</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Khomeini-Successor, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's parliament speaker, Hashemi
Rafsanjani, said today that Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini was well
and cheerful following surgery to stop intestinal bleeding, Tehran
radio reported.
   Rafsanjani said he visited Khomeini, 89, in the hospital today,
one day after the operation.
   ``He was in bed, and the doctors were around him. His health was
very good,'' he told the radio. ``He was very cheerful. I asked him
if he had any pain and he replied that he has very little and that
he is comfortable.''
   The radio was monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp. in
London.
   Khomeini's son, Ahmad, said Tuesday that his father was in
``very good condition'' after the surgery.
   Iranian television, monitored in Nicosia, later showed film of
Khomeini leaning on a stick, walking slowly into a Tehran hospital
accompanied by his son. It also showed Khomeini after surgery,
wrapped in a colorful shawl and rubbing a string of worry beads in
one hand, propped up on a hospital bed.
   Using Khomeini's title of Imam, or spiritual leader, his son
told Tehran radio: ``Some blood had been detected in the Imam's
digestive tract. The doctors and surgeons consulted among
themselves and concluded that the best course would be to operate.''
   Khomeini's previously unreported illness highlighted the
question of who will govern Iran after he dies.
   The revolutionary patriarch ousted his designated successor,
Ayatollah Hussein-Ali Montazeri, on March 28 for criticizing his
policies and appointed a 20-man constitutional committee.
   The committee's deliberations on changing the 1979 constitution
and clarifying the succession has taken place and amid factional
wrangling.
   Indications are that without any single figure with Khomeini's
combined spiritual and political authority, Iran will have a
collective leadership after he dies.
