<HEAD>Noriega Sends Gifts to Michigan Schoolgirl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEGAUNEE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old girl has become pen pals
with Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and is impressing her
schoolmates with letters and gifts from the embattled leader.
   Sarah York first wrote Noriega in March 1988, after seeing him
on television, saying she wanted to learn more about his country.
   After a correspondence, Noriega paid for Sarah and her mother,
Pauline, to visit in October. The girl said after the five-day trip
that she was writing then-President Reagan to say that Noriega ``is
a very good man.''
   Noriega, Panama's military chief and de-facto ruler, has been
accused of nullifying May 7 elections to prevent the defeat of his
handpicked candidate for the presidency. President Bush has sent
extra troops to Panama and is advocating Noriega's ouster.
   On Monday, Sarah received a package from the general containing
baseball caps and T-shirts bearing slogans in Spanish, copies of
three of his speeches and a desk calendar with a photo of the
twosome from Sarah's visit.
   It also included a handwritten note from Noriega that said:
``You are always in our thoughts. And we want to send greetings to
your parents and everybody at your school.''
   Sarah's classmates were impressed, she said, adding, ``They want
me to bring more stuff to show them.'
   Sarah was wearing one of the T-shirts on Tuesday at Negaunee
Middle School, where she is in the sixth grade.
   It said, in Spanish, ``Panamanian Youth Revolution and
Democracy.''
   Negaunee, with about 5,200 residents, is in Michigan's Upper
Peninsula, near Marquette.
