<FIRST>r a PM-Prison-PMS     05-24 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison-PMS,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premenstrual Syndrome Linked to Prison Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Harri is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premenstrual syndrome may contribute to
violence in women's prisons, and helping inmates cope with
depression, anxiety and other symptoms may prevent trouble, a
psychologist said.
   ``Prisons need to recognize if women suffer from PMS and train
people to teach about it,'' said Kate Harri, a Minneapolis
psychologist who specializes in PMS and has consulted with
prisoners.
   For unknown reasons, women who live together often begin to
menstruate at the same time each month, she told participants
Tuesday at the Third National Workshop on Female Offenders.
   ``Do you remember going to college, living in a dorm, cycling
with your roommate? Think about women in a prison,'' she said.
``Those women in a prison are going to cycle together.
   ``There are times when they have behavior disturbances. If you
have more than one woman who is premenstrual at one time, who has
PMS, then of course you're going to have behavior disturbances.''
   PMS is a hormonal condition in which a variety of symptoms
regularly occur in the same phase of the menstrual cycle, usually
the week before menstruation begins, and disappear, usually within
a few days.
   It can lead to mood swings and, in rare cases, acts of violence,
Harri said.
   Helping inmates deal with the disorder will speed
rehabilitation, she said.
   ``PMS is not a cause of criminal behavior, but it can be a
contributing factor to it'' she said. ``Some women become very
aggressive and out of control.''
   About 32,800 women were housed in state and federal prisons as
of December 1988, said Helen G. Corrothers, commissioner of the
U.S. Sentencing Commission.
   Millicent A. Pulkownik, a corrections officer at the State
Correctional Institute at Waynesburg, Pa., is one of about 500
people attending the four-day conference. She said she has noticed
many of the 200 women at the prison menstruate at about the same
time.
   ``You can just tell when everybody is going into cycle,'' she
said. ``There's a shortness of temper, a lower tolerance for
people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0074 </DOCNO>
