<SECOND>PM-BRF--Religious Death,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Science Couple Ordered to Stand Trial in Son's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christian Science couple must stand trial on
manslaughter charges for not seeking medical attention for their
dying son, the state Supreme Court ruled.
   David and Ginger Twitchell had argued that state abuse laws
protect spiritual healing, which Christian Scientists favor over
doctors and medicine.
   On Tuesday, Judge Herbert Wilkins ruled that the issue can be
dealt with by an appeals court only after a trial.
   The Twitchells' 2{-year-old son Robyn became feverish and
lethargic in 1986, according to police. They contacted a church
practitioner who came to their home to pray for his recovery. The
boy was pronounced dead at a hospital.
   The Twitchells' attorney has said the official cause of death
was complications from a bowel obstruction that stemmed from a
birth defect.
</TEXT>
