<HEAD>Customs Solves Manpower Shortage; Diverts 800 to Tampa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Customs Service delayed about 800
passengers for up to eight hours because it didn't have enough
inspectors in Orlando and had to divert their British Airways jet
to Tampa for processing.
   Customs officials refused to let the plane carrying 427 people
land at Orlando International Airport late Monday, saying the
agency can't afford to pay inspectors to work there after 10 p.m.
   An additional 386 passengers who expected to leave Orlando late
Monday aboard the same plane for Britain were stranded at the
airport until Tuesday morning.
   The decision to send the plane land to Tampa infuriated Orlando
airport officials, who are trying to boost its reputation for
international service.
   ``We had 800 unhappy campers waiting,'' said Bruce Boudreau, the
airport's deputy executive director. ``And we had an unhappy
airport staff.''
   After the jet landed in Tampa, passengers were processed and put
back on the plane for the 80-mile trip to Orlando.
