<SECOND>PM-Convention Resignation,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embattled Convention Head Resigns in Flap Over Remarks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the city's convention bureau has quit
under fire for making derogatory remarks about blacks and Hispanics.
   Don Vaughn on Tuesday resigned his $145,000-a-year job as
president and chief executive officer of the Greater Houston
Convention &amp; Visitors Bureau.
   ``I think it's in the best interest of Houston in order to move
forward both on the local and state level,'' he said, ``and I
believe that any further divisiveness in the community would not be
helpful to Houston and the convention industry.''
   He had been under fire from Mayor Kathy Whitmire and minority
groups, including the NAACP, since he told a state representative
last month that he didn't want black and Hispanic council members
reviewing his annual budget because they would not understand it.
   Vaughn has since apologized to local members of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   His remarks led the NAACP to threaten to take its lucrative
national convention elsewhere in two years unless the bureau makes
changes to help minorities.
   NAACP officials at its Baltimore headquarters and local
officials did not return calls for comment on Vaughn's resignation.
   The NAACP convention in 1991 is expected to attract 10,000
people and generate $6.8 million for the local economy, the bureau
said. Delegates are expected to occupy 3,000 hotel rooms during the
six-day convention.
   Vaughn's remarks about minorities came while he and Rep. Steve
Wolens were discussing a bill by Wolens that would give city and
county governments more scrutiny over convention bureau budgets.
</TEXT>
