<FIRST>u i PM-France-Nazi 4thLd-Writethru a0532 05-24 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Nazi, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0532,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head Of French Pro-Nazi Militia Arrested at Priory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to update with report that Touvier caught
at Lefevbre priory; Pickup 8th pvs, ``President Georges...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Frenchman accused of committing crimes against
humanity as head of a pro-Nazi militia during World War II was
arrested today in southern France, police said.
   Paul Touvier, 74, was captured at a priory near Nice.
   The French news agency Agence France-Presse said he was arrested
at St. Francis Priory, which is run by followers of Monsignor
Marcel Lefevbre, a fundamentalist priest. Lefevbre was
excommunicated from the Roman Catholic Church last year after a
long battle with the Vatican over church doctrine.
   There had been persistent reports extreme-right Roman Catholics
were protecting Touvier.
   In Nice, police said Touvier was being questioned, but they
refused to provide further information.
   ``We see this with great satisfaction,'' Beate Klarsfeld,
France's best-known Nazi hunter, said of the arrest. ``It's a great
bravo for French justice.''
   In 1945 and 1947, Touvier was sentenced to death in absentia on
convictions of collaborating with the Nazis and executing and
torturing members of the resistance.
   Touvier was the Lyon head of the Milice, which worked closely
with the Gestapo during the Nazi occupation. At the time, the
Gestapo was headed in Lyon by Klaus Barbie, who in 1987 was
sentenced to life in prison for crimes against humanity.
   Touvier was not caught, and the sentences against him could not
be carried out because of a 20-year statute of limitations.
   President Georges Pompidou quietly pardoned Touvier in 1971,
restoring his rights as a citizen.
   Touvier went into hiding two years later when new charges were
raised. Charges of crimes against humanity were filed against him
in 1981, and an international arrest warrant issued.
   The new warrant lists six charges, including the slaying of
Victor Basch, the 81-year-old president of France's League for
Human Rights, who had taken refuge in the Lyon area.
   Investigators determined that when Basch and his wife were
arrested by Touvier's Milice in January 1944, they were ``judged
too old to be deported and they were killed on the spot.''
   Magazines and newspapers have published extensive accounts of
Touvier's protection by the Catholic hierarchy until 1967.
   The address on his official identity card was the archbishop's
headquarters in Lyon, and church officials reportedly lobbied for
the 1971 pardon.
   Since Touvier's return to hiding, there have been reports that
he came under the protection of fundamentalist Catholics with
extreme-right political views.
   Historian Henri Amouroux, a specialist on France's wartime
collaboration, said Touvier's trial would bring out ``the role the
church played in the protection he was accorded.''
   In an odd twist, a death notice for Touvier was published in a
Grenoble newspaper in 1984, giving thanks in the name of his family
for expressions of sympathy. It was never explained, and there were
frequent reports afterward that Touvier was seen in monasteries in
France, Italy or Switzerland.
   Touvier's brother Andre, 61, said in an interview that he was
surprised by news of the arrest, because he had been ``99 percent''
convinced his brother had died.
   ``In a certain sense, his arrest is a good thing. The inquiry
will show, even if he is not lily white, that people have
exaggerated and made a mythic figure out of him,'' Andre Touvier
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
