<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0930EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Exports     05-24 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Exports,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Investigating Alleged Illegal Exports to East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are investigating a Japanese machinery
company that may have illegally exported to East Germany rare
materials for use in nuclear reactor rods, officials said today.
   The Tokyo-based Prometron Technics allegedly exported an
unspecified amount of hafnium to East Germany in 1986 and 1987
without clearance from the Japanese government, a police official
said on condition of anonymity.
   Executives of the company, which has a branch office in East
Berlin, allegedly carried the metallic chemical element in their
luggage when they traveled to the East bloc country, the official
said.
   Prometron Technics maintains technology swaps with East
Germany's Electrotechnic Export and Import Corporation and several
other East German companys, he said.
   Hafnium is principally used to make control rods for reactors on
nuclear-powered vessels and submarines. It is among a list of items
strictly regulated by the Coordinating Committee on Multilateral
Export Control, a Paris-based watchdog body that controls trade in
strategic items with the communist bloc.
   Police on May 9 searched the offices of Prometron Technics and
the home of the company president, Hirokuni Matsuda, the official
said.
   He said an investigation into whether the firm violated customs
laws and foreign exchange and control laws is still under way.
Violators face up to five years in prison.
   The case is the tenth involving Japanese firms accused of
violating the watchdog agency rules since 1985.
   In 1987, Toshiba Machine Co., a subsidiary of electronics giant
Toshiba Corp., sold sophisticated propeller milling equipment to
the Soviet Union in 1986 in violation of committee rules.
   U.S. officials charged the equipment helped the Soviets
manufacture quieter submarines, and thus undermined Western
security. The incident prompted the U.S. government to prohibit
Toshiba Machine exports to the United States for three years
beginning in 1988.
</TEXT>
