<FIRST>r a PM-LostCostumes     05-24 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lost Costumes,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bolshoi Dancers Vow To Go On _ Even Without Costumes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stars of the Bolshoi Ballet say the show must
go on even if they have to pirouette in hand-me-downs after their
luggage got lost.
   Ten crates of costumes and props that were supposed to arrive
ahead of the 30 Bolshoi dancers who are opening in Chicago on
Thursday disappeared in New York during transit, and the company is
having to make do with borrowed goods.
   A high-level diplomatic search continues for the baggage, sent
nine days ahead of time on Aeroflot, the Soviet Union's state-run
airline.
   ``We know the flight took off from Moscow, and we know it landed
in the United States,'' said Susan Arons, a spokeswoman for
Classical Artists International, which is sponsoring ``The Stars of
the Bolshoi Ballet'' tour.
   ``But we have no idea where the crates are,'' she said.
   A second shipment of ballet essentials has been sent from the
Soviet Union and is expected to arrive Friday night or Saturday,
Ms. Arons said.
   In the meantime, the dancers will borrow from the Ballet
Chicago, the Ruth Page Foundation and the Milwaukee Ballet, which
is sending its entire production of ``Giselle'' to Chicago by bus.
   ``It's like if the White Sox went out onto the field in Cubs,
Brewer and Indians uniforms,'' Ms. Arons said Tuesday.
   The borrowed costumes have meant extra rehearsals for fittings
and practicing of precision moves.
   ``The greatest problem is the toe shoes,'' said prima ballerina
Natalya Bessmertnova, speaking through an interpreter. ``We are
used to our shoes, and they are special shoes. Russian toe shoes
are different. Every dancer has a master who makes the shoes by
hand to fit perfectly to the foot.''
   ``Maybe some of us will have to dance in the costumes first and
then we will all have to switch, but we'll make the best of it,''
Ms. Bessmertnova said. ``We have already cried. Now we have to
laugh.''
   The dancers are scheduled to give four performances at Chicago's
Civic Opera House. Besides ``Giselle,'' the program includes
excerpts from other classical pieces such as ``Swan Lake'' and
``Sleeping Beauty.''
</TEXT>
