<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 0952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-GermanAnniversary     05-24 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-German Anniversary,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Extols Virtues, Shortcomings of West German State</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Two Germanys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Richard von Weizsaecker
today extolled the virtues of his nation on its 40th birthday,
praising the spirit that has made West Germany a world economic
power but warning against ``self-satisfaction.''
   At a celebration to observe West Germany's founding, Weizsaecker
said Germans, through their suffering and successes of the postwar
period, had earned the right to enjoy prosperity.
   He declared his nation's allegience to the West, twice praising
the United States for its help in rebuilding the West German state
from the ashes of the Third Reich.
   His clear embrace of the NATO alliance appeared to be a signal
to the increasingly left-leaning populace that notions of a neutral
German state are ill-advised and could jeopardize peace and
stability built over the past four decades.
   West Germany is embroiled in a dispute with the United States
and Britain over the fate of short-range nuclear missiles, and the
argument has strained relations among the traditionally close
allies.
   ``Under the conditions of the Cold War, it was easy to be
united,'' Weizsaecker told his audience at Bonn's Beethoven Hall.
``It becomes more uncomfortable when the world no longer gives
clear information on who is for us and who is against us.''
   Weizsaecker praised Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev for the
``breathtaking'' process of change he has introduced in his
country, but he tempered the accolades with a warning that no one
is sure of the Kremlin leader's future.
   He paid tribute to West German economic prowess but said West
Germans have much work ahead of them.
   ``The economy is blooming, science has won back its prominence
and education has become an example for the world,'' said the
69-year-old president, re-elected Tuesday to a second five-year
term.
   ``Yet we have no ground for self-satisfaction,'' Weizsaecker
said. ``We have not become angels under the Basic Law.''
   The Basic Law, adopted May 23, 1949, serves as the
constitutional foundation of West Germany and has won praise for
guiding the defeated nation from ruin to international respect.
   West Germany is the world's largest exporter and enjoys one of
the highest standards of living and a strong social security net.
   But Weizsaecker suggested West Germany's way of life is
threatened by resistance to social change.
   In particular, he decried the lot of German women, who bear the
brunt of a system that has been slow to develop day care or
flexible work scheduling, despite the fact that about two-thirds of
the nation's women work outside the home.
   ``As never before must the family make way for the work market,
instead of the other way around. This is regretted by all. And the
women bear the lion's share of the burden,'' the president said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
