<SECOND>PM-Arab Summit, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0539,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Summit Takes on Lebanon Issue After Welcoming Back Egypt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Lebanese conflict threatening
to delay summit closure. Pickup 9th pvs, Gadhafi sat ...;</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASABLANCA, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya threatened to walk out of an
Arab League summit today if any moves were made toward concessions
to Israel, but the Lebanese crisis proved the most divisive issue
for Arab leaders.
   Syrian leader Hafez Assad, rather than Libyan leader Moammar
Gadhafi, threatened to delay the closure of the extraordinary
summit, which was convened Tuesday mainly to welcome Egypt back
into Arab ranks after a 10-year ostracism. Assad today continued to
press his support for Lebanon's Moslem leader, acting Prime
Minister Salim Hoss, while Syria's strongest challenger in the Arab
world _ Iraq and its President Saddam Hussein _ outspokenly backed
Lebanon's Christian Maronite Gen. Michel Aoun.
   While the conflict is undecided, the summit remains closed to
the rival Lebanese delegations for the first time in Arab League
history.
   The leaders met behind closed doors Tuesday and today but failed
to resolve the issue. The summit was scheduled to close later
today, but Moroccan officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the dispute might force a delay until Thursday.
   King Hassan II of Morocco invited some of the quarreling leaders
to a private meeting in his palace late Tuesday. Several had not
met for years, and Hassan persuaded some of them to shake hands,
conference sources said. Those shaking hands included Gadhafi and
Palestine Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat, Assad and
Saddam Hussein, and everyone with Egyptian leader Hosni Mubarak,
the sources said.
   Mubarak moved quickly to reassert Egypt's traditional domination
of the Arab world when he reoccupied Egypt's seat in the league for
the first time since 1979. That was the year Cairo was suspended
for signing its peace treaty with Israel.
   ``Lebanon has become a grave problem,'' the leader of the Arab
world's most populous state said at the opening session. ``It
exhausts us and is exhausting our consciences. We must work
together to overcome this crisis before the fire overcomes us all.''
   Gadhafi sat silently during Mubarak's 20-minute address, taking
notes.
   Morocco's national news agency MAP and Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported Gadhafi and Mubarak met privately Tuesday night
with Presidents Hafez Assad of Syria and Chadli Bendjedid of
Algeria, in what MAP described as a warm session of reconciliation.
   The Egyptian agency quoted its Information Minister Safwat
Sherif as saying the leaders openly discussed differences of
opinion and a ``spirit of understanding'' prevailed.
   Liby'a news agency JANA has warned Gadhafi would walk out if any
attempt were made to surrender to Israel by compromising on the
Arab demand for Palestinian statehood.
   No such surrender has been discussed.
   In his speech Tuesday, Mubarak asked the league to back the
efforts of its six-nation committee on Lebanon to restore Lebanese
national unity and end the civil war that is in its 15th year.
   In particular, Mubarak said, the committee should seek
withdrawal of all foreign forces from Lebanon _ meaning both
Syrians and Israelis _ and help the country live peacefully under
its ``constitutional authority.''
   Mubarak gave Egypt's full backing to the Palestinian uprising in
the Israeli-occupied territories and backed the right of the
Palestinian people ``to choose whatever road they find suitable for
the achievement of their aspirations.''
   He also spoke of ``the great financial burden'' of the uprising
on the Palestinian people, echoing the PLO complaint that Arab
states have not lived up to their promise of financial aid.
   PLO spokesmen said only Saudi Arabia and Libya have paid
anything.
</TEXT>
