<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0524 05-24 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0524,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Accuses Government Of Violating Historic Accords</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with students calling off strike,
backing Solidarity. Pickup 2nd pvs, ``Just hours ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa today
accused communist authorities of breaking a promise made in
historic accords by refusing to legalize the country's independent
student union.
   Angry students, meanwhile, called off a sit-in at Warsaw
University they had called to protest the rejection.
   They said the government refusal was a futile attempt to divide
students from Solidarity just before June 4 parliamentary
elections, and they promised to redouble campaign efforts for the
independent union's Parliament slate.
   Just hours after a Warsaw court refused Tuesday to register the
Independent Students' Association, the government struck a further
blow by banning a scheduled broadcast of Solidarity's election show
from state television.
   Registration of the student union, known as NZS, and opposition
access to television were both agreed to by Communist authorities
in the broad ``round-table'' agreements reached April 5 with the
Solidarity-led opposition.
   ``The rejection of the registration of NZS breaks the
round-table decisions,'' Walesa said in a statement released by the
Solidarity Citizens' Committee.
   The court said it rejected the student group's registration
application because NZS did not renounce the right to stage student
strikes.
   The government press office said it had no immediate response to
Walesa's charge and referred inquiries to state television and to a
court spokesman. Spokesmen at both institutions said no one was
available to comment.
   Walesa's statement included no reference to the cancellation of
the TV show but he promised that his free trade union movement
would pursue the issue of NZS with authorities.
   ``Solidarity will not abandon the matter of NZS registration,''
Walesa said. ``Solidarity will give NZS access to its offices and
to other means until it is registered.''
   Solidarity-endorsed senators and deputies to parliament also
will raise the matter after they are elected, Walesa pledged.
   Announcement of the television ban on the Solidarity program
came just as the show was to go on the air Tuesday night.
   An announcer read an official communique that said authorities
had blocked the show ``because the contents ... aim against the
round-table agreements.''
   The main thrust of the agreements was that Solidarity would be
reinstated after a seven-year ban if the opposition agreed to take
part in Poland's first democratic elections since World War II.
   Tuesday's 45-minute broadcast would have been the third such
Solidarity-produced TV show.
   Today's editions of the opposition daily newspaper Gazeta
Wyborcza said the program was to have included a discussion on the
law led by opposition journalist Wanda Falkowska as well as
interviews with Solidarity candidates for the two-chamber
legislature.
   The government communique said that state TV management, which
is headed by former government spokesman Jerzy Urban, had decided
to refer the program to an arbitration committee that includes
Solidarity activists.
   The committee, co-chaired by Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and
Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, was set up to handle
disputes that arise in the implementation of the accords.
   ``The opposition presents many programs on radio and television
containing aggressive and bitter remarks,'' the communique said.
``There are however limits which may not be crossed, as they would
erase the constructive achievements attained at the round-table
...''
   At the round-table, the opposition agreed to take part in
``non-confrontational'' elections to the current unicameral
parliament, or Sejm, and a newly created Senate that is to be the
first freely elected legislative chamber in the East bloc.
   Only 35 percent of the Sejm is open to opposition candidates.
The remaining 65 percent is reserved for the ruling Communists and
their allies.
   The banning of the program was the lead item in today's editions
of Gazeta Wyborcza, while official newspapers did report on it.
   A Solidarity-produced radio broadcast was shortened May 17
because a censor barred a segment of it. And Gazeta Wyborcza, which
has just begun publishing, has come under sharp attack in the
Communist Party daily Trybuna Ludu.
</TEXT>
