<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Politics 1stLd-Writethru   05-24 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0538,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Won't Dictate to New Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with hope for free congress, quotes; Changes
byline; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reformers said today they are hopeful the new
parliament will be truly independent because the Communist Party
called a Kremlin meeting of its deputies and did not issue orders
on what policies to pursue.
   The Congress of People's Deputies, which opens Thursday, is the
country's first legislature chosen in contested elections in seven
decades.
   The decision of the Communist Party _ the only political power
in the 70 years _ not to dictate policy at a Tuesday gathering
offered hope for democratic decision-making, Moscow deputy Yuri
Andreyev said.
   ``This is very important,'' Andreyev said. ``There are no
decisions required of all the deputies.''
   About 80 percent of the congress' deputies are members of the
Communist Party, but party leaders cannot count on automatic
support among Moscow radicals or from the Baltic republics, which
want freedom from Kremlin control.
   Andreyev said the spirited discussion Tuesday indicated the
congress itself will be ``open and active.''
   ``We were surprised that so many deputies from Russia were so
free in expressing their opinions,'' said Marju Lauristen, a deputy
from the Baltic republic of Estonia.
   Party ideology chief Vadim Medvedev added to hopes, saying on
national television late Tuesday: ``I don't think we should limit
any discussions. We just have to live through them.''
   Today, hundreds of legislators met in strategy sessions to
hastily garner support for proposals to solve the political and
economic problems facing the Soviet Union. For the first time, they
must please the voters who chose 1,750 of the congress' 2,250
deputies. The remainder were appointed by official organizations.
   The formal duties of the congress are to meet annually, choose a
president and 542-member Supreme Soviet legislature, and approve
the president's recommendations for premier, head of the Supreme
Court and national prosecutor.
   But cooperatives want to repeal a decree that kicked them out of
profitable businesses, Armenians want a solution to ethnic problems
and Baltic leaders want economic independence.
   A group of Moscow reformers, including figures as diverse as
human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov and populist party
official Boris N. Yeltsin, will propose congress consider economic
and political reform. And Sakharov has gone as far as saying it
ought to replace the smaller Supreme Soviet as the legislative body.
   A poll reported in today's Moscow News said 89 percent of 1,100
city dwellers nationwide believed the congress should discuss the
economic, social and political situation in the country.
   ``The people expect very much _ unfortunately,'' said Yuri
Shcherbak, a Kiev deputy known for his writings on the Chernobyl
nuclear power plant disaster. ``The people expect us to be able to
solve everything immediately.''
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda today quoted a resident of
south-central Kemerovo as saying he hoped to ``make our life, our
country such that you can once again say without blushing,`I am a
citizen of the Soviet Union.'''
   The party's Central Committee on Monday proposed Gorbachev for
president, and little opposition is expected. However, a battle may
develop because reformers want Gorbachev to make a report on the
state of the Soviet Union before they vote for president.
   The official schedule gives the congress just two morning
sessions before the Supreme Soviet convenes on Saturday. The party
has planned for election of the president and Supreme Soviet as the
first order of business, followed by discussions.
   But the progressives are demanding discussions first, and then
elections. ``We have to pick the Supreme Soviet deputies after we
have seen in the discussions who is who,'' said Andreyev.
   Otherwise, he said, the congress will be no better than the old
rubber-stamp legislature, where officials blathered while deputies
wandered off to the caviar-and-sturgeon buffet and unanimously
approved legislation studied for all of 20 minutes.
   Few negative votes were cast in the previous 1,500-member
Surpeme Soviet that the new body is replacing. Reformers, speaking
to TV interviewers late Tuesday, said the party should not be
afraid of dissent.
   ``If there is democracy, then these factions are inescapable,''
historian Roy Medvedev said.
   Medvedev, a specialist on the repression of the Stalin era,
could not be published for years. But he has gained acceptance in
the freer atmosphere of Gorbachev's reforms and won a parliamentary
seat from Moscow.
   Writer Daniel Granin, another reformer, added the ``customary
unity of opinion is extraordinarily dangerous. We have lost a lot
because of it.''
</TEXT>
