<HEAD>Theater Seat Occupied By Oswald Donated To Exhibit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The movie theater seat Lee Harvey Oswald was in
when he was arrested has been donated to an exhibit at the old
Texas School Book Depository.
   The chair, spray-painted black to underscore its place in
history, was removed from the Texas Theater last week and given to
The Sixth Floor, an exhibit on the assassination of President John
F. Kennedy.
   Theater manager Maxine Burroughs said the theater owners are
considering other ways to mark the spot where Oswald sat only
moments after he shot to death police Officer J.D. Tippit six
blocks away.
   Oswald was arrested during a showing of ``War Is Hell'' 80
minutes after shooting Kennedy from the sixth floor of the book
depository on Nov. 22, 1963.
   The seat might be put on display, said Conover Hunt, director of
the assassination exhibit.
