<SECOND>PM-New Zealand-American,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arrested Man Claims to be Missing American in Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said today they arrested a
man claiming to be an American whose disappearance four years ago
led to allegations he faked his death to collect $2.8 million in
life insurance.
   The man, in custody in Auckland on shoplifting charges, claims
he is Milton Windsor Harris of Baton Rouge, La., police said. The
43-year-old man was charged under the name William Travis. Police
said he also used the alias Rodoleho Jose Mancano of Chile.
   The Auckland Star newspaper today quoted police spokesman Tony
Bouchier as saying the man's claim to be Harris was supported by
fingerprints and photographs sent from the United States.
   Harris, who used to fill vending machines with candy and earned
less than $10,000 a year, supposedly fell overboard while on a
ferry in New Zealand's Cook Strait in 1985.
   Lloyds of London insurers refused to pay $2.8 million in
insurance policies Harris took out in the 18 months before he
vanished.
   A witness said he saw Harris fall from the ferry. But Lloyds
produced witnesses who said they had seen Harris after his alleged
death, and it contended the insurance policies were an elaborate
fraud scheme.
   The mystery man faces three charges of theft and escaping from
custody following his arrest on Monday. He was scheduled to appear
in court June 7.
   Police would not comment on possible extradition. The insurance
case is still pending.
