<FIRST>r a PM-NEC-Nintendo 1stLd-Writethru a0562 05-24 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NEC-Nintendo, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0562,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Company to Challenge Nintendo in U.S. Video Game Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `The Times ...' to FIX typo in newspaper's
name.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese company says it has come up with a
new home video game that offers more color and sharper graphics
than Nintendo _ at about twice the price.
   NEC Home Electronics, a U.S. subsidiary of Japanese computer and
telecommunications giant NEC, announced Tuesday it would begin
selling the new video game system in the fall.
   The new game ``allows us to provide the user over 10 times more
color and 16 times bigger characters,'' said Keith Schaefer, senior
vice president of NEC Home Electronics.
   ``You will be able to see them cry, you can see the eye
movement, the muscle movement,'' he said. ``In the baseball games,
you will be able to see dirt on the players' uniforms when they
slide.''
   The new game will sell for about $200.
   Nintendo, which offers computerized video games played on
regular TV sets, holds about 75 percent of the $3.5 billion U.S.
market for such games.
   The New York Times today said the key to the NEC system is a
16-bit graphics processor that provides clearer and more detailed
images than those generated by Nintendo's smaller processor. The
system also will have an optional compact disk player attachment
that produces stereo sound.
   Nintendo does not release the size of its processor, but it is
believed to be 8 bits, the Times said.
   Officials at Redmond, Wash.-based Nintendo said they were not
worried. Nintendo games, which emerged after 1985, are believed to
be in 17 percent of U.S. households.
   ``(NEC's) software is offering improved graphics, but it's not
offering another level of play and challenge to the player,'' said
William White, Nintendo director of advertising.
   Nintendo plans to offer a 16-bit machine in Japan this summer
and may introduce it in the United States as early as next year,
White said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
