<FIRST>r a PM-LongtimeFugitive 1stLd-Writethru a0499 05-24 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Longtime Fugitive, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0499,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Denies Pardon Request for Woman Who Spent 10 Years as Fugitive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `The Department ...' to CLARIFY that she
requested pardon investigation, the first step in obtaining a pardon.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH GROAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the state board that refused
to consider a pardon for an armed robber who built a family and
career during 10 years on the run says the woman can still hope for
parole.
   Kay Smith's attorney had argued that her release would send ``a
message of hope'' to people to trying to rehabilitate themselves.
   But board vice chairman Thomas Neal said Tuesday he felt the
state already provided ``mechanisms of hope, and the hope we
provide in this state is for parole.''
   The Department of Probation, Parole and Pardon Services rejected
Mrs. Smith's request for a pardon investigation by a 5-2 vote but
moved up her parole date from April 1990 to Dec. 15 because of the
work the 37-year-old woman has done in prison.
   If the investigation had been approved, the board would then
have considered actually granting a pardon.
   Mrs. Smith, who did not attend the hearing, had hoped to become
the first inmate other than a terminally ill one to be pardoned
since at least the 1940s, when the state Constitution was amended.
The governor has no power to grant pardons.
   In 1975, Mrs. Smith, then known as Pamela Rodgers, was convicted
in South Carolina on five counts of armed robbery and sentenced to
12 years in prison. She walked away from a work release program
three years later and hitchhiked to Maryland.
   Over the next 10{ years, she earned her high school diploma,
overcame drug and alcohol abuse, married Ray Smith, raised a foster
child and two sons and became a successful real estate agent.
   But Mrs. Smith's role as what others describe as a model citizen
ended last year when she was arrested as a fugitive. Her previous
husband, convicted of murder in Idaho, had tipped officials to her
whereabouts.
   Mrs. Smith was returned to South Carolina to finish her term and
serve an additional year for escape. Last fall, she was transferred
to the Women's Correctional Institution in Jessup, Md., so she
could be closer to home.
   Her husband, who drove all night from his Severn, Md., home to
attend the hearing, said afterward, ``It's going to be rougher now
than it was.''
   Overcome with emotion, he was unable to speak further.
</TEXT>
