<HEAD>U.S. Serviceman Indicted for Shooting Air Gun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean authorities today
indicted an American serviceman on charges he fired an air gun that
injured a Korean man, news reports said.
   Prosecutors in southern Chonju charged Sgt. John D. Wilson, 26,
of Henderson, N.C., with violating arms control laws and indulging
in violent acts, according to Yonhap, the South Korean news agency.
   Wilson, who is stationed in South Korea, was accused of firing
an air gun at Yun Chun-ho, 33, a farmer at Kunsan, a port city
about 130 miles south of Seoul, the agency said.
   Yun was slightly injured in the thigh when he tried to stop
Wilson from aiming the air gun at two passers-by. The Feb. 20
shooting occurred off base.
   If convicted, Wilson faces a maximum jail term of 10 years.
   Wilson was being held at Kunsan Air Base, pending the outcome of
investigations by U.S. and Korean authorities.
