<FIRST>r a PM-EvergladesFire     05-24 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Everglades Fire,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Burning In Heart Of Everglades National Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters from as far away as California today
battled a swift wildfire that has scorched more than 75,000 acres
in the Everglades.
   Smoke from the fire, centered in Everglades National Park about
30 miles from downtown Miami, caused a haze over much of the Miami
area.
   ``I believe the fire is moving at 1 mph, which doesn't sound
very fast, but for a fire it is,'' said duty officer Catherine
Migliano of the state Division of Forestry.
   More than 250 people, including ``hotshot'' teams of seasoned
firefighers from California, have joined the battle, officials said.
   A slight shift in wind lessened the danger to a Miccosukee
Indian village of about 500 people in the park, said park
information officer Pat Tolle.
   ``The distance to the village is still some 10 to 12 miles from
the fire line itself,'' she said.
   Tolle said lightning started the fire May 16.
   ``The area burning right now, in the center of the park, hasn't
burned at all in 30 years, so it has a very heavy fuel load and a
rapid rate of spread,'' she said.
</TEXT>
