<DOCNO> AP890524-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-NATO     05-24 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-NATO,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woerner Says Possible NATO Missile Compromise Emerging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner said today
a possible compromise is emerging in the alliance's dispute over
short-range nuclear missiles in Europe.
   Woerner said in a British Broadcasting Corp. radio interview
that he thought there was a greater than 50 percent chance of a
compromise being worked out before next week's NATO summit.
   The 16-member NATO summit, marking the 40th anniversary of the
founding of the alliance, opens in Brussels on Monday.
   The dispute involves West Germany's call for early negotiations
with the Soviet Union to reduce short-range nuclear missiles, which
have a range of less than 300 miles.
   The United States and Britain oppose such talks on the grounds
they could lead to pressure to eliminate short-range nuclear
missiles. They say the West needs nuclear arms in Europe to offset
a big East bloc advantage in conventional forces.
   President Bush said in an interview Tuesday with London's
Guardian and three other West European newspapers that he felt the
dispute might not be resolved before the summit.
   Woerner, interviewed from Brussels, was asked in the BBC
interview about a proposal, reportedly backed by the United States,
to link talks on short-range missiles to progress in talks on
conventional force reductions.
   Asked if he thought that was likely to emerge as a possible
compromise, Woerner said: ``Yes, that is really one of the crucial
questions _ which link do you establish between the conventional
arms control talks and the start of the negotiations on short-range
nuclear weapons?
   ``You can imagine several solutions. You just spelled out one of
the possible solutions. They are still working on that.''
   The BBC said this possible solution followed recent contacts
between Washington and Bonn. But it said there was already
opposition to it in West Germany, with some people fearing that the
conventional arms talks now being held in Vienna could drag on for
years.
   Woerner said he doubted this and maintained that the two sides
in the dispute were not so far apart.
   He said NATO could not afford a split at a historic moment when
so many changes are taking place in Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
