<FIRST>u w PM-JailedMother 2ndLd-Writethru a0529 05-24 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jailed Mother, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0529,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress is Drawn Into Child Custody Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 4th graf, Wolf made, with 2 grafs updating with court
proceeding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is slowly being drawn into a custody
battle so bitter that a prominent plastic surgeon has been in jail
for almost two years on contempt charges after refusing to turn
over her child for a court-ordered visit with dad.
   ``Every time I read about this case I see everyone wash his
hands of it,'' Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., said Tuesday in urging
passage of legislation that would free Dr. Elizabeth Morgan from
her District of Columbia jail cell.
   ``If we don't act now, who will? This has been stalemated for 21
months,'' Wolf told a House subcommittee with jurisdiction over the
nation's capital.
   Today, in the latest round of legal arguments in the 3-year-old
case, a city appeals court was urged to overturn a lower-court
judge's ruling that has kept the physician incarcerated since
August 1987.
   ``Dr. Morgan is confined unconstitutionally because her
incarceration will not serve a coercive function,'' Morgan's
attorney, Stephen Sachs, told a three-judge District of Columbia
Court of Appeals panel. ``There is no substantive likelihood that
she will relent (and reveal her daughter's location) _ not today,
not tomorrow, not ever.''
   Morgan accuses her former husband, oral surgeon Eric Foretich,
of sexually abusing their 6-year-old daughter Hilary. Morgan was
jailed on contempt charges for refusing to disclose where she hid
the girl rather than allow her near her father.
   Foretich vigorously denies ever molesting his daughter.
   In an attempt to break the legal deadlock, he offered during an
interview outside the committee hearing room Tuesday to submit to
interviews with social workers and psychiatrists who would
determine whether he was fit to be with Hilary.
   Congressional involvement and Foretich's renewed effort at
compromise are only the latest twists in the protracted dispute
over the child.
   Normally, the 11-member House District of Columbia Committee
concerns itself with the city's schools, budget and police
department, much like a city council in many American cities.
   But in this case, Wolf is trying to propel the panel, and the
entire Congress, into what amounts to a private quarrel between
parents.
   Wolf's bill seeks to limit imprisonment for civil contempt
charges to 18 months. After that, the district would be required to
either file criminal contempt charges against a person in Morgan's
position, thus guaranteeing a trial, or dismiss the case.
   The bill would be made retroactive for 18 months so as to apply
to Morgan.
   Similar laws limiting civil contempt jailings are in effect in
Wisconsin and California.
   ``In this case, coercion has clearly proven to be ineffective,''
Rep. Stan Parris, R-Va., said at the hearing. ``At what point do we
realize that this lady is really serious about this?'' D.C.
Superior Court Judge Herbert Dixon has said he's continuing to
imprison the woman in an effort to coerce her into revealing her
daughter's whereabouts.
   The city council has no authority over the city's court system.
However, council member James Nathanson told the House panel he
opposed setting a time limit for contempt jailings.
   ``If you put a cap on the court's authority, some people will
decide they're willing to pay that price,'' Nathanson said. ``I
think that a court would be rendered less effective.''
   Nathanson suggested instead establishing a three-judge panel to
review all civil contempt cases extending past 12 months. Under
Nathanson's plan the panel, which would include the judge who
initially jailed the person, would have to unanimously favor
continued incarceration to keep the person in prison.
   Foretich blasted Wolf's bill, saying it offered no guarantees
that Hilary would be produced even if Morgan were freed.
   ``Hilary is the one we should be concerned with,'' Foretich
said. ``I have great concerns about her safety.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
