<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   05-24 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: good one.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   May 22
   Daily News, Los Angeles, on the catastrophic illness plan for
the elderly:
   Woe to the elected representative who listens to the pros but
not the people. That's what quite a few members of Congress
apparently did last year when they passed a law setting up a new
plan for insuring the elderly against catastrophic illness. ...
   Now ... across the country, thousands of AARP (American
Association of Retired Persons) members are fighting mad at their
national leadership for supporting a requirement in the 1988 law
that all Medicare Part A recipients (those covered for in-patient
hospital care and other services) purchase catastrophic-care
coverage from the government.
   Glossed over during last year's health-insurance debate was that
virtually all federal retirees, and most private-sector retirees,
already have some form of private catastrophic coverage.
   Now, AARP members are particularly upset at being forced to pay
a wealth-based tax surcharge of up to $800 next year for the
long-term coverage, on top of premiums of $382.80 a year. ...
   Many members argue the legislation is also faulty because it
does not provide coverage for critical needs such as nursing home
stays, ... a benefit that many elderly people and their families
need most. ...
   It was a classic case of lawmakers lazily accepting the sales
pitches of six-figure Washington lobbyists and high-profile
spokesmen as gospel. ...
   Perhaps if Congress and others had done a little more of the
old-fashioned kind of research _ listening to their constituents _
it wouldn't be looking to revise or repeal the catastrophic care
law just a few months after it took effect.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 20
   The News and Courier, Charleston, S.C., on OAS and Noriega:
   Rarely has the Organization of American States been able to
muster the votes or summon the courage to condemn a Latin American
dictator.
   Usually, it weasels out of taking a stand by arguing that it
must not interfere in the affairs of member nations. It is almost
unprecedented for a dictator to be condemned by name.
   The value of the OAS resolution is the message that it sends to
Panama. It is a convincing counter to Gen. (Manuel Antonia)
Noriega's claim that all the charges made against him are part of
U.S. plot to oust him and annul the Panama Canal treaties.
   Although Gen. Noriega will insist that the OAS resolution was
dictated by Washington, officers of the Panamanian Defense Forces
who, perhaps alone, hold the key to his ouster, will have their
loyalty (better said, the depth of their complicity in corruption)
put to the test. ...
   The next step is the visit of an OAS delegation, formed by the
foreign ministers of Ecuador, Guatemala and Trinidad and Tobago,
which has been charged with working out an agreement ``through
democratic mechanisms'' to bring about ``a transfer of power in the
shortest possible time.'' The delegation must report back by June
5. Then the OAS must bite the nail.
   If Gen. Noriega thumbs his nose at the 19 Latin American
nations, as he has at the United States, then the OAS must act. We
will see then whether this much despised organization has the
courage as well as the votes to rid Panama of a despicable dictator
and an evil man.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 20
   Watertown (S.D.) Public Opinion on adding Reagan's likeness on
Rushmore: Every now and then somebody comes along with a screwball
idea that is so preposterous, so outrageous, that it takes on a
life of its own. ...
   Such a situation, we suspect, is what is developing around an
idea submitted for your consideration by one R. Emmett Tyrrell Jr.
... Tyrrell's idea is to add a likeness of Ronald Reagan on Mount
Rushmore.
   Tyrrell is editor-in-chief of American Spectator magazine, a
monthly conservative review. ...
   Now there may be some merit to Tyrrell's desire to honor Reagan
in some grand way.
   But we see one tiny, little problem with his proposal. What
happens if liberals come back to power? What happens if the
country, in the grips of a liberal revival, wants to honor some
recently retired chief executive by sandblasting Reagan's face off
the mountain and replacing it with a liberal?
   We have a better idea, why not pick an existing national
treasure that doesn't have a face of its own? ... Why not make a
giant bust of Reagan and hoist it atop the Washington Monument?
   And besides, if the liberals come back to power, it wouldn't
cost much money or take much time to replace the Reagan likeness
with another.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
