<FIRST>r a PM-KinseyInstitute     05-24 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kinsey Institute,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Review of Reinisch, Institute Put Off for Two Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indiana University has agreed not to
press for the ouster of the director of the Kinsey Institute on
human sexuality for two years.
   IU said in a statement Tuesday that the school and members of
the institute's board of trustees agreed not to investigate June
Reinisch during the cooling-off period. The university on Dec. 19
asked her to resign.
   The agreement will allow the institute on sexual behavior to
return to normal operations and attempt to resume its research,
said chancellor Kenneth Gros Louis.
   Reinisch was accused of heavy-handed management and failure to
produce the expected volume and quality of research. She has been
director more than six years.
   Reinisch has an unlisted home number and the institute was
closed today. She has denied any evidence existed to support
criticisms of her research or superviion.
   The university houses and partially funds the institute, which
was founded in 1947 by Alfred C. Kinsey. It is incorporated
separately from the university.
</TEXT>
