<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Drought     05-24 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Drought,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drought Kills $93 Million in Crops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last three months of a drought
killed about $93 million in spring crops, the government said
Wednesday.
   Agriculture Minister Abdul Munem told Parliament that 16 of 64
districts were hit by the drought that also claimed 150 lives.
   Munem said experts had estimated a spring harvest of 5.6 million
tons of rice and wheat, about one-fourth of the country's annual
needs of 18.5 million tons.
   The country produces 17 million tons of grain every year for its
110 million people and imports the rest. Bangladesh, one of the
world's poorest nations, has an annual per capita income of $160.
   Munem did not say how much crop was lost but experts had
predicted that more than half of the grain might be destroyed by
drought.
   Bangladesh alternates between dry and wet spells and last year
more than 1,400 people were killed in floods that inundated
three-fourths of the nation, the size of Wisconsin.
   Another 1,100 died in a cyclone in November. A tornado last
month killed 1,100 people.
</TEXT>
