<DOCNO> AP890524-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Raid 1stLd-Writethru a0504 05-24 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Raid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Raids Homes; Soldiers Shot At; Palestinians Sentenced.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with soldiers shot at in Bethlehem;
Palestinians jailed for riot. No Pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUSAN, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a pre-dawn raid today,
Israeli soldiers pounded on doors in this West Bank village and
took 24 Palestinian suspects away in blindfolds and handcuffs.
   ``We want to show the local citizens that we are in control,''
said 2nd Lt. Uziyah, 22, a red-bereted paratrooper.
   An American aid worker said soldiers kicked and slapped some
detainees.
   In the occupied West Bank, soldiers patrolling Bethlehem on foot
said they were shot at today, but no one was hit. It was the second
gun attack on Israeli forces in Bethlehem in two days.
   Meanwhile, a military court in Nablus jailed five Palestinians
in connection with a riot in which a Jewish guard accidently shot
and killed a 15-year-old Israeli girl.
   It was an emotional issue involving hikers from a Jewish
settlement, which first claimed the girl, Tirza Porat, was stoned
to death by villagers at Beita, on the West Bank.
   Israelis shot and killed two Palestinians during the April 6,
1988, incident, which began with villagers throwing stones at the
hikers.
   The defendants confessed and were convicted.
   Haled Hassin Abed Benishams, 19, was sentenced to four years'
jail for forcing the hikers into a violent situation and attempting
to stab the guard. His three companions were sentenced to terms of
18 months to two years for throwing stones and threatening the
hikers.
   In the Israeli town of Petah Tikvah, municipal officials said
they plan to build shacks for Arab laborers on the outskirts to
discourage them from entering the city.
   ``It's a catastrophe today. They are walking around everywhere.
They use the hallways as toilets,'' said city official Avi Lavi.
   Left-wing city councilor Avraham Oren said he has filed a police
complaint against Lev on grounds of racist incitement. ``The danger
is ... that this will create a wave of hatred,'' he said.
   The Petah Tikvah proposal is the latest in a series of
restrictions against Palestinian laborers in Israeli towns. Also in
past weeks, Israelis have begun stoning Arab workers, killing one
and injuring scores. The violence follows the killing of an Israeli
army sergeant blamed on Palestinians.
   Today's army raids were aimed partly at West Bank villages that
have declared themselves ``liberated'' Palestinian enclaves. More
than 30 have been raided since Sunday and scores of Palestinians
detained in the crackdown to arrest organizers of the uprising.
   ``We shake them up with such raids. ... They say `Hey, the
Israelis are here, and we can't do anything, not even throw a
stone,''' said Uziyah, whose full name could not be used under army
regulations.
   But he said he believes ony a political settlement will end the
17-month revolt against Israeli occupation that has claimed the
lives of 497 Palestinians and 22 Israelis.
   Lt. Col. Yehtiel, commander of operation in Husan, five miles
southwest of Jerusalem, said soldiers do not make indiscriminate
arrests and many of those sought are involved in blocking a nearby
highway or stoning Israeli motorists.
   Accompanied by several reporters, Uziyah's squad pounded on the
door of a single-story stone house. ``Open the door!'' he shouted
in Arabic as soldiers with automatic rifles flanked him.
   The house belonged to a man suspected of belonging to the Moslem
fundamentalist Islamic Jihad. No one was home. But soldiers went
into the house next door, belonging to the suspect's father, farmer
Jaber Taha Hussein.
   Hussein's wife screamed at soldiers who barged into her living
room and demanded identity cards from three of her sons. She
complained they already have arrested one.
   ``This is the third time you have searched this house. You are
besieging us!'' said the middle-aged woman.
   The soldiers left when they failed to find the man on their list.
   Twenty-four Palestinians arrested earlier were lined up in Husan
secondary school, blindfolded with hands bound behind their backs.
   On one wall, a large Israeli star of David emblem had been
painted with a swastika inside.
   Four Arabs were freed after questioning and the rest taken away
in a bus. None showed signs of beatings, and soldiers said they did
not use night sticks because the detainees did not resist arrest.
   In another pre-dawn raid today, however, aid worker Chris George
of Montclair, N.J., said he saw several people ``yelled at or
kicked.''
   George, 35, who works for Save the Children, was detained for
three hours with about 300 Palestinians after soldiers raided his
apartment overlooking Al Amari refugee camp.
   When he protested after a soldier kicked a young Palestinian
three times, ``I was told to shut up,'' he said. He said an elderly
man was slapped in the face and kicked in the back after he
complained of leg cramps.
</TEXT>
