<HEAD>Teen-Ager Says She and Lukens Took Part in a Sexual Threesome</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with teen-ager's testimony. No pickup. NOTE
contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who says she had sex with Rep.
Don Lukens testified today she appeared uninvited at his home with
a 19-year-old girlfriend and that the three of them climbed into
bed together.
   Rosie Coffman said she met Lukens in 1985 and did not see the
58-year-old Ohio Republican again until Nov. 6, when she and
Michelle Foster visited him.
   ``My friend Michelle gave me a call. She said she had met a
congressman. She called him by the name of `Buz,''' Ms. Coffman
said, referring to Lukens' nickname.
   Ms. Coffman said the two took a cab to Lukens' Columbus
apartment. Lukens met them at the door in boxer shorts and gave Ms.
Coffman a $20 bill to pay the driver, Ms. Coffman said. Ms. Coffman
was 16 and Ms. Foster 19.
   ``I said `Do you remember me?' He said `Yes.' ... He said `Nice
to see you again,''' Ms. Coffman said.
   Lukens shook his head repeatedly during her testimony.
   Ms. Coffman said Lukens showed the two around his apartment and
took them to a guest room.
   ``He told us to get undressed and put on ... two black robes,''
Ms. Coffman said. She asked him why they could not wear two white
robes she saw in the room. ``He said those were for white people
... other kind of people,'' she said.
   Ms. Coffman and Ms. Foster are black. Lukens is white.
   Ms. Coffman testified that they got into bed with Lukens. ``He
started talking nasty,'' she said.
   The judge recessed the trial until the afternoon to let Ms.
Coffman regain her composure.
   The congressman is on trial on a charge of contributing to the
unruliness or delinquency of a minor for allegedly having sex with
the girl one day before she turned 17.
   If convicted of the misdemeanor, Lukens, who is divorced, could
receive six months in jail and a $1,000 fine.
   Before Ms. Coffman testified, defense attorney Thomas Tyack
attacked the testimony of the girl's mother, Anna Coffman, and
tried to depict the woman as continually unemployed and desperate
for notoriety and money.
   Also today, Domestic Relations Judge Ronald Solove ruled that
Ms. Coffman's juvenile record is not admissable.
   During cross-examination, Tyack suggested that Mrs. Coffman was
lying when she said her daughter did not tell her she was going to
Lukens' apartment. He presented evidence she had told police and TV
station WSYX that her daughter did tell her.
   ``You knew where she was going and you didn't try to stop her,''
Tyack charged.
   ``I did not know the place she was going,'' Mrs. Coffman said.
   Mrs. Coffman also said she was paid $1,500 for an interview with
a local TV show. She previously testified WSYX paid for a two-day
stay at a Columbus hotel.
   Mrs. Coffman contacted Lukens and confronted him during a
meeting at a Columbus fast-food restaurant that was secretly
videotaped by WSYX. The 50-minute tape, in which Lukens was barely
audible, was shown to the jury Tuesday.
   ``I told him how old she was,'' Mrs. Coffman said, adding she
showed Lukens pictures of the girl. ``It didn't bother him a bit
because apparently he's been doing that all along.'' She said
Lukens told her he thought her daughter was 18.
   Mrs. Coffman testified Tuesday that she took her story to WSYX
because Lukens ``should be exposed for what he was.''
   ``A person with his power should not be in office,'' she
testified.
   She said she also called Lukens in 1985 to discuss ``him
contributing to her delinquency by getting her intoxicated'' and
told him the girl was 13.
</TEXT>
