<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--BridalShop     05-24 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bridal Shop,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rent Dispute Spawns Bridal `Nightmare'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE OAK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a bridal shop padlocked in a
rent dispute is grateful to a judge who cleared the way for anxious
brides and prom-goers to get their gowns.
   ``It's been a nightmare for the girls as well as for me,'' said
Mildred M. Marsh, owner of the House of Bridal Elegance in White
Oak, a Pittsburgh suburb. ``I've had brides crying hysterically,
not knowinig what was going on.''
   Ever since her shop was padlocked Friday, Marsh said she has
received more than 50 calls from tearful brides and high school
girls who want their gowns.
   Allegheny County Common Pleas Judge Robert Horgos ordered the
padlock removed Tuesday.
   Brandywine Agency Inc. closed the shop because it said Marsh
owed three months' rent. Marsh said she put the rent money in an
escrow account until landlord Robert Biros finishes renovations he
promised.
   At a hearing May 31, White Oak Magistrate Paul Kahn will decide
whether to continue to enforce the court order allowing Marsh
access to the store.
