<FIRST>r a PM-SmogPatrol 2ndLd-Writethru a0489 05-24 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smog Patrol, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0489,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smogbusters Tackle Tailpipes to Clean Up Country's Worst Air</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `The agency ...' to CORRECT title to `Management'
sted `Maintenance.'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ONTARIO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tractor-trailer belches black smoke
as it rumbles up a mountainous pass, leaving behind a gritty
landscape obscured by gray haze: the Los Angeles basin at high noon.
   ``There's a good one,'' says California Highway Patrol Officer
Greg Dettinger and the smog patrol is off and chasing yet another
18-wheeled contributor to Southern California's choking smog.
   In Southern California, the CHP ``Smokeys'' are living up to
their nickname by pulling over the puffing tailpipes as well as the
speeders.
   ``We pull people over on the freeway and other people will go by
and blow their horns and give the thumbs up,'' said Sgt. George
Johnson, who is in charge of the patrols.
   As Dettinger was writing a citation, trucker Thomas Schwartz
conceded, ``Something has to be done, there's no doubt about it.''
   Southern California's skies are the most polluted in the nation
_ a result of surrounding mountains that trap the filth along with
stagnant weather and industries that operate in the area.
   The agency responsible for reducing the pollution, the South
Coast Air Quality Management District, took part of its cleanup
effort last yearto the streets by dispatching highway patrol
officers to stop polluting vehicles and issue orders to clean up or
pay up.
   Drivers can join the crackdown by calling a hotline to report
the license numbers of smoking vehicles. The culprits are sent
stern letters and must provide proof the problem is fixed.
   The air quality district has found people are eager to help
clean up the air by reporting others. More than 7,200 people phoned
the smog hotline to report smoking cars in March, said spokesman
Bill Kelly.
   The district's territory extends over 13,600 square miles from
the Pacific Ocean to Palm Springs, 110 miles east of Los Angeles,
then north to the Ventura County line and south to where Orange
County meets San Diego County.
   An estimated 11 million people live in the district, which
encompasses Los Angeles, Orange and Riverside counties and
non-desert areas of the vast San Bernardino County. In Los Angeles
County alone, there are 5.4 million licensed drivers.
   All that exhaust contributed to ozone levels that exceeded
federal health standards 176 days in 1988.
   Southern California's air is so fouled that in March, the agency
proposed a drastic change in driving habits. Under the plan, 40
percent of non-commerical and 70 percent of vehicles would be
required by 1998 to run on methanol, fuel cells or electricity
rather than on gasoline.
   Unlike the high-level ozone layer, which filters the sun's
harmful ultraviolet radiation, low-level ozone is dangerous.
   The pale-blue gas formed by a chemical reaction involving
nitrogen dioxide and hydrocarbons is one of the principal
components of smog.
   Vehicle exhaust is believed to cause up to 8 percent of lung
cancer in non-smoking urban residents. Research has shown ozone
aggravates respiratory ailments in children, the elderly and people
suffering from heart and lung diseases. It eats away at tires and
nylon, damages crops and has damaged the lungs of animals used in
experiments.
   Since July, when the program became full time, eight officers
driving cars marked with the winged-dove logo of the air quality
district have written more than 8,000 citations to smoking
vehicles, mostly diesel trucks.
   Jim Crape, a state engineer who works in Chino, carries a tape
recorder to take down license numbers of polluting vehicles.
   ``I turned in about 120 already,'' he said. ``We can't let it
keep going, because what is it going to be like when the population
doubles, triples? What? Are we going to wear gas masks?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0590 05-24 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0590,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets OK Limits On Troops In East Europe; Bush Says Not Enough</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 4th graf, The twin, with 4 grafs on Bush reaction;
inserts new 10th graf, And Margaret, with State Dept. reax; edits Bush
reference in 11th graf, Gorbachev's overture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has
agreed to impose ceilings on Soviet forces stationed in East
European countries, U.S. officials said today.
   In a parallel move, the officials said, Gorbachev suggested that
no country _ including the Soviet Union and the United States _ be
allowed to have more than 35 percent to 40 percent of the combined
manpower totals of NATO and the Warsaw Pact.
   This would have the effect of diluting the forces of the Soviet
Union in Eastern Europe and overall, as well.
   The proposals were the latest in a series of arms control
initiatives by Gorbachev, and President Bush welcomed them today.
   ``The Soviets are now being forthcoming and we hope to achieve
the reductions that we seek,'' Bush said in a commencement speech
at the U.S. Coast Guard Academy in New London, Conn.
   But he added: ``These reductions alone, even if implemented, are
not enough to eliminate the superiority the Soviet Union enjoys
now'' in Europe.
   The twin moves by Gorbachev were in response to longstanding
U.S. demands for reducing a large Warsaw Pact edge over the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization in non-nuclear strength. For instance,
Soviet tanks now account for nearly 70 percent of all NATO and
Warsaw Pact armor.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater sought to play down the
importance of the latest Soviet proposal, saying it was a response
to a plan proposed last March 9 by the United States and its NATO
allies.
   But Fitzwater said, ``The Soviets have provided details in a
meaningful way at the negotiating table. It is a serious proposal
and we look forward to the negotiations.''
   And Margaret Tutwiler, the State Department spokeswoman, said
``we view this as a serious and substantial proposal that is being
received as such.''
   Gorbachev's overture came less than a week before NATO holds a
summit meeting in Brussels attended by Bush and the leaders of the
15 other Western governments.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
Soviets had also offered to reduce Warsaw Pact tank and armored
personnel carriers to just above NATO levels.
   Specifically, the Soviets said they would reduce their tank
total by 17,580 and personnel carriers by about 27,000, the
officials said.
   The Soviet position was outlined by Soviet negotiators in a
closed meeting Tuesday in Vienna with U.S. and NATO officials. It
was an elaboration of the cuts Gorbachev and Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze had told Secretary of State James
A. Baker III about two weeks ago in Moscow.
   In exchange for NATO reductions, the Soviets offered to cut
Warsaw Pact tanks by 40,000, combat aircraft by 42,000, and
artillery pieces by 47,000. NATO has somewhat different totals in
each category.
   Gorbachev also proposed a reduction of 1 million troops in both
alliances and a 55 percent cutback in NATO's combat aircraft.
   By 1997, there would be equal levels of 1.35 million troops in
NATO and the Warsaw Pact, 1,500 strike aircraft, 20,000 tanks,
1,700 helicopters, 24,000 artillery pieces and 28,000 combat
vehicles.
   The two alliances opened negotiations in Vienna in February with
the aim of reducing non-nuclear forces across the vast expanse of
Europe _ from the Atlantic Ocean in the West to the Ural Mountains
in the Soviet Union.
   Besides seeking overall Warsaw Pact reductions, the United
States and its allies for years have tried to persuade the Soviets
to impose limits both on the forces they keep in Czechoslovakia,
East Germany, Poland and Hungary, and ceilings on each of the
allies' troops. These include Bulgaria and Romania, which are also
members of the Warsaw Pact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
