<FIRST>r i AM-China-HongKong     05-24 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Hong Kong,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>100,000 People Rally in Rain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100,000 people Wednesday jammed the
neon-lighted, rainy streets of Hong Kong for a fifth straight day
to support the pro-democratic movement in China.
   Students, teachers, workers and clerks marched through Causeway
Bay, a major shopping district.
   The marchers paralyzed traffic for two hours, chanting:
``Support Beijing students!'' and ``Long Live People Power!''
   Chinese Premier Li Peng Saturday imposed martial law in Beijing
and described the student movements as ``turmoil.''
   Marchers also sang patriotic songs, including ``For Freedom,''
which was written and recorded Tuesday by about 100 singers to
support the Beijing students.
   ``We should have endurance,'' said a woman who also joined the
territory's largest march Sunday. She had left her husband and
young children at home to march.
   ``We hope to arouse the morale among the students in Beijing,''
said Yeung Chi-Keung, a high school teacher who led 200 students
for the march.
   ``This is also a good civic education for our students,'' he
said. ``No matter how much and how well we explain civic rights at
school, it is not as good as this first-hand experience.''
   At the rally, civic leaders spoke to the protesters and urged
Chinese Premier Li Peng to step down. They also called the Chinese
government to lift martial law and press restrictions.
   Earlier Wednesday, about 90 senior citizens chanting slogans
demonstrated outside the Xinhua News Agency, China's unofficial
representive in Hong Kong, a British colony to be turned over to
China in 1997.
</TEXT>
