<FIRST>r a PM-CritterDinner     05-24 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Critter Dinner,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Humane Officer Fired for Shooting Groundhog for Dinner </HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dog catcher who shot a
groundhog for a neighboring town's annual Critter Dinner has been
forced to step down for firing his gun inside city limits.
   H.E. ``Spot'' Hudson said he was called last week to get a
groundhog out of a garage. The resident, in trapping the animal,
had injured it, so Hudson shot it and gave it to the town of Dunbar
for its wild animal dinner.
   ``I was an officer of the law. I had a right to,'' Hudson said.
   Mayor Richie Robb didn't think so and asked Hudson to step down
after nine years as dog catcher.
   ``It is illegal for citizens to do that. I think it was the
improper thing to do even if he was an officer of the law,'' Robb
said.
   Hudson usually set aside wild animals for Dunbar Mayor Frank
Leone, who holds a free Critter Dinner each February for senior
citizens.
   ``If you get young groundhog, it's excellent eating,'' Leone
said.
</TEXT>
