<FIRST>r a PM-FusionWorkshop 2ndLd-Writethru a0559 05-24 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion Workshop, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0559,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Differ on Fusion Claims, Most Agree It's Worth Pursuing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, `The announcement ...' to CORRECT that conference
is sponsored by Los Alamos but is not at Los Alamos.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED MORENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many scientists at a workshop set up to
investigate cold fusion say they will keep looking for evidence of
the process, but nearly all of them say they have seen no sign yet
it exists.
   The workshop on the claims of University of Utah chemist Stanley
Pons and his British colleague, Martin Fleischmann, has brought
together an estimated 500 physicists and chemists with a wide
variety of theories.
   Pons and Fleischmann startled the scientific world with the
announcement two months ago that they had achieved cold fusion in a
simple experiment using a palladium electrode and water made with
deuterium, a heavy isotope of hydrogen.
   The conventional belief was that fusion as an energy source
could be attained only at high temperatures and by applying high
power.
   The announcement has been the subjects of several conferences
around the country, including the three-day workshop here. The
workshop, sponsored by Los Alamos National Laboratory, concludes
Thursday.
   ``There seems to be an intense scientific interest in the
possibility that a nuclear reaction takes place in a so-far
unanticipated site,'' said Norman Hackerman, retired professor of
chemistry at Rice and Texas universities.
   Pons and Fleischmann ignored the opportunity to attend the
workshop and defend their claims. They also canceled a meeting with
Utah officials who want to give them $5 million for their research.
   The observations at the conference included many like those of
physicist Nathan Lewis of the California Institute of Technology.
He flatly rejected the Pons-Fleischmann assertions.
   Hopeful commentary came from Texas A&amp;M University chemist John
Appleby. He suggested that fusion has sometimes occurred in his
team's experiment.
   Appleby declined to say in an interview that fusion occurred in
the Pons-Fleischmann experiments. If it is fusion, he said, it is
not occurring in the usual way.
   Fusion is a process in which light atoms combine to form heavier
elements, releasing energy.
   Appleby's encouraging findings included the discovery of large
amounts of tritium in the heavy water solution, along with a small
number of neutrons. Tritium can be a product of fusion.
   He also described different heat measurements using different
solutions, such as a lithium-based bath and a sodium solution that
shut down all reactions.
   ``We don't know what's going on, but it is not chemistry,''
Appleby said. ``There's a lot of confusion, rather than fusion,
going on.''
   Petar Tomas, a physicist with the Ruder Boskovic Institute in
Yugoslavia, said he found the Utah claims ``difficult to believe.''
But he proclaimed much of the theoretical physics presented at the
workshop ``positive'' and headed in the right direction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 6thLd-Writethru a0620 05-24 1131</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0620,1080</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing in grafs 17-24, White House, subbing for
pvs grafs 17-26, A NATO.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today welcomed new arms
reduction proposals by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev but
said they were ``not enough'' to redress the edge Warsaw Pact
forces maintain over NATO in Europe.
   He also challenged Gorbachev to disclose accurate figures on
Soviet military spending. ``Open the ledger,'' Bush said in a
commencement address to the Coast Guard Academy.
   Speaking only a day after the Soviet leader offered to impose
new limits on troops stationed in Eastern Europe and on Soviet
forces overall, Bush said, ``The Soviets are now being forthcoming
and we hope to achieve the reductions that we seek.''
   However, he said, ``these reductions alone, even if implemented,
are not enough to eliminate the superiority the Soviet Union enjoys
now.''
   Bush declared communism ``a failed system'' and said the West
was entering a new era based on economic and political success.
   ``There is an opportunity before us to shape a new world,'' Bush
said.
   He took note of the pro-democracy demonstrators who have
occupied Beijing's Tiananmen Square for more than 10 days and said
the United States ``will do all it can to encourage'' those who
``are speaking the language of democracy and freedom.''
   He wished Gorbachev success in attempting to restructure the
Soviet economy and said lasting peace was now more likely than ever
before.
   But Bush said it still was necessary to maintain a strong
nuclear deterrence with a new U.S. long-range mobile missile and
making other ocean-spanning land-based missiles transportable.
   ``We live in a time when we are witnessing the end of an idea _
the final chapter of the Communist experiment,'' Bush said. He
called Communism ``a failed system, one that promised economic
prosperity but failed to deliver the goods, a system that built a
wall between the people and their political aspirations.''
   He urged further reductions by the Soviet-led alliance and
reiterated his call for territorial overflights on both sides.
   Bush also played on the theme of open markets in his speech and
said ``if we succeed, the next decade, and the century beyond, will
be an era of unparalleled growth.''
   Bush said success also required an end to conflict and turmoil.
He said the United States and its allies were pursuing a strategy
of strength, economically, diplomatically and militarily.
   In the Soviet Union, the president said, a dramatic process is
unfolding.
   ``Make no mistake, our policy is to seize every _ and I mean
every _ opportunity to build a better and more stabile relationship
with the Soviet Union.''
   He said ``we want to see perestroika (economic restructuring)
succeed'' as well as the policy of openness, known as glasnost.
   White House aides said Bush rejected a prepared text and added
new sections hours before he was to speak.
   A NATO session Bush is attending in Brussels next Monday and
Tuesday with the leaders of 15 other Western governments is likely
to be dominated by how to respond to a series of arms control
initiatives by Gorbachev.
   In Washington, U.S. officials said Gorbachev had made proposals
to impose ceilings on Soviet forces stationed in Eastern Europe as
well as outlining possible reductions in Soviet conventional arms.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the latest Gorbachev
proposal represented the first time the Soviets had agreed to an
overall ceiling on conventional forces.
   ``We find this very promising,'' Fitzwater said. ``These are
major, major concessions that put them more in line with the NATO
proposal.''
   National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft said Gorbachev had
given Secretary of State James A. Baker III a general description
of the Soviet proposal during Baker's visit to Moscow earlier this
month but that ``they were vague. Now they've put more meat on it.''
   Scowcroft, who accompanied Bush to the Coast Guard academy, told
reporters the Soviet proposal ``looks like a serious proposal and
we will treat it as a serious proposal. We will look at it.''
   Meanwhile, Bush said in an interview with European journalists
released today that new Soviet proposals for reducing conventional
forces would be helpful, but it would be reckless for NATO ``to lay
down our weapons and turn them into plowshares.''
   Bush also expressed interest in a possible visit to
Communist-ruled East Germany. Asked what it would take to get him
to make such a trip, the president said: ``First, an invitation.''
   Addressing the Coast Guard graduates, Bush said that ``never
before has the idea of freedom so captured the imaginations of men
and women the world over _ and never before has the hope of freedom
beckoned so many.
   ``Trade unioninsts in Warsaw. The people of Panama. Rulers
consulting the ruled in the Soviet Union. And even as we speak
today, the world is transfixed by the dramatic events in Tiananmen
Square.
   ``Everywhere those voices are speaking the language of democracy
and freedom. And we hear them. And the world hears them. And
America will do all it can to encourage them.''
   In the interview with European journalists, he said that the
massive protests in China and political reform movements in other
parts of the world show ``the democratic way is on the march and it
is not going to be stopped.''
   Still, the president cautioned, ``I'm old enough to remember
Hungary in 1956 and I don't want to be a catalyst for encouraging a
course of action that would inevitably lead to violence and
bloodshed.''
   He said Gorbachev's recent offers, in reality, were no more than
responses to NATO proposals ``and then it's reported as though this
is an enormous step forward...So we need a little light in all of
this.''
   And, while giving the Soviet leader points for public relations,
Bush declared, ``You do not make foreign policy based on the
personality or charm of an individual in another country. You do it
on facts.''
   Bush indicated in the interview, with reporters from news
organizations from Britain, West Germany, Italy and Belgium, that a
compromise with West Germany on short-range missiles might not be
possible before the 16-nation NATO summit that begins on Monday.
   ``I have felt that we can resolve this issue before we get to
Brussels. I'm not sure now, but we'll keep working the problem,''
Bush said.
   Despite a transatlantic flurry of proposals and counterproposals
over the past few days, there is no agreement on proposed
superpower talks to reduce short-range missiles in Europe.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has called for such talks.
Bush opposes them, at least while Soviet-bloc nations retain an
advantage in tanks and troops.
   Bush spoke to reporters from Italy's Il Messaggero, Britain's
The Guardian, Belgium's De Standaard and West Germany's Frankfurter
Allgemeine Zeitung.
</TEXT>
