<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Powers     05-24 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Powers,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Powers, Duties of New Soviet Congress Still Uncertain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The exact powers and duties of the Congress of
People's Deputies remain uncertain as reformers scrambled Wednesday
to unite forces and promote their own agendas.
   Under political reforms championed by President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev that created the congress, the 2,250-member body is
supposed to meet once a year to elect a smaller, working
legislature and a handful of top officials, including the Soviet
president.
   But progressive deputies are demanding the congress debate the
country's critical problems, including the economy and environment,
and human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov has even called for it
to supersede the smaller legislature, the Supreme Soviet, as the
chief law-making organ.
   The exact role the congress assumes for itself won't be known
until the deputies gather at the Kremlin Palace of Congresses. As
foreseen in the laws and constitutional amendments that created the
congress, its duties include:
   _ Electing the Soviet president, who will assume more power. The
president will be in charge of general administration of the
country and will chair the Defense Council, make proposals to the
Supreme Soviet, negotiate with foreign countries and sign treaties
and make laws.
   _ Electing from among its members the the 542-member Supreme
Soviet. That body will meet for two four-month terms yearly as the
country's working legislature.
   _ Making changes in the Soviet Constitution.
   _ Reviewing the president's choice for premier, the chairman of
the Supreme Court and the prosecutor-general.
   Among the new parliamentarians who will convene Thursday morning
at the Kremlin for the inaugural session of the congress, there are:
   _ 750 deputies elected by Soviet voters from geographical
districts of equal population throughout the country.
   _ 750 deputies elected by voters to represent the 15 constituent
Soviet republics as well as the autonomous territories and regions
that are official homelands for the Soviet Union's more than 100
ethnic groups.
   _ 750 deputies directly chosen by officially sanctioned
organizations ranging from the Communist Party, labor unions and
the Soviet Academy of Sciences to the national associations of
booklovers and stamp collectors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
