<FIRST>r a AM-MarijuanaRally     05-24 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marijuana Rally,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Tells Lawyers To Work Out Location For Gathering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Wednesday told
lawyers squabbling over a planned marijuana rally in North Adams to
agree on a site suitable for the crowd expected or risk a court
order.
   ``I hate to issue an order requiring the town to use one of
those fields,'' Chief U.S. District Judge Frank Freedman told
attorneys for the city of North Adams and for the rally organizers.
   The North Adams Parks and Recreation Commission denied a permit
to a marijuana law reform group that wanted to stage a May 28 rally
in North Adams. The group advocates decriminalizing marijuana.
   The commission argued that city parks could not accommodate the
3,000 people that the Massachusetts Cannabis Reform Coalition said
it expected for the rally.
   ``It's not who they are,'' commission Chairman Donald Esposito
said. ``The only thing I'm interested in is protecting the city's
fields.''
   Richard Evans, an attorney representing the coalition, filed a
complaint May 15 alleging that the group's constitutional rights to
free speech and assembly were being violated.
   ``The plaintiffs are residents of North Adams who wish simply to
exercise their rights to a meeting on a serious topic of interest,
both nationally and locally,'' Evans said.
   He called the crowd estimate of 2,000 to 3,000 people ``a little
optimistic'' and said plaintiffs would be willing to accept a limit
of 1,000 people at the rally.
</TEXT>
