<DOCNO> AP890524-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1536EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-911-Rape     05-24 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-911-Rape,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>911 Foul-Up Was Human Error, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDVALE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispatcher jotted down the wrong
telephone number when a terrified woman called 911 to report a
break-in, prompting police to send a patrol car to the wrong town
while the woman was being raped, authorities said.
   Police also revealed Tuesday that the woman spent several
chilling minutes on the phone with emergency dispatchers while the
rapist listened and brandished a knife.
   The woman had called to report a prowler early Sunday morning,
but the intruder burst into her home in mid-call. She then
pretended to be talking to her mother while trying to convey
information to the dispatcher.
   When the dispatcher asked for a phone number, the victim
``rattled it off, saying something like, `Oh, you know my number,
Mother, it's ...,''' Midvale police Capt. Dan Pearson said.
   However, the dispatcher copied down the number incorrectly. And
when she read it back to the victim for confirmation, the victim
affirmed it was correct.
   Moments later, the victim hung up.
   The incorrect phone number corresponded to an address in Sandy,
about two miles northwest of Midvale, and two police officers were
dispatched. When they found nothing amiss at the Sandy address,
they reported the call to be unfounded and no further action was
taken.
   An hour and a half later, the rapist left the victim and she
phoned again for police assistance. Police found her home the
second time.
   The victim was able to get a vehicle license number and a
33-year-old man was arrested Sunday and booked into the Salt Lake
County Jail.
   Dale Floyd Garrett of Kearns was charged Tuesday with aggravated
rape, aggravated burglary and aggravated kidnapping. Bail was set
at $50,000.
   The incident occurred during the transition to an enhanced 911
system in the Salt Lake City area. Sandy and Midvale are Salt Lake
suburbs.
   Under the new system, Pearson said, the possibility of similar
mistakes occurring will be virtually eliminated because a caller's
telephone number and address will automatically appear on a
dispatcher's computer screen.
   Under the old system, calls have been lost and numbers garbeled
``time and time again,'' Pearson said. ``That's why we pushed for
the new system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
