<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1540EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearPlants     05-24 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Plants,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auditors Criticize Energy Department Plan For New Military Reactors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department gave Congress ``improper
and unrealistic'' estimates of the cost of building new military
reactors in South Carolina and Idaho, federal auditors told a House
panel Wednesday.
   Officials of the General Accounting Office also said the
department had understated the time it would take to complete the
reactors, which the Bush administration says can be in operation
within 10 years for $6.8 billion.
   In testimony before a special panel of the House Armed Services
Committee, J. Dexter Peach, the GAO's assistant comptroller
general, raised doubts about other key aspects of the
administration's plan, which was announced last August. The
administration is seeking $300 million in next year's budget for
design work.
   The reactors would produce tritium, a radioactive gas used to
make nuclear warheads.
   One reactor is to be built at the department's Savannah River
Site, near Aiken, S.C., and the other would be new at the Idaho
National Engineering Laboratory, near Idaho Falls. The department
wants them in production by 1998 as replacements for three
35-year-old Savannah River reactors which have been shut down for
repairs.
   Peach said recent breakdowns at the existing Savannah River
reactors, which are the nation's only source of tritium, make the
need for new reactors ``more acute,'' but he raised doubts about
the new technology to be used at the new plants.
   ``There is some high risk associated with getting the technology
to work,'' he said.
   Peach also questioned the Energy Department's cost calculations
for the 18 different options it considered. He said the department
had taken cost estimates for full-sized reactors and ``scaled them
down'' for use in figuring the cost of smaller reactors.
   ``In our judgment, DOE's scaling assumptions were not realistic
and resulted in improper and unrealistic cost estimates for the
various options,'' Peach said.
   Peach's public remarks were less harsh than the language used in
private reports to the panel's members and its staff, according to
sources who asked not to be identified.
   These sources said panel members were told in private briefings
by GAO officials who are working on the agency's review of the new
reactor program that the Energy Department had ``misinformed'' the
Congress and was guilty of ``manipulation'' of figures used in
calculating the construction cost and timetable.
   The GAO review is not yet complete, and no official report has
been published.
   When asked about the accusations made by other GAO officials,
Peach did not disavow the charges but said his main concern was
that the Energy Department had not yet provided Congress with
enough information to make a decision on the plan's merits.
   A department official acknowledged to the panel that it could
take 1{ years longer than the 10-year estimate offered to Congress
for getting the new reactors running.
   The GAO says it would take at least 12{ years to get a
heavy-water reactor into production at Savannah River and 16 years
to begin tritium output at a modular high-temperature gas-cooled
reactor proposed for the Idaho site. It disputed the department's
$6.8 billion cost estimate for the two reactors but gave no
estimate of its own.
   The agency said a shorter and less costly alternative would be
to convert the partially completed WNP1 commercial nuclear plant at
the Hanford Reservation, near Richland, Wash., to tritium
production. This could be done in seven years for $2.2 billion.
   Ronald W. Cochran, acting director of the department's new
reactor program, said he could give no firm cost estimates for the
proposed reactors until design work is finished next year.
   Cochran also said Energy Secretary James D. Watkins was leaving
open the possibility of converting the WNP1 reactor to tritium
production but is concerned about public and congressional
opposition.
</TEXT>
