<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-China     05-24 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Calls Chinese News Restrictions Regrettable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration said Wednesday China's
renewed restriction of news broadcasts transmitted by satellite
``is regrettable,'' and called for an end to the jamming of the
Voice of America and open access for journalists.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Chinese
authorities informed Western networks they would not be able to
transmit by satellite after 1 a.m., or noon Washington time on
Wednesday.
   ``It is regrettable,'' Ms. Tutwiler said of the satellite
restriction.
   The move ends the networks' ability to broadcast pictures
directly from China.
   Satellite transmissions had been banned after martial law went
into effect on Saturday. The news organizations were prevented from
using their own satellite installations to transmit their reports.
   But foreign broadcasters were allowed to transmit news reports
for a brief time on Tuesday on the satellite operated by the
Chinese television network, CCTV.
   ``The unimpeded reception of radio broadcasts and unrestricted
satellite transmissions are, in our view, among the elements of a
free press, and we hope they will be supported and sustained in
China,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   The spokeswoman reminded reporters that President Bush had urged
non-violence and restraint during his White House meeting on
Tuesday with Wan Li, the chairman of the Chinese People's Congress.
   She said the president ``urges that not only the satellite feeds
but the Voice of America not be jammed and that reporters be given
open access.''
   Many of the demonstrators have relied on foreign news radio
broadcasts for updates on events in their own country throughout
the five weeks of protests.
   The spokeswoman added that the State Department's warning that
American citizens delay travel to China is still in effect. The
department has also advised Americans in China to avoid the
demonstrations.
   She termed the situation in China ``tense ... but calm.''
   The U.S. Embassy has been in touch in with American businesses
in China ``to keep them appraised of the situation of what's going
on,'' but Ms. Tutwiler said she was unaware that anyone had been
advised to transfer personnel out of the country because of the
unrest.
</TEXT>
