<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1602EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DC-10CrashAnniversary     05-24 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Crash Anniversary,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ten Years Later, Chicago Crash Still Worst Domestic Air Disaster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gleaming American Airlines DC-10 taxied down
the runway for takeoff 10 years ago Thursday, lifting off into a
nightmarish niche in U.S. aviation history.
   Flight 191 was over in seconds, the jetliner and its inhabitants
instantly reduced to scattered debris in what remains the nation's
worst air crash.
   The plane lost an engine on takeoff, banked sideways out of
control and slammed into a nearby field, exploding into a jet-fuel
inferno. All 258 passengers and 13 crew members died, as well as
two people on the ground.
   ``Just the sound of a jet _ it just brings it back every time I
hear a plane go by,'' said Raymond Devito of Mokena, who had driven
his girlfriend, Debra Ann Moruzi, 21, of Joliet, to O'Hare
International Airport.
   Ms. Moruzi and a girlfriend were booked onto Flight 191 to Los
Angeles, the first leg of an eagerly awaited trip to Hawaii. After
they boarded, Devito went to an observation deck to watch the
takeoff.
   As the plane moved down the runway, Devito noticed white smoke
coming from one engine. Once the plane was airborne, he saw flame
and black smoke along a wing.
   Then the plane was down in a column of black smoke, and Devito
was scrambling over fences and across runways to the site. Nothing
resembling a plane was left.
   ``To this day, it's something that's hard to comprehend, how a
big plane like that could disintegrate into little pieces,'' said
Devito, 34, a real estate salesman. ``I ... didn't see a sign of a
person, a piece of luggage, a magazine.
   ``Nobody had to tell me there were no survivors.''
   The field is green now, but Chicago Police Sgt. Kenneth J.
Burger, who was at a training facility nearby, can still find the
furrow plowed by the DC-10's left wing in the flight's chaotic
final seconds.
   ``I would never forget,'' said Burger.
   After the crash, he and other officers ``went through the smoke
and came out the other side and there was no plane,'' he said.
   More than 200 lawsuits were filed after the crash. American
Airlines and the plane's builder, McDonnell Douglas Corp., have
paid damages estimated at more than $70 million.
   The National Transportation Safety Board laid primary blame for
the crash on American, citing ``maintenance-induced damage'' _ a
10-inch crack in the engine mount _ that caused the left engine to
tear loose.
   At issue was American's practice of removing the engine and the
pylon that attached it to the plane as a unit, rather than in two
pieces.
   The board said the accident ``resulted directly from improper
and abusive maintenance practices.''
   The NTSB also criticized McDonnell Douglas' design as vulnerable
to maintenance damage.
   And it said the Federal Aviation Administration had been remiss
by not learning that a similar crack had recently been repaired in
a Continental Airlines DC-10.
   ``One thing we did do is get very specific about what has to be
reported to us and what doesn't,'' FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said
Wednesday from Washington.
   Elaine Bendell, a spokeswoman for McDonnell Douglas in Long
Beach, Calif., said no changes have been made in the DC-10 pylon
design, except for a shift to flathead rather than raised-head
bolts.
   Officials for Dallas-based American declined to comment. ``It's
a sensitive issue,'' spokesman Tom Stack said in Chicago. He added
that the airline would prefer to ``let the public record speak for
itself.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
