<HEAD>Description Fits Suspect to a T</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say the description they have of a
robbery suspect is the most thorough they've ever had, because the
victim had just measured the man for a suit before he was robbed.
   Philip D. Smith, 31, owner of a tailoring and design shop, was
bound and gagged with duct tape and slightly injured in Tuesday's
robbery.
   He told police his assailant was 5-foot-9 or 5-foot-10, about
165 or 170 pounds, 14{-inch neck, 18-to-19-inch shoulders, 39-inch
chest, waist 34 to 35, sleeves 25{ inches from the shoulder, and
41-inch hips.
   The description of a companion was not so thorough, just around
6-foot-4 and at least 275 pounds.
   After being measured for the suit, Smith said, the smaller man
pushed him into a back room and, with the help of his friend, bound
and gagged him after a struggle.
   The two then ransacked the rear of the shop, taking off with a
camera, a watch and $24 from the cash register, Smith told police.
He was freed after he managed to get the attention of the
storekeeper next door.
   Smith said he was given 13 stitches for a cut lip and suffered a
possible broken nose and several bruises.
   ``What killed me was that they were so nice'' while discussing
the suit, Smith said.
