<FIRST>r a AM-FireOutlook     05-24 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fire Outlook,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire In Shoshone Forest Has Officials Concerned About Fire Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CODY, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A unusual spring fire in a national forest
next to Yellowstone National Park, still recovering from last
year's huge fires, has forest officials nervous about this year's
fire outlook.
   The fire in the southern end of the Shoshone National Forest
only covered about a quarter-acre, forest fire officer Bernie
Spanogle said Tuesday.
   ``But normally you don't get something like that happening this
early,'' he said.
   The fire near Dubois, southeast of Yellowstone, so concerned
Shoshone officials that beginning next month rangers will monitor
fuel conditions in the southern end of the forest, he said.
   ``It could be a real problem area,'' Spanogle said. ``Once you
get fire in it, it could be hard to stop. ... We have a potential
of having some large fires down there.''
   Last summer, forest fires started in northwestern Wyoming in
late June and continued through the fall, charring more than 1
million acres in Yellowstone, Grand Teton National Park, and the
Shoshone and Bridger-Teton national forests.
   The conflagrations prompted the Interior Department last July to
abandon the ``let burn'' policy, which calls for most naturally
caused fires in the park to burn untended as long as they don't
threaten structures or people.
   Federal officials still are reviewing that policy and through
this fire season all blazes _ natural and man-caused _ in national
forests and parks will be attacked from the outset.
   Despite the relatively low fire danger conditions now being
reported in Wyoming forests, the long Memorial Day holiday weekend
kicks off the summer tourist season and rangers will be urging
campers to be careful with fires, said Spanogle.
   ``As it stands right now, we will have no (fire) restrictions on
the Shoshone National Forest, but I will sure urge that any campers
who have live fires (to) be very careful,'' he said.
   In the Bridger-Teton National Forest, spokesman Mark Van Every
said fire danger currently is low.
   ``Contrary to last summer, we're in pretty good shape ... We got
a pretty good snowpack this past winter,'' he said.
   In Yellowstone, officials say heavy winter snow and a moist
spring should produce a ``very, very lush'' early summer.
</TEXT>
