<HEAD>Wrecking Crane Begins Work on Stubborn Tower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The apartment building that 550 pounds
of dynamite couldn't destroy offered stiff resistance Wednesday to
a wrecking ball.
   Three families evacuated from their nearby homes before the
failed demolition attempts prepared to spend at least one more
night in a motel.
   A larger wrecking crane was brought in after the 10-story
Hartford Park housing project building's walls buckled, but did not
break, when a 2-ton wrecking ball slammed against them.
   The tower was battered but largely intact after two attempts
failed to bring it down Sunday.
   ``It's a hard building,'' said Tom Santanelli, a wrecking crane
operator. ``It's coming apart good, but I can't see what I'm
doing.''
   Santanelli said the job will take three weeks but the building
should be low enough that the three evacuated families can return
Thursday.
   Stephen J. O'Rourke, executive director of the Providence
Housing Authority, said the authority paid more than $400 to put
the families up for two nights at a downtown hotel before moving
them to a less luxurious motel in Johnston on Tuesday.
   O'Rourke said he told the owners of a delicatessen and a coin
laundry that have been closed by the demolition to file a claim for
lost business with the insurance company that covered David Evans,
the explosives expert who failed to raze the building.
