<FIRST>r w AM-IndianLunch     05-24 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Lunch,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassadors' Wives, from Afghanistan to Zaire, Meet American Indians</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX23</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two dozen embassy wives ate an American Indian
lunch of quail, wild rice, cornbread and pumpkin cake Wednesday at
the Capitol, where Rep. Ben Nighthorse Campbell invited them to
enjoy the ``wonderful, rewarding experience'' of visiting an Indian
reservation.
   ``The Indian people are known for their hospitality,'' said
Campbell, a Colorado Democrat who is the only Indian member of
Congress.
   ``If you have time, go out and visit our brothers and sisters in
Indian country,'' he said, adding: ``You will have a wonderful,
rewarding experience.''
   A group of American Indian women wearing the traditional
clothing of Navajos, Choctaws, Kiowas, Seminoles, Payutes and other
tribes presided over the get-acquainted lunch for ambassadors'
wives from Afghanistan to Zaire, many of whom also wore their
native dress.
   The lunch was sponsored by the non-profit American Indian
Heritage Foundation, which provides emergency assistance to needy
Indians and promotes public awareness of native American culture.
   Campbell, whose father's ancestors were Northern Cheyenne from
Montana, said he knew little about his mother's family, which came
from Portugal's Azores Islands. Campbell warmly greeted the wife of
Portuguese ambassador Joao Eduardo M. Pereira Bastos, who said she
knew the little town where Campbell's maternal forebears once lived.
   The embassy wives applauded Rob ``Swift Arrow'' Rose, a young
North Carolina Cherokee who performed an intricate hoop dance, and
Dora Roanhorse, a Navajo from Chinle, Ariz., who is Miss Indian
U.S.A. She performed a ``swan dance'' which she said reflected
``the Indian philosophy of being in harmony with nature.''
   Campbell told the lunch guests that American Indians bear no
resemblance to the Hollywood stereotype of the warring ``noble
savage'' or the drunken bum. Like the peoples of foreign countries,
he said, ``we're all concerned about our children, our homes and
our livelihoods, and we're proud of our homelands.''
   Wil Rose, the foundation's chief executive officer, invited the
embassy wives to attend a major auction of American Indian arts and
crafts here in November to raise money for construction of an
Indian cultural and performing arts center in Washington.
   ``All the people of the world can benefit from exposure to the
values and diversity of American Indian culture,'' Rose said.
</TEXT>
