<DOCNO> AP890524-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1747EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DolphinUlcers     05-24 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dolphin Ulcers,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dolphins' Illness Created By Stress From Crowds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three bottlenose dolphins that developed ulcers
shortly after arriving at the National Aquarium had something in
common with many of the tourists watching them: They didn't like
crowds.
   Kibby, Mimi and Aphrodite became ill from the stress of being
unable to escape the hordes of people lining their tank, a
researcher said Wednesday. They recovered within six months after
being sent home to Florida.
   Unfortunately, ``the farthest point they could get away to in
the tank was still within their `flight distance,''' the distance
to which they would flee from the crowds, if they could, said
Michael K. Stoskopf, chief of medicine at the aquarium from 1981 to
1988 and a professor of comparitive medicine at Johns Hopkins
University School of Medicine.
   His study is awaiting publication by the Animal Welfare
Information Center of the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
   In July 1982, barely a year after the aquarium opened, the
dolphins were flown home to Grassy Key, Fla., where they have been
on exhibit at the Dolphin Research Center.
   The multimillion-dollar dolphin tank was never used for dolphins
again.
   But the lessons they taught scientists guided the selection of
beluga whales as the dolphins' replacements, and the manner in
which the belugas were moved from the wild to captivity, Stoskopf
said.
   ``We learned things about the animals that will help to make not
only their lives in captivity better, but may also make their lives
in the wild better,'' Stoskopf said.
   Stoskopf and his associates watched the dolphins' behaviors and
where they took place, looking for relationships between behavior
and possible stress factors in the tank.
   ``We looked at everything we thought could be stressful to them,
such as the configuration of the tank, temperature, being watched
by the public, light levels and noise from the pumps,'' he said.
   The results showed ``the real problem with the exhibit was the
people.''
   When the aquarium was crowded, almost 98 percent of the dophins'
activity was in parts of the tank away from people. As the number
of visitors increased, the animals began showing abnormal
``stereotypic'' behaviors.
   Crowds at the newly opened aquarium were three times what had
been expected, said Robert L. Jenkins, the aquarium's director of
operations and husbandry.
   ``The building was open until 2 a.m., and then it had to be
cleaned. The lights never went out,'' he said.
   The dolphins retreated as far as they could, but researchers
found that by fleeing from the crowds, the mammals congregated in a
spot where noise from the tank's pumps was loudest.
   For replacements, officials settled on beluga whales, arctic
mammals that are accustomed to very long or very short periods of
daylight.
   ``We also thought it would be better to acclimate the animals
slowly to a new home,'' Stoskopf said. The dolphins had been
brought to the aquarium too soon after being captured, with little
time to adjust to captivity or people.
   The belugas, Anore and Illamar, spent their first year in a
quiet tank at the New York Aquarium and were introduced slowly to
larger numbers of people. Today they ``seem to be very happy,''
Jenkins said. They were joined last summer by a third whale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush Bjt   05-24 0910</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, Bjt,910</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush: Gorbachev's Latest Proposal Good, but not Good Enough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Wednesday that
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's latest proposal to reduce
conventional arms in Europe could make the world safer but was not
enough to erase the Warsaw Pact's ``massive advantage'' over NATO.
   Bush, in a commencement address at the Coast Guard Academy, said
Gorbachev's offer confirms ``what we've known all along _ that
Soviet military power far exceeds the levels needed to defend the
legitimate security interests of the U.S.S.R.''
   Officials in Washington said Gorbachev on Tuesday proposed the
imposition of ceilings on Soviet forces stationed in Eastern Europe
and outlined possible reductions in Soviet conventional arms as
well.
   More broadly, Bush told the newly commissioned officers that,
internationally, he sees ``the ascendancy of the democratic idea.''
   The world, he said, is ``witnessing the end of an idea: the
final chapter of the communist experiment.
   ``Communism is now recognized, even by many within the communist
world itself, as a failed system, one that promised economic
prosperity but failed to deliver the goods, a system that built a
wall between the people and their political aspirations.''
   And, in some of his most pointed comments yet on the situation
in China, Bush took note of the pro-democracy demonstrators who
have jammed Beijing's Tiananmen Square for nearly two weeks and
said the United States ``will do all it can to encourage'' those
who ``are speaking the language of democracy and freedom.''
   But the bulk of Bush's speech dealt with relations with the
Soviet Union and the prospects for mutual arms reductions in
Europe, now the subject of negotiations between NATO and the Warsaw
Pact in Vienna.
   ``The Soviets are now being forthcoming, and we hope to achieve
the reductions that we seek,'' Bush said. But he challenged
Gorbachev to disclose accurate figures on Soviet military spending.
``Open the ledger,'' Bush said.
   Bush told the graduates that ``for more than 40 years, the
Warsaw Pact's massive advantage in conventional forces has cast a
shadow over Europe.''
   Now, he said, ``The unilateral reductions President Gorbachev
has promised give us hope that we can now redress that imbalance.
We welcome those steps because, if implemented, they will help to
reduce the threat of surprise attack.''
   But he reiterated the U.S. position that NATO must maintain a
strong force of European-based nuclear weapons to counter the
Warsaw Pact's conventional arms superiority.
   Earlier this month, Gorbachev proposed _ but the United States
rejected _ talks aimed at mutual reductions of European-based
nuclear weapons.
   Bush said it would be ``irresponsible to depend solely on
strategic (long-range) nuclear forces to deter conflict in Europe.''
   Bush leaves Friday for next week's 40th anniversary meeting of
leaders of NATO, with the future of the alliance's nuclear force an
still-unresolved point of contention between the United States and
West Germany.
   The Bonn government of Chancellor Helmut Kohl wants the Bush
administration to take the Soviets up on their request for talks on
short-range nuclear weapons and is also pushing to reverse plans to
modernize the arsenal of short-range nuclear weapons on German soil.
   The United States says the Soviets have such an advantage in
those weapons that cuts beyond what Gorbachev unveiled two weeks
ago must be made before talks can begin on mutual reductions.
   As for Gorbachev's newest proposal to reduce conventional arms,
Bush's advisers took a largely positive stance.
   ``We find this very promising,'' said spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater. ``These are major, major concessions that put them more
in line with the NATO proposal.''
   Brent Scowcroft, the president's national security adviser, said
Gorbachev had given Secretary of State James A. Baker III a general
outline of the Soviet proposals when the two met earlier this
month. Then, Scowcroft said, ``They were vague. Now they've put
more meat on it.''
   Also on Wednesday, the White House released the transcipt of an
interview between Bush and European journalists.
   In the interview, Bush said the massive protests in China and
political reform movements in other parts of the world show ``the
democratic way is on the march and it is not going to be stopped.''
   Still, the president cautioned, ``I'm old enough to remember
Hungary in 1956 and I don't want to be a catalyst for encouraging a
course of action that would inevitably lead to violence and
bloodshed.''
   In the New London speech, Bush said that ``never before has the
idea of freedom so captured the imaginations of men and women the
world over _ and never before has the hope of freedom beckoned so
many.
   ``Trade unionists in Warsaw. The people of Panama. Rulers
consulting the ruled in the Soviet Union. And even as we speak
today, the world is transfixed by the dramatic events in Tiananmen
Square.
   ``Everywhere those voices are speaking the language of democracy
and freedom. And we hear them. And the world hears them. And
America will do all it can to encourage them.''
   Bush, reflecting the fast-changing developments on the arms talk
front, made extensive revisions in his speech, both before and
after attending a banquet for White House photographers Tuesday
night and this morning as he flew here in a small Gulfstream jet.
   The last-minute revisions may have contributed to Bush's
stumbling over one passage, where he repeated the word ``security''
three times and finally told the audience, ``The text is going
crazy on this machine'' _ his prompter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
