<FIRST>r w AM-MinimumWage     05-24 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Try `Real People' In Minimum Wage Lobbying Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic congressional leaders, unable
themselves to convince President Bush to sign legislation raising
the minimum wage above what he has proposed, brought three low-wage
workers to Capitol Hill on Wednesday and gave them a shot at
changing the president's mind.
   ``Raise the minimum wage so we can live a little better and have
a little more,'' said Eula Malone of Atlanta, who said a custodial
company she works for has paid her the minimum wage for 18 years.
   ``We're not asking for you to give us anything,'' she said. ``We
want to work for it.''
   The unusual forum was hosted by the House Democratic Caucus,
which traditionally holds private meetings to plot strategy and
hear from people who would be affected by pending legislation.
Wednesday's session was opened to reporters as part of the
leadership's effort to pressure Bush to sign the measure.
   Bush has promised the bill that has cleared Congress, which
would raise the minimum wage from $3.35 an hour to $4.55 by October
1991, will be vetoed when it reaches his desk. The president
proposed a $4.25 hourly minimum wage by 1992.
   Democrats urging Bush to change his stance frequently remind the
president that the last time the minimum wage was increase was in
January 1981.
   Mrs. Malone put it more simply.
   ``We haven't had a raise since President Carter was in there,''
she said.
   Also at the forum was Verlie Reed, a receptionist at a
Philadelphia community center whose hourly pay jumped from $3.35 to
$3.70 because Pennsylvania increased its state minimum wage.
   ``We're still working on a poverty income,'' she said. ``I think
it's a disgrace, it's not right and something needs to be done.''
   House Democratic leaders, who applauded each of the three
witnesses at the hearing, also fired a few salvos at Bush.
   ``This scandalous neglect of hard-working American workers has
contributed to the rise of a new underclass in our society _ the
working poor and working homeless,'' said Rep. Bill Gray, D-Pa.,
the caucus chairman.
   ``We're trying to do justice to millions of American workers who
depend on the minimum wage,'' added House Majority Leader Thomas
Foley of Washington.
</TEXT>
