<SECOND>BC-Communism-Glance,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Upheaval in Communism at a Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief look at the latest developments in the movement
toward reform in communist nations:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CHINA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of students continued their sit-in at
Tiananmen Square, calling for a freer society and an end to
official corruption. A meeting of the ruling Communist Party
Politburo was scheduled for Thursday or Friday, perhaps signaling
the backstage power struggle between Premier Li Peng and Communist
Party chief Zhao Ziyang was coming to a head.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SOVIET UNION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's new parliament, the Congress of People's
Deputies, convenes its first session Thursday. Gestures from the
Kremlin have given hope to deputies of the body that they will have
an independent voice in solving the Soviet Union's economic and
social problems during the session.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>POLAND</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Students voted Wednesday to end a university sit-in against
government refusal to legalize their independent union, and said
they instead would concentrate on electing the Solidarity
parliament slate June 4. Solidarity spokesmen said their surveys
indicate the union's candidates will do well.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CZECHOSLOVAKIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Prague government Wednesday softened its previous demand
that Hungary must complete its part of a joint Danube River power
project on which the Hungarians suspended construction work.
Hungary, undergoing a political liberalization, had announced the
suspension of all work on the dam at Nagymaros, Hungary, because of
environmental and financial reasons, prompting a protest by
Czechoslovakia. However, Czechoslovak Premier Ladislav Adamec has
taken a more conciliatory stand following talks with his Hungarian
counterpart, Miklos Nemeth.
</TEXT>
