<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1902EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OperatorServices     05-24 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Operator Services,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Endorse Federal Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel Wednesday endorsed a bill
allowing federal regulation of the prices charged an increasingly
confused and angry traveling public by the proliferation of new
phone companies for operator services.
   The bill, approved by the Energy and Commerce telecommunications
and finance subcommittee on a voice vote, would require the
operator-services companies to clearly identify themselves, provide
rates to callers, not charge for incompleted calls and ensure that
credit-card callers are billed at their long-distance companies'
rates if they so choose.
   The bill was amended to force such companies to file a list of
their prices with the Federal Communications Commission. If the FCC
finds a company's rates to be unreasonable, the company then must
justify their charges.
   The bill also would require the FCC to determine whether the
operator-services industry as a whole is charging just and
reasonable rates. If not, the FCC would decide how to establish
rate regulation for the industry.
   The bill now goes to the full Energy and Commerce Committee,
where it is expected to pass and be sent to the full House.
   Operator-services companies typically lease long-distance lines
from the major long-distance carriers and then contract with such
operations as airports, motels, hospitals and schools to provide
service. In most cases, the companies pay airports and other
customer a commission on each call handled from their phones.
   The FCC has received 2,000 complaints about operator-services
companies, mostly regarding prices, which sometimes can be two or
three times the rates charged by the long-distance carriers
themselves.
   But the FCC in February said there was not enough evidence that
companies were charging excessively and instead told the companies
to post their names and telephone numbers on pay phones, stop
blocking callers from using the long-distance carrier of their
choice and stop billing customers from cities other than where the
calls are made.
   The House bill includes similar provisions. But Rep. Matthew
Rinaldo, R-N.J., said the bill also orders the pricing
investigation because of the FCC's ``wholly inadequate'' response
to the raft of complaints.
   The subcommittee chairman, Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., said the
bill was a response to ``a litany'' of complaints from consumers
``who innocently picked up pay phones and made calls which resulted
in charges 250 percent higher than their regular long-distance
rates.''
   ``For the first time in its 100-year history the public pay
phone has become an instrument of confusion and frustration,''
Markey added. ``A constituent recently told me she was afraid to
use her local phone booth because she did not know what to expect
in her next month's phone bill. This morning's action should end
the fear and the guesswork.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
