<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1910EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CottonClub     05-24 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cotton Club,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Limousine Carried Away Producer Later Found Dead, Witness Testifies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the night he vanished, film producer Roy
Radin stepped into a limousine with a drug dealer after arranging
for actor Demond Wilson to follow him with a gun, Radin's former
assistant testified Wednesday.
   But the signals for the actor to follow an apparently frightened
Radin got mixed up at the last minute, Radin's assistant, Jonathan
Lawson, testified in a hearing on the so-called ``Cotton Club
murder.''
   Lawson said he saw another, unidentified car take off in pursuit
of the limousine, and never saw Radin again.
   Lawson testified at a preliminary hearing in Municipal Court to
determine if the drug dealer, Karen DeLayne Greenberger, and three
men should stand trial for the 1983 kidnapping and murder of Radin.
   Prosecutors allege Radin was killed because of a disagreement
over how to split anticipated profits from the movie ``The Cotton
Club'' with Ms. Greenberger and former Paramount Pictures
production chief Robert Evans.
   Lawson said that on the last night of Radin's life, the
33-year-old New York businessman had a series of arguments with
Mrs. Greenberger, who was known then as Laynie Jacobs. He said they
argued over missing cocaine and over Miss Jacobs' share in profits
from ``Cotton Club.''
   She had introduced Radin to Evans and the two were negotiatng a
deal for the movie about the legendary Harlem nightspot of the
1930s.
   ``There was a discussion of her remaining as part of the `Cotton
Club' deal, and she expected to get her ($50,000) finder's fee for
making the introduction,'' Lawson testified.
   ``Roy said something about, `Yes, if it all goes through.'''
   Lawson said he had planned to drive Radin and Ms. Jacobs to La
Scala restaurant in Beverly Hills for dinner. Wilson, formerly the
star of television's ``Sanford and Son,'' was waiting outside with
a gun, ready to follow Radin's car.
   But Ms. Jacobs arrived in a limousine and insisted Radin ride
with her to the restaurant, Lawson testified. He said he walked
outside and tried to signal Wilson, but was unsure that Wilson saw
the signal.
   ``As I turned, lights came on on a car parked up from the hotel.
It pulled away from the hotel and pulled into the traffic lane the
limousine was in,'' Lawson testified.
   That was the last time Lawson saw Radin, whose bullet-riddled
body was found a month later in a dry riverbed 65 miles north of
Los Angeles.
   Another witness has said the plan was for Mrs. Greenberger to
lure Radin into the limousine, stop at some point, get out and let
two men who were following replace her in the car.
   Prosecutors allege that Mrs. Greenberger hatched the murder
conspiracy along with three former bodyguards of Hustler magazine
publisher Larry Flynt. They are William Molony Mentzer, Alex Lamota
Marti and Robert Ulmer Lowe. Lowe is fighting extradition in
Maryland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
