<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1912EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FutureBarnyard     05-24 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Future Barnyard,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Genetically Engineered Livestock May Be in 21st Century Barnyards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department predicted Wednesday
that barnyard animals in the 21st century may include genetically
engineered livestock that are naturally resistant to disease.
   Beef cattle destined for consumer dinner tables may be able to
thrive on low-grade crop residues and fibrous plants that are
barely digestible now. And chickens may be grown in closed,
disease-free environments.
   The predictions are part of a project by the department's
Agricultural Research Service to highlight some of the possible
changes that agency scientists see over the next 25 to 50 years.
   ``Of course, there are no guarantees that what the scientists
envision will become reality,'' said R. Dean Plowman, administrator
of the agency. ``But based on the research they're involved in
right now, it's certainly within the realm of possibility.''
</TEXT>
