<DOCNO> AP890524-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1915EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WestPoint     05-24 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-West Point,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Expects Revolution in Military Affairs Over Next Decade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle told
graduating cadets at the U.S. Military Academy on Wednesday that a
revolution in military affairs will require ``new military
organizations and new methods of warfare.''
   Quayle told the 1,011 cadets that their job was to ``maintain a
military establishment that is respected by friend and adversary
alike'' and said that because of their training he was confident
they would meet that challenge.
   The vice president said he expects a revolution in military
affairs over the next 10 to 15 years that will ``require us to
develop new operational concepts, new military organizations and
new methods of warfare.''
   A new strategic planning tool created by the Defense Department,
called Competitive Strategies, will help ``identify, develop and
field the weapons systems we need to be competitive with our major
adversary and to understand how those weapons might be used
operationally,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle was sheltered by a canopy during his 10-minute speech
while the cadets and their families stood and sat in a steady and
often-heavy rain.
   He said the best and shortest speech he could come up with would
have only two words: ``Beat Navy.'' The crowd responded with
thunderous applause.
   He noted that two graduating cadets from Indiana who he had
appointed to the academy made the dean's list, ``something I was
unable to do.'' Quayle's academic record, which reportedly was
below average, was questioned extensively during the 1988
presidential campaign.
   The vice president also praised the cadets' parents for their
support, understanding and encouragement and called families ``the
bedrock of our society.''
   ``This is particularly evident on occasions such as these, which
are in effect celebrations of our families and of their role in
instilling values in succeeding generations of young Americans,''
Quayle said.
   After the diplomas were handed out, the cadets gave the
traditional hat toss.
</TEXT>
