<FIRST>r w AM-DefenseConsultants     05-24 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Consultants,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Charges Called Questionable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 20 percent of the costs consultants
charged to the Pentagon in 1988 were deemed ``questionable,'' with
fees for advertising and lobbying mixed into the bills, according
to a Defense Department audit released Wednesday.
   ``If the taxpayers knew they were footing the bill for large
defense contractors to pay for lobbying, lawsuits, advertising and
constant reorganizations, there would be an uproar,'' Sen. David
Pryor, D-Ark., said in releasing the report.
   The Defense Contract Audit Agency, in a study of 118 audits,
found that of the $269 million in consultant costs charged to the
Pentagon, contracts worth $53.7 million were considered
``questionable.''
   Among the charges were $2.2 million for executive or legislative
lobbying and about $440,000 for unallowable public relations and
advertising. The highest cost was $33.8 million for ``lack of
adequate agreement@work product.''
   These costs were incurred because a defense contractor did not
have a written agreement with the consultant.
   ``This type of loosely monitored buddy system is what created
the need for last year's Ill Wind investigation,'' Pryor said. ``I
can only hope that the Defense Department learns from these DCAA
audit reports and improves its management of its contractors.''
   The audit agency recommended that defense contractors correct
the deficiencies in their system of estimating, approving and
accounting for consultant costs.
   The Pentagon is reviewing federal acquisition regulations
covering the definition, allowability and documentation
requirements for consultant costs.
</TEXT>
