<FIRST>r a AM-PuertoRicans     05-24 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Puerto Ricans,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Puerto Ricans Gather to Improve ``Desperate Social Conditions''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 500 leaders of the Puerto Rican
community met Wednesday at the start of a convention aimed at
improving what they called ``desperate social conditions'' facing
the 2.5 million Puerto Ricans in the United States.
   ``They're living in dire poverty, families are shaking at the
seams,'' said Zorlo Torres, president of the National Congress for
Puerto Rican Rights. ``We've made very little progress in this
country over the last 50 years.''
   Congress members issued a report outlining the status of Puerto
Ricans in the mainland United States showing that 38 percent of the
families live at or below the official poverty line. The report
also said 44 percent of Puerto Rican families are headed by single
mothers, the majority of whom live at the poverty level.
   ``Those of us who are here, those of us who were born here, feel
we are not sharing in the American dream,'' said Angel A.
Amy-Moreno, a professor and historian and a member of the local
Congress chapter.
   ``Some of us live in the worst conditions in this country,'' she
said.
   Torres and Amy-Moreno were among the Puerto Rican leaders who
addressed the start of the fifth National Puerto Rican convention
Wednesday.
   The majority of Puerto Ricans in the United States live in New
York City or nearby. Other large groups are concentrated in New
Jersey, Illinois, California, Connecticut and Massachusetts.
   The report contained mostly discouraging news about life among
Puerto Ricans on the mainland. Among the other findings:
   _Official unemployment for Puerto Ricans is almost double that
of the general working age population in the United States.
   _AIDS is the leading cause of death among Hispanic men in New
York City, where most Puerto Ricans in the United States are found.
   _Puerto Rican families have incomes that are less than half
those of non-Hispanics.
   _Few Puerto Ricans own property and spend much of their incomes
on rent.
   _Only 53 percent of Puerto Ricans over 25 have attended four
years of college, compared with 75 percent for the U.S. general
population.
   ``Puerto Ricans, as well as other Latinos and African Americans,
have benefited the least from the expansion which has characterized
the economy since the recession of the early 1980s,'' the report
concluded.
   But Torres said there are signs of progress, some of which were
sparked by the National Congress, formed in Philadelphia in 1981.
The Congress now has more than seven chapters countrywide.
   ``We've provided a forum for Puerto Ricans to discuss the most
pressing problems facing the community and how to deal with them,''
said Torres.
   Puerto Ricans in this country have tried to better their lot
with labor, convention officials said. Many Puerto Rican workers at
a major Wall Street firm have joined with other minority employees
to demand equal opportunity and more hiring of Hispanics.
   The United Third Bridge, a group of Puerto Rican workers within
Local 3 of the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, has
taken the union to court for failing to defend them against
discrimination in construction.
</TEXT>
