<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1919EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-StudentAthletes     05-24 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Student Athletes,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Would Require Colleges To Say How Many Athletes Graduate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill requiring colleges to disclose how many
of their athletes graduate could improve education standards for
student athletes, a congressman and former pro basketball player
said Wednesday.
   Rep. Tom McMillen, D-Md., a sponsor of the ``Student-Athlete
Right to Know Act,'' called the effort ``a relatively innocuous
consumer information bill, designed to provide the students and
parents with valuable information about the school they are
considering.''
   McMillen played for the University of Maryland before playing
professionally with the Atlanta Hawks and Washington Bullets.
   In testimony submitted to a House subcommittee, he said the
disclosure bill itself will not ensure that athletes get the
education they deserve but could help ``to move us back towards the
primary goal of educating young people and to developing basic
standards for student-athletes.''
   The right-to-know measure, sponsored by former New York Knicks
star Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., in the Senate, would require
schools receiving federal assistance to report on the graduation
rates of their athletic-scholarship recipients and compare their
rate with that of the general student population.
   Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont., chairman of the House Education and
Labor subcommittee on postsecondary education, heard testimony on
the bill last week and again at the hearing Wednesday.
   The Rev. Timothy Healy, president of Georgetown University in
Washington, offered a number of recommendations including reducing
the college basketball season by five weeks and not allowing
freshmen to play.
   He said every school should publish graduation rates and require
that graduation rates for athletic teams must be equivalent to
rates for the entire school. Healy also recommended consideration
of another idea, to limit athletic scholarships based on players'
failure to graduate.
   ``Anything would be better than we have today,'' Healy said in
his testimony.
   The chancellor of the University of Nebraska at Lincoln, Martin
Massengale, said the staff of the National Collegiate Athletic
Association has drafted its own version of right-to-know
legislation. He said NCAA members will consider it at a convention
in January.
   There are several serious issues to be resolved, including which
institutions should have to report and what type of data they need
to submit and to whom, Massengale said in testimony submitted to
the House panel.
   He also said it is unclear whether data should be reported by
race ``as suggested in the Bradley-McMillen bill,'' adding many
institutions would find such a requirement offensive, and in some
cases it night cause legal problems.
   ``These are all legitimate questions, even for one who believes
in the fundamental concept of disclosure,'' Massengale said.
</TEXT>
