<FIRST>r w AM-FuelEconomy 1stLd-Writethru a0691 05-24 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fuel Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>NHTSA Rejects Bid for Tightening of 1989 Gas-Mileage Standard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update, inserts graf 6, ``If the,'' with reax; deletes pvs
graf 4, bgng ``Neither the,'' as outdated by this lead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fuel-economy standard for 1989 passenger
cars will remain at 26.5 miles per gallon, the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration said Wednesday in rejecting a
petition for reconsideration of the regulation.
   The petition filed by two Washington-based advocacy groups, the
Center for Auto Safety and Public Citizen, asked NHTSA to allow the
corporate average fuel economy standard to revert to 27.5 mpg, the
level set by a 1975 law intended to reduce dependence on foreign
oil.
   The advocacy groups failed to make a case that ``the standard
should have been set at a level other than 26.5 mpg,'' NHTSA's
order said.
   In their petition, the organizations argued that contrary to
NHTSA's findings, Congress' fuel-economy goals remaned unmet. The
organizations said NHTSA erred in determining that General Motors
Corp., the world's largest automaker, could only meet at 26.5 mpg
standard and in blaming declining GM sales on the fuel-economy
standards.
   The petition put NHTSA in a position of defending the 26.5 mpg
fuel-economy standard after Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner
said last week he would allow the standard to revert to 27.5 mpg
for the 1990 model year. Skinner said then he hoped the stiffer
standard would encourage the automakers to make more efficient cars.
   ``If the agency had applied the same standards to 1989 as it did
to 1990, it would have kept the standard at 27.5 mpg,'' said
Clarence Ditlow, director of the Center for Auto Safety. ``Today's
decision is simply inconsistent with last week's decision by
Secretary Skinner. One of the two decisions has to be wrong, and
we're sure Secretary Skinner was wrong this week and right last
week.''
   The fuel economy standards require each automaker's fleet of
passenger cars, on average, to attain a certain gas mileage.
   The 1975 law set a gradually rising scale of fuel economy that
must be met, with the goal of reaching 27.5 mpg, but also allowed
NHTSA's parent agency, the Transportation Department, to loosen the
minimum standard through administrative order to account for
economic and technical factors.
   The standard was loosened under that provision to 26 mpg in 1986
at the request of the automakers, and remained there until 1989.
</TEXT>
