<FIRST>u i AM-Nazi 1stLd-Writethru a0666 05-24 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nazi, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0666,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nazi Collaborator Arrested After Decades in Hiding</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Touvier charged with crimes
against humanity. Pick up 4th pvs, `Touvier, 74...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of France's most notorious Nazi collaborators
was arrested Wednesday and charged with crimes against humanity
after spending most of four decades in hiding.
   Paul Touvier, captured at a priory in Nice, faces trial for
crimes he allegedly committed while leading the pro-Nazi French
militia in Lyon, where he worked closely with Gestapo chief Klaus
Barbie.
   Touvier, 74, was captured Wednesday morning in Nice and flown to
Paris for questioning, police said. He was taken in a guarded fire
department ambulance to the Palais de Justice where he was charged,
and then transferred to a prison in Fresnes, south of the capital.
   The French news agency Agence France-Presse, quoting neighbors
who witnessed the arrest, said Touvier was taken into custody at
St. Francis Priory, which is run by followers of excommunicated
Monsignor Marcel Lefevbre. The Vatican expelled the right-wing
fundamentalist priest last year after a long battle over church
doctrine.
   ``We see this with great satisfaction,'' said Beate Klarsfeld,
France's best-known Nazi hunter. ``It's a great bravo for French
justice.'' Mrs. Klarsfeld was instrumental in tracking down Barbie,
who in 1987 was sentenced to life in prison for crimes against
humanity.
   Touvier was arrested when France was liberated, but he escaped.
He was convicted twice and sentenced to death in absentia for
executing and torturing members of the resistance.
   He managed to stay hidden until the sentences against him
expired under a 20-year statute of limitations. In 1971, President
Georges Pompidou quietly pardoned Touvier.
   New charges were raised two years later, however, and the
collaborator again became a fugitive.
   Touvier's protection during the early postwar period by senior
members of the Roman Catholic hierarchy has been extensively
documented, and historian Henri Amouroux said his trial would bring
out ``the role the church played.'' Monsignor Charles Duquaire, who
was private secretary to the archbishop of Lyon during the
occupation, urged Pompidou to pardon Touvier, who had lived in a
succession of monasteries in the southern French region.
   One account, by the Lyon journalist and historian Pierre
Merindol, said Duquaire was fulfilling a pledge in return for
Touvier securing the release of 42 hostages about to be shot by the
Germans in retaliation for an act of sabotage.
   When asked to comment on the arrest, Cardinal Albert Decourtray,
current archbishop of Lyon, said he hoped ``the respect for others
will prevail over lies and settling of accounts.''
   Written accounts suggest Touvier could expose prominent
Frenchmen as collaborators. Similar fears were expressed before
Barbie's trial, but no revelations were made.
   The new arrest warrant against Touvier lists six charges,
including the killing of Victor Basch, president of France's League
for Human Rights.
   Investigators determined that when Basch, 81, and his wife, were
arrested by Touvier's militiamen in January 1944 they were ``judged
too old to be deported and they were killed on the spot.''
   A death notice for Touvier was published in a Grenoble newspaper
in 1984, giving thanks in the name of his family for expressions of
sympathy. It was never explained, and there were frequent reports
afterward that Touvier was seen in monasteries in France, Italy or
Switzerland.
   Touvier's brother Andre, 61, said in an interview he was
surprised by the arrest because he had been ``99 percent''
convinced his brother was dead.
   ``In a certain sense, his arrest is a good thing. The inquiry
will show, even if he is not lily-white, that people have
exaggerated and made a mythical figure out of him,'' Andre Touvier
said.
   Robert Nant, who was an 18-year-old resistance fighter when he
says he was captured by the militia and tortured by Touvier for 10
days in May 1944, said the collaborator should be brought to trial.
   ``He's 74 years old, time passes, but Touvier still has an
account to settle with justice today,'' Nant said.
</TEXT>
