<FIRST>r w AM-Nitze-Arms     05-24 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nitze-Arms,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nitze Says His Arms Control Plan Was Rejected</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief arms control negotiator under
President Reagan said Wednesday he was rebuffed in January when he
urged the Bush administration to negotiate cuts in short-range
nuclear missiles with the Soviets.
   ``It was my view that it is important to capture, to the extent
that you can, the political initiative,'' said Paul H. Nitze, who
left office May 2.
   President Bush, headed for a summit of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization next Monday, is trying to end an alliance crisis
involving the short-range missiles.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, whose party faces tough
elections next year, wants Bush to open immediate negotiations, but
Bush is pressing Kohl to agree to modernize the existing 88 Lance
missile launchers in Europe.
   Nitze, in a speech at the National Press Club, said Bush's
course would gain no advantage for the United States and was
putting the Germans in an impossible political position.
   ``It appeared to me that we could well take the iniative and
propose to Kohl that we ask the Soviets to join us in prompt
neogiatiations on short-range missiles,'' said Nitze.
   ``This propsal would be contingent on the German government
agreeing to adhere to its previous position opposing the total
elimination of short-range missiles, and to support us as we
attempted to secure equal ceilings on such missiles to a level
around 200 or 300 such missiles on each side,'' he said.
   ``I thought that the time was right in January to take this
iniative to (Secretary of State James A.) Baker. But it was
rejected by him,'' said Nitze.
   ``The Soviet Union has a great superiority in such weapons
today. And without an agreement providing for one-sided reductions
by the U.S.S.R. to U.S. levels, it will be able to maintain such
superiority indefinitely in the future,'' Nitze said.
   ``An exchange betweeen us in short-range missiles would be
totally and one-sidely destructive for ourselves and our allies,
primarily the Germans,'' he said.
   ``If the point is our ability to be able to initiate a nuclear
attack regardless of its effectiveness, we have in the European
area a variety of nuclear weapons of every significant range. The
true deterrent to Soviet attack in Europe on ourselves or our
allies must be the great power and diversity of our strategic
nuclear forces deployed at sea or based in the United States,'' he
said.
   Nitze said he anticipates an agreement will be worked out. ``In
the past 40 years, NATO has always appeared to be in more or less
in dissarray,'' he said.
   ``The manifest and continuing threat from the East, and the
essential reality of the U.S. contribution to both the conventional
and the nuclear deterrrence to that threat were evident and tended
to overcome the centrifugal forces in the alliance in every crisis
situation,'' he said.
   ``The view that the threat from the East has diminished to the
unimportant is already widespread. Few credit that shift to the
continuing strength and unity of NATO when that was needed,'' Nitze
said.
</TEXT>
