<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1947EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-24 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEDLEY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is such a thing as a free lunch in
this industrial Miami suburb. There also are free school buses,
free van trips, free boat rides, free housekeepers _ the list goes
on and on.
   In fact, with 120 full- and part-time employees serving Medley's
547 residents, the townfolk pay nothing for just about all their
municipal services.
   Their secret? It's no secret, really. Medley has a tax base that
would be the envy of any town: three businesses for every two
residents.
   Businesses provide 98 percent of Medley's tax earnings,
according to Mayor Tobie Wilson. An estimated $400,000 a year, or
10 percent of the annual budget, goes into free services for
residents.
   All residents in Medley, a dusty town jammed against the
Everglades, are entitled to a free hot lunch every weekday. One
resident, Alvaro Arango, has accepted the offer every weekday for
the past eight years.
   In addition to the free school bus rides for children and free
van rides to the supermarket and beauty parlor, there are free car
trips to the doctor's office and free pickup of medical
prescriptions.
   Residents get free boat rides on the Miami River. They pay
nothing to swim in the town pool, lift weights in the gym, even
receive health care and housekeepers in their homes. Kids can play
video games all day long at the town's game room and never spend a
quarter.
   And more services are on the way. Medley officials are planning
to set up low-cost housing for less-privileged residents. Their
efforts will be reported in the town's free weekly newspaper,
delivered door to door.
   ``There's a lot of local stuff in there the people like to
read,'' Wilson said. ``If people know what's going on, they usually
complain less.''
   Did he say complain?
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida legislators may be winning the
war on taxes during the 1989 session, but many admit they're losing
the battle of the bulge.
   With the Legislature approaching its scheduled June 2 deadline,
the last two months of wining and dining is taking a heavy toll on
waistlines, House and Senate members say.
   An 18-page legislative social calendar shows lawmakers have as
many as eight chances a night for free chow, sponsored by groups
ranging from the Florida Funeral Directors Association to the
state's School Food Service Association.
   ``I usually lose weight when I'm up here, but not this year,''
said Sen. William ``Doc'' Myers, who, at 370 pounds, is the largest
person in either body of the Legislature.
   Rep. Jack Tobin, who dropped 80 pounds two years ago, has swung
back up to 250 pounds.
   ``There's just an awful lot of receptions and cocktail
parties,'' Tobin said. ``When you go, you indulge.''
</TEXT>
