<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WarPowers     05-24 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-War Powers,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Urge Rewriting of War Powers Act</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress must change the War Powers Act,
witnesses told a House panel Wednesday with some suggesting
measures to strengthen consultations between the executive and
legislative branches and others calling for repeal of the
Vietnam-era law.
   Rep. Larry J. Hopkins, R-Ky., told the House Armed Services
subcommittee on investigations that the law is flawed, but he
cautioned against repealing it.
   ``We have an obligation as lawmakers ... when we see something
wrong to right it, when something is broken, fix it,'' said
Hopkins, the ranking Republican on the panel.
   Enacted in 1973 over the veto of then-President Nixon, the law
requires a presidential report to Congress when U.S. military
personnel are sent into situations of ``imminent hostilities.''
Under some instances, the troops must be withdrawn after 60 or 90
days unless Congress votes to allow them to remain.
   Hopkins said the United States was fortunate that the War Powers
Act was not invoked in the Persian Gulf in 1987 when former
President Reagan allowed Kuwaiti-owned oil tankers to sail under
the American flag and sent U.S. Navy warships to protect them from
Iranian attack.
   According to Hopkins, Iran could have taken advantage of the
limited time the troops could remain in the gulf.
   The Kentucky Republican mentioned legislation he introduced last
year that would remove the provision automatically withdrawing
forces and strengthen consultation between Congress and the
president.
   The measure has been referred to the subcommittee for
consideration, Hopkins said.
   Morton Halperin, who served on the National Security Council
during the Nixon administration, said he opposes the time limit of
the War Powers Act and urged Congress to alter the law.
   ``Do not be deterred by critics who say it's fine, leave it
alone,'' said Halperin, who is the director of the Washington
office of the American Civil Liberties Union.
   But Robert F. Turner of the University of Virginia Law School
called for repeal of the War Powers Act, describing the law as
``irrelevant, illegal, incompetent, irresponsible and insensitive
to the safety of U.S. Armed Forces.''
   Turner, associate director of the school's Center for Law and
National Security, said the law was unconstitutional because it
gives Congress powers delegated to the president.
   In a sharp attack, Turner also said Congress ``cannot keep
secrets. Congress cannot act with speed and dispatch,'' and should
not have the authority of the executive branch, he added.
   The War Powers Act has been the subject of an ongoing battle
between the White House and Congress. In November 1983, Congress
voted to override Nixon's veto of the bill with supporters arguing
that Nixon's Vietnam War policies were usurping Congress'
constitutional right to declare war.
   Hopkins said President Bush recently indicated to him that he
would be willing ``to open it up for some discussion'' on the War
Powers Act.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0193 </DOCNO>
