<FIRST>r a AM-EvergladesFire     05-24 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Everglades Fire,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Burning In Heart Of Everglades National Park</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hampered by rules against motorized vehicles,
firefighters are battling a fire in the heart of Everglades
National Park that has burned more than 75,000 acres in an area
that hadn't burned in 30 years, officials said Wednesday.
   ``This has become a logistical nightmare,'' said park
information officer Pat Tolle. ``You have no roads. Federal laws
prohibit the use of motorized vehicles, so this has become a major
firefighter's nightmare. What looks flat when you're sitting in
your car is the worst hiking.''
   She said about 257 people, including ``hotshot'' teams of
experienced firefighters from California, were battling the blaze,
which has charred more than 75,000 acres. They use five helicopters
to move personnel and dump water.
   South Florida has been plagued by brush and grass fires during
an unusually dry spring. Residents of metropolitan Miami have grown
accustomed to a blanket of smelly smoke that sometimes covers the
area, as it did Wednesday.
   Tolle said the Everglades blaze is typical of early rainy season
fires in the park. It was sparked by lightning May 16, and if rain
in the area had been more evenly distributed, it might not have
burned as long as it has.
   ``But rain is not yet general,'' she said. ``It may dump 6
inches here and none across the road. And the lightning struck out
to the side in areas where it's really dry.''
   The fire is roughly 30 mile southwest of downtown Miami. Ms.
Tolle said that particular area hadn't burned over for about 30
years, giving the fire plenty of fuel.
   Officials had been worried that a Miccosukee Indian village in
the park might be threatened, but the wind changed direction
Wednesday morning.
   ``The distance to the village is still some 10 to 12 miles from
the fire line itself,'' Tolle said, adding that some precautionary
steps were being taken at the village ``as much to reassure the
residents of their safety'' as to get ready for fire action.
   About 500 people live in the village along U.S. 41, known as the
Tamiami Trail, the southernmost route across the Everglades region.
   The wind shift may have been part of a weather change that could
bring firefighters some help, according to the National Weather
Service office in Coral Gables.
   ``There is a chance that we will get some rain on it and if it
does occur it will be a heavy rain,'' said meteorologist Bob Pifer,
citing a combination of unstable air and warmth.
</TEXT>
