<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-YorkshireRipper     05-24 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yorkshire Ripper,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mass Killer's Wife Awarded Record Libel Damages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury awarded the wife of British mass killer
Peter Sutcliffe, the so-called ``Yorkshire Ripper,'' a record
$942,000 in libel damages Wednesday against a satirical magazine,
Private Eye.
   Ian Hislop, editor of Private Eye, said the bimonthly may have
to fold and declared, ``If this is justice, I'm a banana.''
   Sonia Sutcliffe, whose truck driver husband was jailed for life
in 1981 for killing 13 women and attempting to kill five more,
hurried from the court with a blanket over her head.
   The 200,000-circulation Private Eye was ordered to pay the
damages for alleging that Mrs. Sutcliffe sold her story to a
tabloid newspaper for $392,000 after carousing with its reporters
at a hotel.
   ``We are totally flabbergasted,'' said Hislop. ``I think this is
very nearly the end of Private Eye. We cannot possibly pay that
amount of damages. We are going to launch a Ripper Balls Fund and
try to raise some money (for an appeal).''
   Hislop, whose gossipy, muckraking magazine is often sued,
complained the award was 100 times the average compensation paid to
three of Sutcliffe's victims.
   The award to 38-year-old Mrs. Sutcliffe, who is legally
separated from her husband, was the highest in Britain given by a
jury in a libel suit.
   The previous record was $831,000 awarded to novelist Jeffrey
Archer in 1987 against The Daily Star, a London tabloid newspaper
that said he gave money to a prostitute. He said he never met her.
   Pop singer Elton John won a record $1.84 million libel
settlement from Britain's top-selling newspaper, The Sun, last
year, but in an out-of-court settlment.
   Private Eye also will have to pay $157,000 in court costs.
   During the week-long hearing, Mrs. Sutcliffe appeared composed
as she told how she was pressured to tell her story after her
husband's arrest.
   ``The press seemed to be everywhere, banging on the doors,
shouting through the doors and banging on the windows,'' she said.
``They pushed notes through the windows offering money and shouted
`I'll top any offer.'''
   But she said she decided never to tell her story because she
believed newspapers only wanted details of her sexual relations
with her husband.
   Sutcliffe, who is held at a hospital for the criminally insane,
killed the women over five years in the north England county of
Yorkshire. At his trial, he said he believed God had ordered him to
kill prostitutes.
   Private Eye first alleged in 1981 that Mrs. Sutcliffe had made a
deal with London's Daily Mail newspaper.
   In 1983, it repeated the allegation. This year, after receiving
her libel writ, it published two more articles that Mrs. Sutcliffe
said implied that she knew about her husband's crimes.
   During the trial, Private Eye accepted there was no deal with
the Daily Mail but argued the gist of the story was true. It said
Mrs. Sutcliffe had negotiated with newspapers and was prepared to
capitalize on her husband's crimes.
   Private Eye, launched in 1961, is Britain's best-known satirical
magazine with its chatty mix of gossip and satire along with
reporting on scandal and corruption.
   Libel and legal fees have often bitten into its profits, and its
founder and first editor, Richard Ingrams, once gave his recreation
in Who's Who as ``litigation.''
   Peter Carter-Ruck, Britain's top libel lawyer, said the award
showed juries were now determined to punish newspapers and
magazines, as opposed to compensating the aggrieved.
   ``I think this award is disastrous,'' he said, adding that while
big national newspapers could afford to pay huge damages, smaller
publications will simply go out of business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0195 </DOCNO>
