<FIRST>r a AM-TankerMishap     05-24 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Mishap,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crewman Says Poor Maintenance Led To Exxon-Chartered Tanker Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minor maintenance could have prevented a
near-disaster involving an oil tanker that crashed into a concrete
catwalk and stopped just short of a major oil transfer station in
San Francisco Bay, a crewman said.
   The Exxon-chartered oil tanker, the Overseas Juneau, was laden
with 17 million gallons of crude oil at the time of the April 14
accident. The Coast Guard and state Board of Pilot Commissioners
are investigating the accident.
   Boatswain John Ballentine, 32, said Tuesday that inadequate
maintenance prevented the crew from dropping anchor and slowing the
ship as it approached a Chevron refinery at twice its normal speed.
The tanker demolished a 100-foot section of catwalk.
   ``Another 50 feet down the dock and it would have been the
largest explosion in America,'' Ballentine said outside the pilots
board meeting. He said the anchors had not been greased properly.
   Swift action steered the bow of the boat away from the loading
station and prevented a disastrous explosion inside the partially
filled tanks, he said.
   An official of the company that owns the ship denied
Ballentine's charges and said the anchors had been greased properly.
   The ship had been en route to Alaska to help replace the
crippled Exxon Valdez after it ran aground in Alaska's Prince
William Sound on March 24, spilling nearly 11 million gallons of
oil in the nation's worst spill.
   No one was injured in the April accident and the only damage to
the ship was a large amount of concrete debris on deck. The ship
continued on to Alaska and is now headed back to California.
   The board said the accident is under investigation and declined
to discuss the matter or take testimony from Ballentine. The Coast
Guard says the cause has not been determined.
   The tanker was operated by Marine Overseas Corp. of New York and
chartered by Exxon. Capt. Robert Johnston, vice president of
operations for Maritime Overseas, refused to discuss the accident
but denied Ballentine's charges of improper maintenance.
   ``I'm sure it will come out in the inquiry that the anchors were
properly greased,'' Johnston said.
   Ballentine said he quit his job aboard the ship as a result of
the accident. Johnston said the boatswain had cited a medical
reason for leaving.
   The Chevron refinery, which processes 365,000 barrels of oil a
day, is the largest plant in the San Francisco Bay area, and is
linked to a major crude oil pipeline, said Leslie Estes, of the
Central Coast Regional Studies Program.
</TEXT>
