<FIRST>r w AM-DebtApproval     05-24 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Debt Approval,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>IMF Directors Endorse Brady Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration's international debt
strategy has cleared a key hurdle by winning endorsement from the
board of directors of the International Monetary Fund, Treasury
Undersecretary David Mulford disclosed Wednesday.
   The approval was considered crucial to implementation of the
plan because both the IMF and its sister organization, the World
Bank, have key roles to play in the debt-reduction strategy, which
was unveiled by Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady on March 10.
   Under the Brady plan, Third World debtor nations could tap
resources of the IMF and the World Bank to use an incentive to
encourage commercial banks to voluntarily forgive a portion of the
$1.2 trillion in debt being carried by developing countries.
   Mulford said the IMF agreement came at a closed meeting Tuesday
of the 22 members of the IMF's board of executive directors.
   ``In general terms, the agreement for the most part endorsed the
proposals put forward by the United States,'' Mulford said.
   The Brady plan envisions both reduction of total debt and
reduction of the interest burden countries must pay each year.
   Mulford said the IMF endorsed both of these concepts. He
predicted similar approval when the top executive body of the World
Bank takes up the proposal Tuesday.
   Mulford said he hoped the agreement to go forward with the Brady
plan would help in upcoming negotiations between debtor countries
and commercial banks, in particular in the current talks with
Mexico.
   Mulford told reporters that the precise sums could not be given
on the amounts that would be available for debt relief as nobody
knows how many countries will ask for help.
   Previously, the administration has used estimates that over the
next three years the plan could wipe out about $70 billion of the
$340 billion owed by 39 of the most heavily indebted countries.
   That estimate was based on an assumption that the IMF and the
World Bank would contribute together $20 billion to $25 billion to
back the debt-reduction effort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
