<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;Ls 1stLd-Writethru a0721 05-24 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0721,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Kills GOP Bid to Dilute Key Proviso of Bush Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs on Hyde proposal before last graf pvs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Judiciary Committee on Wednesday
narrowly defeated a Republican attempt to blunt the key capital
reform in President Bush's savings and loan bailout plan.
   The amendment, which failed on a 17-17 vote, would have allowed
some institutions to use administrative appeals to delay the
imposition of tougher capital standards for up to 18 months.
   Eleven Republicans and six Democrats supported the weakening
amedment, offered by Reps. Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., and Lawrence J.
Smith, D-Fla. Three Republicans and 14 Democrats voted no. The
committee chairman, Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas, abstained.
   The vote was the latest in a series by both the Judiciary panel
and House Banking Committee in which Bush has attracted more
Democratic than Republican support for preserving his proposed
reforms.
   The banking committee adopted its version of S&amp;L legislation
three weeks ago. The full House will likely consider it early next
month, along with alternatives to specific sections passed by other
committees.
   The House bill and legislation passed by the Senate last month
then would have to be reconciled in a conference between the two
chambers before a final product can be sent to the president's desk.
   ``We're very happy to see strong capital survive,'' said
Assistant Treasury Secretary David W. Mullins, one of the
architects of Bush's S&amp;L plan. ``But we have no illusions. We'll
have to fight it again and again and again. It's like one of those
cheap movies. The monster keeps coming back,'' he said.
   The key reform in the banking panel's bill would require S&amp;L
owners to risk $3 of ``real money'' or ``tangible'' capital for
every $100 they lend. Senate-passed legislation would require $1.50
in tangible capital for every $100 lent.
   Both versions would eliminate an accounting break known as
``supervisory goodwill.'' In the early 1980s, S&amp;L regulators
authorized some healthy S&amp;Ls to count goodwill as capital in
exchange for assuming the losses of ailing institutions.
   Hyde argued that it is unfair to ``change the rules in the
middle of the game'' and said that 152 institutions would have to
be considered insolvent unless they are permitted to continue
counting goodwill as capital.
   He would have required financial regulators to conduct hearings
under the Administrative Procedures Act for S&amp;L owners who believed
the government was reneging on an agreement by changing the rules
for counting goodwill.
   ``My amendment says ... you get a chance at due process before
we hold the funeral,'' he said.
   In other action, the Judiciary committee defeated on a voice
vote an attempt by Rep. William J. Hughes, D-N.J., to halve the
maximum proposed jail term for financial institution fraud from 20
years to 10 years and to eliminate sentencing guidelines calling
for jail terms for first offenders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
