<FIRST>r w AM-ArmyHandguns     05-24 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Army Handguns,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen Vow To Investigate Army's Handgun Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two congressmen said Wednesday they would
investigate Pentagon selection of an Italian gunmaker over Smith &amp;
Wesson to make the military's chief handgun.
   The Army, for the second time in four years, selected Beretta
USA, a subsidiary of Armi Beretta SpA, over Smith &amp; Wesson of
Springfield, Mass. Sturm, Ruger &amp; Co. of Southport, Conn., also was
rejected by the Army.
   The Army on Monday said sample weapons submitted for testing by
Smith &amp; Wesson and Sturm, Ruger failed to meet minimum performance
requirements and the Beretta USA M-9 tested significantly better.
   ``I cannot say at this time that the tests were rigged, but my
hunting dog nose tells me that something might be amiss here,''
said Rep. Silvio O. Conte, R-Mass. ``I will not give up until I am
certain Smith &amp; Wesson is given a fair shake.''
   Rep. Richard Neal, D-Mass, said he and Conte ``will scrutinize
every aspect of this competition. If there is a hint of any
irregularity, we'll insist on a full explanation and appropriate
corrective action.''
   ``We have not seen the test results yet, but I will insist upon
a full accounting by the Defense Department,'' he said.
   The latest competition was ordered by Congress after Conte and
former Democratic Rep. Edward P. Boland of Springfield, complained
that Beretta was unfairly awarded a contract in 1985 to build its
M-9 pistol as the replacement for the military's venerable Colt .45.
   The General Accounting Office agreed with the lawmakers that
Smith &amp; Wesson was improperly shut out of the final bidding process
for the original $75 million contract to build 315,000 pistols.
   The new contract competition is worth $9.9 million to build
56,705 guns, the Army said.
   ``The General Accounting Office on two separate occasions found
against the Army in favor of Smith &amp; Wesson,'' Conte said. ``The
(House) Government Operations Committee agreed that Smith &amp; Wesson
has previously been treated unfairly in technical
disqualifications, and here we are again. You can rest assured that
I will look into every aspect of this evaluation.''
   The Army, in its statement Monday, did not specify the problems
with the Smith &amp; Wesson or Sturm Ruger guns. Army officials said
they would brief the companies Thursday at the Aberdeen (Md.)
Proving Ground.
   The contract award comes in the wake of a series of problems
with the 140,000 Beretta pistols already delivered.
   Beretta, which opeates a plant in Accokeek, Md., where the guns
are assembled, agreed last summer to suspend deliveries while it
corrected a problem that led to a dangerous cracking of the gun's
chamber slide. Deliveries resumed earlier this month, according to
Beretta officials.
   The Army ordered reduced usage of the guns after a fifth
accident in which a chamber slide cracked, sending fragments toward
the shooter's chest.
   In March, the Navy said its SEAL commando forces would not
switch to the Beretta 9mm because of the slide failures.
</TEXT>
