<FIRST>u w AM-US-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0679 05-24 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0679,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker to Meet with South African Envoy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS reference to Namibia, making it Angola, 3rd graf, ``A
senior''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a further signal of improving relations,
Secretary of State James A. Baker III will meet in Rome this
weekend with South African Foreign Minister Roelof Botha, the State
Department said Wednesday.
   The meeting is part of an expansion of contacts planned by Bush
administration officials with leading South Africans both in and
out of government.
   A senior U.S. official, asking not to be identified, said the
mood between the two countries has improved partly as a result of
the U.S.-mediated agreement last December under which Cuba agreed
to the phased withdrawal of its forces from Angola and South Africa
consented to end its colonial role in Namibia.
   ``There is a greater atmosphere of confidence,'' the official
said.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler disclosed that
Baker will meet with Botha during a stopover in Rome prior to
attending the NATO summit meeting in Brussels.
   Last week, President Bush met with three anti-apartheid
activists, including Nobel Peace Prize winner Archbishop Desmond
Tutu. The administration also is planning to invite the leader of
South Africa's ruling National Party, F. W. de Klerk. Regular
meetings also are planned with representatives of the country's
main anti-apartheid group, the African National Congress.
   The new assistant secretary for African affairs, Herman Cohen,
hopes to visit South Africa within the next two months.
   The goal of the intensified U.S. diplomacy is to determine
whether the United States can help promote meaningful discussions
among South Africans toward the establishment of a system that will
give the majority black population political rights for the first
time.
   ``To the extent that the two sides can get together on a
framework, so much the better,'' a U.S. official said.
   He added that the December agreement negotiated by Cohen's
predecessor, Chester Crocker, is progressing well, with the
independence process in Namibia moving ahead and the Cuban troop
withdrawal being carried out on schedule.
   There are also inconclusive signs that Angola's Marxist
government may be interested for the first time in negotiating an
end to the 14-year civil war with U.S.-backed rebels.
   U.S.-South African relations were set back sharply by the
economic sanctions Congress imposed in 1986 and officials
acknowledged that the relationship is still ``traumatized'' by that
action.
   President Reagan vetoed the sanctions but was overridden by
Congress.
</TEXT>
