<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-NATO     05-24 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-NATO,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Time Running Out' As Bush Sends New Response to West Germans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has sent a new letter to the
West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl on the short-range missile
dispute in NATO as Bush's national security adviser said Wednesday
that ``time is running out'' for resolving the rift in the alliance.
   Bush sent the letter to Kohl late Tuesday evening and the German
leader intends to respond to the U.S. proposal ``as soon as
possible,'' a diplomatic source in Washington said.
   Officials on both sides of the Atlantic have been scrambling to
heal the rift in advance of a summit meeting of leaders of the 16
NATO countries in Brussels, Belgium, next week.
   The disagreement may continue to fester until the meeting, which
is Bush's first as the leader of the Western alliance and is
designed to mark the 40th anniversary of the founding of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   The leaders will gather amid a series of arms control proposals
by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev that have enticed many in
Western Europe to question the need for updating NATO's nuclear
stockpile.
   Bush's national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft, commented to
reporters as the president delivered the commencement address at
the Coast Guard Academy in New London, Conn.
   Asked if there had been progress in negotiations with the West
Germans, Scowcroft responded, ``Not measureably.''
   Queried whether that meant that the president would travel to
the summit without a solution, he said, ``Time is running out.''
   The national security adviser added that both sides were ``still
talking'' and that the United States had not given up on finding a
way out of the problem.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler confirmed
that the United States had responded to the West Germans, but she
refused to give any details of the U.S. reply.
   ``We're not negotiating in public; I just can't get into the
specifics,'' she said.
   She repeated Secretary of State James A. Baker III's expression
that the United States is ``hopeful'' that a compromise can be
reached prior to the summit meeting in Brussels.
   The controversy stems from a push by the United States and
Britain to update aging Lance surface-to-surface nuclear missiles,
most of which are based in West Germany.
   Public opinion in West Germany has turned against such a move,
and Kohl has pressed for an early round of U.S.-Soviet talks on the
missile, in part as a means of shoring up his domestic political
position.
   Baker told West German Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg last
week that the United States accepted the idea of such negotiations
in principle, but has opposed opening any such talks until Warsaw
Pact forces are reduced. The Americans have also demanded that the
Germans oppose the total elimination of the weapons.
   If the short-range Lances were modernized, their range would be
tripled to just below 300 miles. All U.S. and Soviet missiles with
ranges between 300 and 3,000 miles were banned under a 1987 treaty.
   The U.S.-built Lances now can hit targets from about 75 miles
away.
</TEXT>
