<FIRST>r i AM-SovietIdeology     05-24 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Ideology,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Ideology Chief Speaks About Multiparty System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vadim Medvedev, the Kremlin's top ideologist, was
quoted Wednesday as saying he saw no contradiction between a
multiparty system and a communist state, but that the Soviet Union
is not ready for such a system.
   Medvedev, secretary for ideology in the Soviet Communist Party
Central Committee, said in an interview in the daily Le Monde it
was necessary ``to maintain the force for integration that the
(Communist) party represents in the present state of development,
in the extreme complexity and diversity of perestroika.''
   Perestroika, the Russian word for restructuring, has been the
hallmark of the rule of Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Medvedev was quoted as saying that ``efforts to weaken'' the
party ``by putting other political forces and organizations up
against it'' were aimed at ``blocking perestroika.''
   Asked why Soviet television did not at first report on the
massive demonstrations in Tiananmen Square during Gorbachev's visit
to Beijing, Medvedev said the Soviets did not want to give the
impression they were ``trying to influence internal events in the
host country.''
   On the process of ``diversification'' underway in such East bloc
nations as Poland and Hungary, Medvedev was quoted as saying that
Moscow approved of what was taking place and was encouraging the
changes.
   ``We consider it irreversible,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Medvedev also said he believed in the market as a factor in the
economy and that socialist states should not reject lessons learned
from capitalism just because it was another system.
   He refused to discuss rivalries within the ruling Politburo,
saying only that ``lively discussions'' took place. He denied there
were different factions within the Politburo.
</TEXT>
