<FIRST>r a AM-LukensTrial     05-24 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lukens Trial,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Girl Details Alleged Sexual Encounter With Congressman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents. Language of 14th graf, `Lukens then ...,' may
be offensive to some readers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who says she had sex with U.S.
Rep. Donald Lukens testified Wednesday that the congressman paid
her $40 and gave her a birthday gift after going to bed with him
last year.
   Rosie Coffman said Lukens knew she was not 19, as she had
professed to be. She was 16 at the time.
   ``When I told him that I was 19, he looked and sort of laughed
and said, `No, not really,''' Ms. Coffman testified on the third
day of Lukens' trial.
   The 58-year-old Republican, who is divorced, is charged with
contributing to the unruliness or delinquency of a minor, stemming
from the alleged meeting at his Columbus apartment last November.
   If convicted of the misdemeanor, Lukens could be sentenced to
180 days in jail and fined $1,000.
   He appeared agitated when Ms. Coffman described in graphic
detail a sexual encounter that she said she had with Lukens. At one
point, he clenched both fists and hit his knees. He repeatedly
shook his head and scowled.
   Ms. Coffman said she first met Lukens in 1985 and did not see
him again until the night of Nov. 6, 1988, when she and a friend,
Michelle Foster, visited him at Ms. Foster's suggestion. Ms. Foster
was 19.
   Lukens greeted the two at the door wearing boxer shorts, and
gave Ms. Coffman a $20 bill to pay their cab driver, Ms. Coffman
said. She said Lukens recognized her but not Ms. Foster.
   Ms. Coffman said took them to a downstairs guest room.
   ``He told us to get undressed and put on ... two black robes,''
Ms. Coffman said. She asked him why they could not wear two white
robes she saw in the room.
   ``He said those were for white people ... other kind of
people,'' she said.
   Ms. Coffman and Ms. Foster are black. Lukens is white.
   Ms. Coffman testified that she and Ms. Foster got into bed with
Lukens. ``He started talking nasty,'' she said.
   Lukens then sent Ms. Foster out of the room, Ms. Coffman said.
She testified that she then performed oral sex on Lukens and had
intercourse with him twice.
   She said Lukens gave her two $20 bills and paid Ms. Foster $30.
   Ms. Coffman said Lukens also gave her a glass of brandy and two
gifts _ a pink lace fan and a silver pillbox _ and gave Ms. Foster
a bottle of perfume and a diamond pendant.
   Ms. Coffman testified later in the day that she went to Lukens'
apartment to talk to him about how she felt about him in 1985, when
she first met the congressman. A court order has prevented either
side from examining what happened in 1985 at length. Testimony has
only included allegations that Lukens gave her alcohol at that time.
   She said that ``when I got to the door (and made) eye contact, I
felt the same feeling I had inside for him from the first time I
was over there. It was like, should I say love and hate?''
   Earlier Wednesday, defense attorney Thomas Tyack attacked the
testimony of the girl's mother, Anna Coffman, and tried to depict
her as continually unemployed and desperate for notoriety and money.
   WSYX-TV broadcast on Feb. 1 a secretly recorded videotape that
apparently shows Lukens offering Mrs. Coffman a government job
after she asked him why he was ``messing around'' with her
daughter. The Nov. 11, 1988, meeting at a Columbus restaurant was
recorded by the station.
   WSYX reporter Ted Hart, who arranged the videotaping of the
meeting, testified Wednesday he never heard Mrs. Coffman ask Lukens
for money, but said he heard Lukens offer to help her find a job
after she explained that her daughter was underage.
</TEXT>
