<FIRST>r a AM-McCoyExecution     05-24 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McCoy Execution,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatively Speedy Execution Worries Death Row Inmates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas death row inmates expressed worry
Wednesday after a fellow prisoner was executed for a 1981
abduction, rape and slaying because his case sailed through appeals
courts without even a temporary stay.
   Stephen McCoy, a 40-year-old electrician from Houston, was
pronounced dead at 12:25 a.m. Wednesday, seven minutes after a
lethal mixture of drugs was injected into his arms.
   McCoy lost a final appeal late Tuesday when the U.S. Supreme
Court voted 5-4 to deny a stay without further comment. The appeal
was McCoy's first to reach the high court and it has been routine
for initial appeals to merit at least one reprieve.
   ``The significance of this is the courts very clearly are
indicating impatience with dilatory tactics within the process and
they intend to expedite the process,'' said state Attorney General
Jim Mattox, who witnessed the execution and predicted the pace of
executions in Texas would accelerate.
   McCoy's execution was the 31st in Texas and the 110th in the
nation since the 1976 U.S. Supreme Court ruling allowing states to
resume use of the death penalty. Texas has had the most executions,
followed by Florida with 21 and Louisiana with 18.
   ``We anticipate the length between the time of conviction and
execution will grow shorter,'' Mattox said. ``Legitimate issues
(for appeals) are getting fewer and fewer.''
   ``Things never look good for death row inmates,'' condemned
prisoner Lester Bower said Wednesday. ``Things look especially poor
now. We're running out of generic issues to bring to the Supreme
Court.''
   ``The fact he could not (get a stay) changes the seriousness of
everyone,'' added Jim Vanderbilt, another inmate.
   ``They sure zipped it through fast,'' said prisoner James
Beathard. ``It's a bad precedent.''
   McCoy was convicted in the murder of Cynthia Johnson, 18, who
was abducted by McCoy and two other men from her car after it broke
down on a Houston freeway as she was returning home from a New
Year's Eve party.
   McCoy, who had insisted he was in another room when the woman
was slain, made no final statement. He smiled briefly to four
friends he invited to the execution. He coughed and his chest
heaved five times as the drugs began to take effect, then uttered
two long, low groans before he stopped breathing.
</TEXT>
