<FIRST>r i AM-UN-US-Cuba     05-24 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-US-Cuba,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN to Hold Crime Conference in Cuba Over US Objections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. Economic and Social Council voted
Wednesday to hold an anti-crime conference in Cuba. The United
States cast the only dissenting vote and has said it would boycott
the meeting.
   Fifty-one of the 54 members of the council, one of the six major
U.N. organs, voted to hold the conference in Cuba. Two delegations
were absent.
   The U.N. Congress on the Prevention of Crime and the Treatment
of Offenders is to begin Aug. 27, 1990, with the purpose of
promoting cooperation against all forms of crime.
   Arthur Zegelbone, a spokesman for the U.S. Mission, said
American opposition was based partly on Cuba's failure to sign the
Montreal and Hague conventions against aircraft hijackings. He said
Washington also was concerned about human rights violations in Cuba.
   A U.N. human rights report last year said Fidel Castro's
government holds political prisoners and commits human rights
abuses, mainly against religious groups.
   The U.N. observers found far fewer prisoners than Washington had
said, however, and Cuba claimed to be vindicated by the report.
   Amnesty International, a human rights organization based in
London, said Cuba held at least 600 such prisoners at the end of
1987.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering has said the United States
would boycott an anti-crime conference in Havana.
   The Economic and Social Council coordinates economic and social
work of the United Nations and its specialized agencies.
</TEXT>
