<FIRST>r a AM-EtanAnniversary     05-24 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Etan Anniversary,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Etan Patz Case Still Active 10 Years Later</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years ago Thursday, 6-year-old Etan Patz,
walking alone for the first time to his school bus, vanished from
the streets of lower Manhattan. Police and his parents still get
reports of purported sightings of him.
   But despite extensive publicity, a $25,000 reward and
photographs of the boy plastered all over the city, Etan has not
been found.
   The case, No. 8367, is still open, and there have been thousands
of leads, so many of them credible that investigators have been to
every state and some foreign countries.
   But ``the odds are very, very much against Etan being alive,''
said Lt. Robert Davis of the Police Department's Missing Persons
Squad.
   ``It has never happened in the history of this department that a
person missing that long has been found alive,'' said Davis, who
was one of the many officers who canvassed the Soho neighborhood
where Etan vanished.
   Most children abducted by strangers, which is what the police
believe happened to Etan, are killed ``right away,'' Davis added.
   Etan's parents, Stanley and Julie Patz, whose faces were almost
as familiar around the city as their missing son's because of their
willingness to be interviewed, said Wednesday they had decided not
to talk with reporters about the anniversary.
   The thousands of interviews the couple had granted ``have not
been helpful and it's intrusive, it cuts into our privacy,'' Patz
said.
   The Patzes have two other children, Shira, now 18, and Ari, 12.
   Patz told The Associated Press he doesn't agree with the police.
``I think he's still alive, but there's not much evidence to
support that, it's an article of faith,'' he said.
   Davis said his squad still receives ``two to three sightings a
week on Etan,'' from all over the country. The lieutenant predicted
his squad will get more calls because of news stories about the
anniversary.
   The Patz family also receives calls from cranks and psychics
about their son. ``There's a hard core out there,'' Patz sighed.
   ``We live with it every day, this is just a worse week than
others,'' he added. The parents speak weekly with Detective Robert
Shaw, who handles the case, police said.
   Interest in the case still remains strong. ``It has captured the
public's imagination like no other case,'' said Davis.
   When asked why, he shook his head. ``If I could answer that, I
think I could solve the case,'' he said.
</TEXT>
