<DOCNO> AP890524-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DroughtAction     05-24 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought Action,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Programs Expanded in Kan., Neb., Iowa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal programs allowing livestock grazing
and hay cutting on land taken out of production under this year's
crop acreage programs have been expanded in Kansas, Nebraska and
Iowa, Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter announced Wednesday.
   ``I'm encouraged by the rain that has fallen in the Midwestern
and Great Plains growing areas in the past week,'' Yeutter said.
``In many places the drought has broken. However, the additional
relief actions taken today will help reduce livestock sell-offs in
areas where haying and grazing conditions are still not adequate.''
   Yeutter said he will allow statewide emergency haying and
grazing of cropland normally held out of production under 1989
commodity programs in states where 75 percent of the counties have
been designated as already eligible for haying and grazing.
   States which meet that requirement are Kansas, Nebraska and
Iowa, he said. Other states will be added when they meet the 75
percent criterion. Yeutter also relaxed the department's forage
sales policy so producers in eligible counties can sell forage from
the conservation land at full market prices instead of at levels
only to recover harvest costs, which is the current policy.
   ``Rain is predicted for much of the Midwest and Great Plains
areas in the next several days, which could prove to be extremely
beneficial for those growing areas,'' he said. ``The USDA drought
task force will continue to monitor ... situations on a daily basis
and forward additional recommendations to me if and when the
situation warrants it.''
   In his latest actions, Yeutter stopped short of approving
requests from some farm leaders who wanted him to open up for
haying and grazing millions of acres taken from production under
the 10-year Conservation Program. Dozens of states were made
eligible to cut hay from CRP land in last year's drought, but none
has been approved for 1989.
   Kelly Shipp, Yeutter's press secretary, said: ``We have not
ruled out opening up CRP. It's just at this point we think that it
is prudent to watch that very carefully.''
   Asked if some additional states might be near the 75 percent
level required for statewide haying and grazing approval on idled
program land, Shipp said that Missouri would be the closest, with
around 50 percent or so of the counties currently eligible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
