<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Namibia     05-24 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Rebukes South Africa's Claim of Namibia Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations on Wednesday rebuked
South Africa for claiming it has primary authority over Namibia
until the country gains full independence in November.
   In a private briefing with the Security Council,
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar stressed that the United
Nations has ultimate authority over military affairs in Namibia,
diplomats who attended the meeting said on condition of anonymity.
   The U.N. chief drew a clear line between South Africa's
responsibility for local law enforcement and the Security Council's
authority over any potential call-up of the territorial militia or
the South African army, they said.
   In a letter to the United Nations, South African Foreign Minster
R.F. Botha said that responsibility for the administration of
Namibia through independence is the primary task of the South
African-appointed administrator-general. That includes
responsibility for maintaining law and order in the territory,
Botha said in his letter, dated May 19.
   South Africa agreed to a U.N.-mediated independence for Namibia
that began April 1 and is to culminate in elections Nov. 1. But the
process was interrupted the day it began when hundreds of armed
guerrillas from the South-West People's Organization crossed into
Namibia from Angola. In subsequent fighting, 316 guerrillas and 27
South African security force members were killed.
   Both said the administrator-general, Louis Pienaar, ``has the
right to use such measures and means as he would deem appropriate
to counter activities of an aggressive, violent or intimidatory
nature emanating from whatever quarter.''
   But African diplomats said they were concerned Pienaar would
feel free to recall the army to handle any new incursions by SWAPO,
the main rebel group in the territory.
   Under accords signed in December by South Africa, Cuba and
Angola, Pretoria pledged to cooperate with the plan to make Namibia
an independent black majority-ruled nation.
   Under the U.N. timetable, the 50,000 South African soldiers in
Namibia were to withdraw by July 1, leaving only 1,500 troopers
confined to base. South Africa's U.N. Mission said Wednesday that
their numbers in Namibia will be cut to 1,500 a week before the
July 1 deadline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
