<DOCNO> AP890524-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1901EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-24 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms Develop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Intense thunderstorms Wednesday brought large hail and brief
heavy rain to sections of Minnesota and northern Missouri, and
temperatures climbed to record highs in Texas and Florida.
   Hail as big as golf balls fell in Minnesota at Staples, near
Olivia, at Melrose and at Pequot Lakes. In Missouri, hail the
diameter of quarters was reported near Macon.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed across Florida.
One-inch hail fell in Homestead.
   An area of low pressure off the coast of New Jersey produced
showers and some thunderstorms across eastern New York state and
New England. Rain was locally heavy with Hartford, Conn., getting
nearly 4.5 inches of rain in 24 hours. Poughkeepsie, N.Y., got 1.02
inches of rain in the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT.
   Showers fell along the northern Pacific Coast, with snow across
the Cascade Mountains.
   Temperatures climbed to 100 degrees across western Texas,
reaching a record for the date of 100 at Lubbock and 107 at
Midland. Florida also heated up with a record 94 degrees at Miami
and 95 at West Palm Beach.
   But cool air chilled the Pacific Northwest. Yakima, Wash., had a
record low of 30 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 105 at Lubbock,
Texas. Wednesday's low in the 48 contiguous states was 19 degrees
at Truckee, Calif.
   For Thursday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the Great Lakes to the Ohio Valley, the middle Mississippi
Valley, and the eastern Gulf Coast. Showers were forecast from the
Pacific Northwest into eastern Montana.
   Highs in the 50s and 60s were predicted from the central and
northern Pacific Coast to the northern and central Rockies, much of
the northern Plains, northern Minnesota and upper Michigan; in the
90s from the desert Southwest to southern New Mexico, much of Texas
and the lower Mississippi Valley, and in Florida and southern
Georgia; between 100 and 105 degrees in southwestern Texas and
southern Arizona; and generally in the 70s and 80s in the rest of
the nation.
</TEXT>
