<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i Poland-Soviets     05-24 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>Poland-Soviets,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joint Commission Reports on Hitler-Stalin Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint panel on sensitive areas in
Polish-Soviet history says the Soviet foreign minister's comments
after Poland was invaded in 1939 were ``contradictory to
international law and offensive to Poland.''
   A report called ``Origins and Beginning of World War II'' was
published Wednesday in the Communist Party newspaper Trybuna Ludu,
which said it appeared simultaneously in Pravda, the Soviet party
newspaper.
   It includes a reference to the Aug. 23, 1939, Hitler-Stalin
non-aggression pact and the secret protocol attached to it defining
how the Nazis and Soviets would divide Poland.
   World War II began with the German invasion of Poland Sept. 1,
1939, the day after the Supreme Soviet ratified the agreement.
Soviet soldiers invaded from the east Sept. 17.
   Foreign Minister Vyacheslav Molotov told the Supreme Soviet a
month later that the two armies had wiped out ``this grotesque
product of the Treaty of Versailles,'' the report said.
   Molotov's statement was ``contradictory to international law and
offensive to Poland,'' the report declared. ``The present Soviet
leadership and the scientific community of the Soviet Union
distance themselves decisively from it.''
   Western historians learned of the secret protocol from captured
Nazi documents. The report published Wednesday said the original
could not be found in Soviet or other archives.
   It also said a Soviet goverment statement handed to the Polish
ambassador Sept. 17, 1939, declaring the Polish state to be no
longer in existence was ``discrepant with the norms of
international law.''
   That statement said Soviet forces entered Poland only to protect
the inhabitants of Western Byelorussia and the Ukraine.
   ``The course of events connected with the movement of the Red
Army in September 1939 to the west requires more detailed
historical studies,'' the joint report said.
   Wojciech Ziembinski, a Roman Catholic journalist and historian,
said the report only complicates the process of resolving
historical discrepancies.
   ``This does not satisfy the Polish nation in any case and
certainly does not satisfy Polish historians. This document will
receive my reply, although I don't know how it will be with the
censorship,'' said Ziembinski, who has written extensively on
Polish-Soviet relations in World War II.
   Two years ago, authorities banned an article by Ziembinski on
Nazi-Soviet cooperation in partitioning Poland.
   For Poles, the sorest points of mutual history are the murder of
more than 4,000 Polish officers in the Katyn Forest and the
internment of at least 10,000 more in Soviet prison camps.
   Official Polish and Soviet histories say the Nazis killed the
officers in 1941, but many Poles and Western historians believe the
Soviets killed them in 1940.
   The commission, established two years ago, has yet to deliver
its findings on the Katyn massacre, but a Soviet popular magazine
recently raised the possibility that the Soviets were responsible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
