<FIRST>r a AM-RetardedGirl-Assault     05-24 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Retarded Girl-Assault,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Charged with Sexual Assault on Mentally Retarded Girl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents 5th graf, `The girl ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five high school students were charged
Wednesday with sexually assaulting a 17-year-old mentally retarded
girl while eight other students watched, authorities said.
   Two of those arrested were charged as juveniles, and Essex
County Prosecutor Herbert Tate said additional arrests were
possible.
   ``We are satisfied that this was a non-consensual sexual assault
by these five males against this young woman,'' Tate said at a news
conference. ``She didn't understand the nature and quality of her
actions.''
   Tate said the hour-long assault took place March 1 after the
students met the girl in a Glen Ridge park and brought her to the
nearby home of two of those charged, 18-year-old twins Kevin and
Kyle Scherzer, whose parents were away.
   The girl was assaulted with a small baseball bat and a
broomstick in the Scherzer basement, Tate said. There was no sexual
intercourse, he said.
   Kevin Scherzer was released on $25,000 bail, Kyle Scherzer was
freed on $20,000 bail, and Peter Quigley, 18, posted $15,000 bail.
   A 17-year-old and another student who has since turned 18 faced
similar charges, but in juvenile court, where the disposition of
their cases were not made public.
   The Scherzers are co-captains of the school football team, and
Kyle Scherzer is captain of the baseball team at Glen Ridge High
School.
   Glen Ridge is a wealthy suburban community of about 8,000 people
about five miles northwest of Newark.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
