<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1940EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0687 05-24 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0687,0788</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Shot at in Bethlehem; Palestinians Jailed for Riot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to add details, two attacks on settlers.
Pick up 10th pvs, `The army...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers reported they were fired at Wednesday
in Bethlehem, and five Palestinians were sentenced to prison for
their roles in a stone-throwing riot in which a Jewish guard
accidentally killed an Israeli teen-ager.
   The shooting attack was the second reported against Israeli
security forces in Bethlehem in two days. No one was hurt in either
incident.
   The attacks have fueled concern over Palestinian threats to step
up violence against Israeli targets by using guns. A police van was
hit in Monday's shooting.
   Soldiers on Wednesday carried out two in a series of more than
30 pre-dawn raids on West Bank villages this week, in which dozens
of suspected Palestinian activists have been arrested.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens accused Secretary of State James A.
Baker III of harming the chances of Israel's peace plan and
breaking the practice of not speaking publicly about U.S.-Israeli
disagreements.
   In a Nablus military court, five Palestinians were convicted and
jailed in connection with the death of 15-year-old Tirza Porat.
   The death caused a furor in Israel last year because of the
conflicting explanations of what happened. Jewish settlers claimed
the girl was stoned to death or shot by Palestinians who attacked
her and fellow settlers while they were on a hike in the West Bank.
   But the army later said she was shot accidentally by an Israeli
guard who was hit by a stone during the April 6, 1988 rioting in
Beita village.
   In court, the five defendants confessed to crimes in the
incident, in which the Israelis shot and killed two Palestinians.
   Haled Hassin Abed Benishams, 19, was sentenced to four years'
jail for forcing the hikers into a violent situation and attempting
to stab the guard. His companions were sentenced to terms of
between 18 months and two years for throwing stones and threatening
the hikers.
   In El-Azariya near Jerusalem, two settlers from nearby Maaleh
Adumim were slightly injured late Wednesday night when their car
came under an Arab stone-throwing attack.
   Hundreds of angry settlers demonstrated after the attack, the
second in the area in four days. They tried to stage a revenge raid
on El-Azariya but were blocked by troops, the national news agency
Itim said.
   A firebomb was thrown at a settler's car as it passed the West
Bank village of Biddya, 16 miles east of Tel Aviv. No one was
injured, but the car was totally gutted by the flames, Israel radio
said.
   The army on Wednesday asked for an additional $233 million to
put down the 17-month uprising against Israeli occupation of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip. It is the same amount that was cut when
the military's $5.89 billion allotment was approved in February.
   In the latest army offensive, Arab reports said, troops
Wednesday deported to Jordan six women and 10 children because the
women overstayed permits allowing them to visit their Palestinian
husbands.
   They were discovered in a raid at Al Amari refugee camp. The
army confirmed several people were expelled to Jordan.
   Chris George of Montclair, N.J., an aid worker with Save the
Children, was detained for three hours because he lives near the
camp.
   George, 35, said he saw several of 300 men detained in a
schoolyard kicked and slapped, and heard screams from a bus after
soldiers took three Palestinian refugees into the vehicle.
   The army said soldiers ``had to use some force'' when one
detainee tried to grab a soldier's gun.
   Elsewhere in the territories, Israeli soldiers shot and wounded
13 people in clashes with stone-throwing Palestinians, Arab
hospital officials said.
   Since the start of the revolt, 497 Palestinians and 22 Israelis
have been killed.
   Arens returned home Wednesday from a visit to Washington and
Europe to promote an Israeli peace plan aimed at ending the
uprising.
   He told reporters he was concerned about Baker's statement
Monday urging Israel to stop building Jewish settlements in the
occupied territories and to forget about annexing them.
   ``Mr. Baker's speech may make it more difficult ... to get
European support for the plan,'' said Arens. ``The things that were
expressed publicly were harmful to the state of Israel.''
   The plan calls for electing Palestinians to negotiate with
Israel on self-rule in the territories, with talks in three years
on the final status of the occupied lands. Palestinians oppose the
plan because it does not offer independence or Israeli withdrawal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
