<DOCNO> AP890524-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SpendingBill 3rdLd-Writethru a0776 05-24 0851</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending Bill, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0776,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, Another $1.2, with House passage of $1.2
billion veterans measure; should stand</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Debates Higher Anti-Drug, Veterans Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted Wednesday to pump an extra
$822 million into federal efforts this year against illegal drugs,
but decided not to increase anti-drug spending even more by taking
money out of the Star Wars research budget.
   On a party-line 227-197 vote in which the chamber's majority
Democrats prevailed, the House finally passed a $3.7 billion
domestic spending measure for fiscal 1989 that included $822
million for anti-drug efforts. The legislation was a pared-down
version of a $4.7 billion bill the House refused to pass a month
ago.
   But on a 213-205 vote, lawmakers rejected a measure that would
have transferred to next year's drug programs any 1990 spending for
Star Wars missile defense research above this year's $3.7 billion.
President Bush has sought nearly $900 million more for Star Wars in
fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1.
   On a 409-0 vote, the House then reiterated its support for a
$1.2 billion measure for hard-pressed veterans programs, a bill
that has bounced back and forth between Congress' two chambers
because of a dispute between them over pet projects. The vote sent
the legislation back to the Senate, which has approved a smaller
version.
   The Democratic effort to bolster anti-drug initiatives was
opposed by the Bush administration and put Republicans in the
politically embarrassing position of having to vote against higher
drug spending. House Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., called
the two measures containing the drug funds ``a two-headed
malodorous swamp animal.''
   Nonetheless, GOP lawmakers argued the extra money for drug
programs could wait until next year and would add even more red ink
to the federal deficit. They also insisted that spending for
anti-missile research should not be whittled down.
   ``Nobody's opposed to putting more money for drugs,'' said
Silvio Conte of Massachusetts, ranking Republican on the House
Appropriations Committee. ``What we are opposed to is the
irresponsible way we're doing it.''
   But Democrats argued that Congress should provide money for the
Anti-Drug Abuse Act enacted last year and finance a struggle
against drug traffickers that President Bush emphasized during his
campaign last year.
   ``Let's put our resources behind this war,'' said Rep. Jim
Chapman, D-Texas.
   The domestic spending bill contained $822 million for new
prisons, extra law officers and other anti-drug initiatives. It
included $893 million for the Guaranteed Student Loan program for
college students, $423 million for state-run foster care programs,
$342 million for the costs of battling last year's Western forest
fire, and money for other programs.
   It also contains a provision that would grant the Latrobe
Brewing Co. a temporary exemption from a federal law that requires
alcoholic beverage containers to carry health warnings. Latrobe had
complained that the painted labels on the beer it brews, Rolling
Rock, would be too expensive to alter. The measure was sponsored by
Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., whose district includes Latrobe, Pa.
   On April 26, a $4.7 billion version of the measure failed to
gain House approval after lawmakers voted down a plan by Democratic
leaders to pay for the bill by cutting domestic and defense
programs by 0.57 percent.
   The separate measure to transfer spending from Star Wars to
federal drug initiatives was sponsored by a trio of Democratic
liberals: Les AuCoin of Oregon, George Miller of California and
Marty Russo of Illinois. It would freeze 1990 Star Wars spending at
the 1989 level of $3.7 billion, and transfer the amount by which
that program was to grow _ $862 million _ to next year's drug
efforts.
   Last Thursday, the House took the $1.2 billion for veterans out
of the domestic spending bill after Republicans, the Bush
administration and veterans groups complained that disputes over
other portions of the legislation were bogging down the veterans
funds.
   The House then passed the separate $1.2 billion veterans bill,
which provides money for health care, a cost-of-living benefits
increase and other programs run by the Department of Veterans
Affairs.
   Several hours later, however, the Senate approved a different
version of the bill, providing only enough money for veterans
initiatives through June 15, or about $75 million. The Senate then
left on its Memorial Day recess, which lasts until May 31.
   Senators argued that by saving most of the needed veterans money
for a later bill, they could attach to that measure spending for
programs they favor. Chairman Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., of the Senate
Appropriations Committee singled out $6.6 million needed this year
for a program that subsidizes airlines serving remote communities.
   Members of the House objected to this Wednesday, claiming that
veterans would suffer so the Senate could win approval for programs
it favors.
   ``The Senate won't release the veterans as hostages,'' Conte
said.
   The $1.2 billion for veterans was also included in the House's
larger domestic spending bill. House members argued that by putting
the money in both measures, it enhanced their bargaining position
for upcoming negotiations with the Senate on the legislation.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
