<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--MIAsIdentified     05-24 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--MIAs Identified,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Identifies Three More Sets of Vietnam Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three sets of remains from Vietnam have been
identified by the Army's Central Identification Laboratory as those
of U.S. servicemen killed in the Vietnam War, military officials
announced Wednesday.
   The remains of Air Force Col. Edward H. Johnson of Newburg,
Ore., and Capt. Randall J. Craddock of Norman, Okla., and Navy Lt.
Cmdr. William F. Coakley of Lenox, Mass., were among 38 sets of
remains repatriated by Vietnam on Dec. 15, according to the U.S.
Pacific Command.
   Seventeen sets of remains have been identified so far, and
efforts continue to positively identify the remainder, officials
said.
   Johnson and Craddock were listed as missing in action on Dec.
21, 1972. Coakley was listed as missing on Sept. 13, 1966.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
