<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2128EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-House-China     05-24 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House-China,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Takes Note of China Demonstrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday approved legislation
hailing the demonstrations in China as ``one of the most
significant movements for democracy in modern history.''
   The resolution, adopted on a voice vote, also calls on China's
government to resolve the crisis without violence and enter a
dialogue with protest leaders. It says the government should end
martial law and not arrest, jail, prosecute or otherwise punish
those who have led and taken part in the pro-democracy movement.
   In addition, the resolution seeks the immediate release of
``those Chinese citizens still imprisoned for the nonviolent
expression of their political beliefs.''
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., chief sponsor of the resolution,
said that while the United States has only limited influence on the
Chinese government, it is important for China's leaders to know
that ending the demonstrations with a violent crackdown and mass
arrests would adversely effect future U.S.-Chinese relations ``in
no small way.''
   ``Once you let the genie of freedom out of the bottle of
repression it is no easy task to get it back in again,'' Solarz
told the House.
   ``We say to the people of China, we have watched with awe and
admiration your disciplined demonstrations,'' Solarz said. ``We
call on the Chinese government to resolve this crisis in a peaceful
manner.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
