<FIRST>u w AM-House-Leadership 1stLd-Writethru a0783 05-24 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House-Leadership, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0783,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Center of Speculation as Successor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update with member saying Foley near unanimous choice as
Wright successor, subs 2nd graf previous with three grafs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley of Washington
was the center of speculation Wednesday as the odds-on favorite to
succeed Jim Wright as speaker should the embattled Texas
congressmen be forced to relinquish his leadership post.
   ``There is near unanimity of support for Tom Foley,'' said Rep.
Pat Williams, D-Mont.
   But as sources said Wright's lawyers were negotiating a deal
under which he would step down in exchange for dropping the most
serious ethics charges against him, there was no guarantee that
Foley, who has spent 25 of his 60 years in the House, would gain
the top House post without opposition.
   Foley, a former prosecutor from Spokane, emerged as a Democratic
leader in 1974 when younger House Democrats overturned the
long-standing seniority system. He became chairman of the
Agriculture Committee that year, and moved into the leadership in
1980 when he was made majority whip, the third-ranking position.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri was mentioned as one possible
Democratic oopponent for Foley, but in the supercharged political
atmosphere of a House in transition, there was no shortage of names
mentioned for other leadership posts _ vacant or otherwise.
   ``I don't think the Angel Gabriel could beat Tom Foley,'' said
one congressman who insisted on anonymity.
   But there also was talk of a ``clean sweep'' ticket that would
seek to oust all members of the current leadership, including Foley
and majority whip Tony Coelho of California.
   If Wright were to leave the speaker's post, the chamber's 260
Democrats would then choose a successor.
   Lawyers for the speaker were discussing an arrangement under
which Wright would resign his post in exchange for the ethics
committee dropping the most serious charges against him, said
sources, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   One House member who has been a Wright supporter said _ speaking
only on condition of anonymity _ that he had found no evidence on
the House floor that anyone was maneuvering overtly to garner
support for a leadership race.
   Coelho, the third-ranking member of the House leadership, has
his own ethics problems. The congressman has acknowledged that he
failed to disclose a $50,000 loan from a savings and loan in
California that he used toward purchase of $100,000 worth of junk
bonds.
   Mentioned as the possible slate to replace the current
leadership were Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri for speaker; Rep.
Ed Jenkins of Georgia for majority leader; and Rep. Bill Gray of
Pennsylvania for whip.
   Such a bid would be considered highly unlikely and none of those
named would acknowledge any such ambition.
   Gephardt, an unsuccessful candidate for the 1988 Democratic
presidential nomination, is a former chairman of the House
Democratic Caucus and is widely respected by his colleagues.
   ``I don't want to answer hypothetical questions,'' responded
Gephardt when asked if were planning to run for speaker _ a
response considered significant for its lack of a direct denial. He
was also mentioned as a potential candidate for majority leader if
Foley succeeded to the speakership.
   Gray succeeded Gephardt as caucus chairman, after serving as
chairman of the House Budget Committee. He is the only black in the
current leadership.
   Jenkins' strength in speculation was based on his Southern base.
Should Wright resign, there would be no southerner in the
leadership ranks.
   Othere names circulating as potential leadership candidates were
two powerful committee chairmen _ Rep. Dan Rostenkowski of Illinois
of the Ways and Means committee and Rep. John Dingell of Michigan,
who heads the Energy and Commerce Committee.
   If Wright were to resign, said Dingell, ``I would expect the
majority leader, Tom Foley, to be a candidate, and I support him.''
   If Foley chose not to seek the speakership, ``I would consider
my own options at the appropriate time,'' said Dingell.
   Rostenkowski was described as happy with his chairmanship and
unlikely to bid for the leadership. His background in Chicago
machine politics also was considered a detriment should he change
his mind.
</TEXT>
