<FIRST>r a AM-ElvisCologne     05-24 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elvis Cologne,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scents To Bear Trademark of `The King'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A line of Elvis Presley men's fragrances
will be launched worldwide on Jan. 8, 1991, which would have been
the late singer's 55th birthday, a cosmetics company announced
Wednesday.
   Frances Denney Companies Inc. on Tuesday acquired the licensing
rights to Elvis' name from Graceland Enterprises of Memphis, said
Frances Denney spokesman Jay Green.
   Green declined to reveal the purchase price.
   ``It's certainly one of the most recognizable names worldwide,''
Green said of the Elvis trademark. ``The name itself has its own
appeal. Also there is a trend for celebrities to lend their names
to fragrances.''
   The fragrance itself is still in development, Green said.
   Francis Denney also plans to market a women's fragrance and
cosmetic line under the Elvis name, the firm said.
   The company, which has headquarters in New York and Lynchburg,
Va., has not determined how much it will charge for the products,
but said they will be sold in department stores.
   Frances Denney makes an upscale line of fragrances, cosmetics
and skin-care products under such names as Adolfo, Hope and Albert
Nipon.
</TEXT>
