<FIRST>r a AM-People-Haley     05-24 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Haley,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Author Alex Haley Awarded Coast Guard's First Honorary Degree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Alex Haley, who began writing in
his spare time while a cook aboard Coast Guard cutters, was awarded
the Coast Guard Academy's first honorary degree at its 108th
commencement exercises Wednesday.
   President Bush, who delivered the commencement address,
conferred upon Haley, 67, the honorary degree of doctor of humane
letters.
   Haley, author of ``Roots,'' retired from the Coast Guard in 1959
after 20 years of service, leaving with the rating of chief
journalist.
   He completed two years of college before joining the Coast Guard
as a mess cook in 1939. While serving aboard various cutters during
World War II, he worked late many nights writing stories and
letters to family and friends.
   He also wrote some of his shipmates' love letters to their
girlfriends, collecting a dollar a letter.
   The Coast Guard created the journalist rating for him in 1952.
   Haley has often referred to the Coast Guard as his alma mater,
so ``we wanted to make it official,'' said Lt. Paul A. Preusse, a
Coast Guard spokesman.
   It was the first honorary degree awarded by the academy, the
school said.
   Haley said it was 50 years ago that he was heading off to the
Coast Guard to enlist, and that ``this is a marvelous way to end up
that golden anniversary.''
   A resident of Norris, Tenn., Haley sails as a passenger on
international cargo ships for three or four months each year, using
the time to write.
</TEXT>
