<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MosaicsTrial     05-24 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mosaics Trial,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkish Cyprus Enters Flap Over Mosaics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JODI PERRAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Turkish breakaway state on Cyprus
claimed ownership Wednesday of sixth century mosaics already
involved in a tug-of-war between an Indianapolis art dealer and the
Republic of Cyprus.
   The self-proclaimed Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus asked
U.S. District Court for permission to intervene in a lawsuit filed
in March by the Greek Cypriot republic and the Greek Orthodox
Church of Cyprus.
   Experts believe the case could lead to a landmark decision on
worldwide dealing in national art treasures.
   Cyprus claims art dealer Peg Goldberg of suburban Carmel
purchased the rare mosaics illegally and they should be returned to
the church.
   Turkish Cyprus asked Judge James E. Noland to delay the civil
trial, which is scheduled to begin next Tuesday. Noland did not
rule immediately.
   ``As far as we're concerned, there cannot be a full adjudication
of these issues without the input of the people who have control
over that land mass,'' said Joseph D. Youssouf, a Freehold, N.J.,
attorney representing the Turkish occupation state.
   Turks have governed the northern third of the Mediterranean
island since Turkish forces invaded in 1974. The Turkish occupation
state is not recognized by any nation except Turkey.
   ``You can say that something doesn't exist but if you can prove
that it does: has a flag, a national anthem, a population and
regulates the territory from which these four mosaics were stolen
... we are a real party in this case,'' Youssouf said.
   Goldberg, a county commissioner in Hamilton County north of
Indianapolis, bought the mosaics for $1.1 million in July 1988 from
a Turkish dealer in Switzerland. She claims she has legal title to
them under Swiss law.
   The rare mosaics are made of glass and were once part of a much
larger work in the church of Panagia Kanakaria in the Cypriot
village of Lythrankomi. The 2-foot-square mosaics depict the heads
of the Christ child, the apostles James and Matthew and an
archangel. Experts say they are among only a handful of artworks
surviving from the first centuries of Christianity.
   The Republic of Cyprus and the Church of Cyprus claim agents of
the Turkish occupation state surreptitiously ripped the mosaics
from the walls of the church in 1979.
   Court records show the mosaics were allowed to leave Cyprus
under an export document purportedly signed by Osman Orek, who
acted as prime minister for Turkish Cyprus. Orek denies signing the
document and will testify in Indianapolis if allowed to do so,
Youssouf said.
   Turkish Cyprus is asking for the return of the mosaics for
restoration in the church, unspecified damages and court costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
