<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-CarBomb     05-24 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Car Bomb,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Kills Three Police Officers, Basques Suspected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BILBAO, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Basque separatists set a car bomb
that killed three policemen and injured five other people Wednesday
in this northern Basque city, a provincial spokesman said.
   The bomb exploded as a police bomb squad inspected a stolen car
parked outside a dealership. The dealership had been damaged three
hours earlier by a small bomb, said a spokesman for the Vizcaya
province Civil Governor's office.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility. But the spokesman
said police suspected the Basque separatist group ETA, which seeks
independence for the three-province northern Basque region.
   The explosion killed two police officers and a member of a bomb
squad of the Ertzainza, the police force of the autonomous
government of the Basque region, the spokesman said. The five
injured included four police officers and a firefighter, the
spokesman said.
   The car was stolen at gunpoint late Tuesday by two men in
Amorebieta, a town 12 miles northeast of Bilbao, the spokesman said
on condition of anonymity. The car's owner was found tied to a tree
outside the town, he said.
   In its 21-year campaign for independence, ETA has claimed
responsibility for killing more than 600 people, mainly police,
military and Civil Guard officers.
   So far this year, ETA has claimed responsibility for four
killings. All occurred since April 4, when ETA ended a moratorium
on attacks on government targets after breaking off three months of
peace talks with Spanish officials.
</TEXT>
