<FIRST>r a AM-People-Simpson 1stLd-Writethru a0790 05-24 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Simpson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0790,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Community Service for O.J. Simpson, Must Also Pay $700, Continue
Counseling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf with 4 grafs to UPDATE with comment by Simpsons.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor and former football star O.J. Simpson
must pay $700, perform 120 hours of community service and continue
psychiatric counseling for his no-contest plea to wife beating, a
judge ruled Wednesday.
   Simpson, who didn't appear in court, was also placed on two
years' probation by Municipal Court Judge Ronald Schoenberg.
   Simpson, 41, entered a no-contest plea Monday to one count of
spousal battery through his attorney, Howard Weitzman. The maximum
sentence for spousal abuse is one year in jail and a $1,000 fine.
   ``O.J. just decided it was in everybody's best interest not to
contest the charges any longer,'' Weitzman said at the time. The
plea is not an admission of guilt, but allows the defendant to be
judged as guilty.
   Schoenberg ordered Simpson to perform 120 hours of community
service through the Action Bureau organization in Santa Monica, pay
a $200 fine and give $500 to a Santa Monica shelter serving
battered women.
   He was also ordered to undergo twice-weekly counseling, said
city attorney's spokesman Mike Qualls. Simpson has been undergoing
counseling since January, he said.
   Simpson, a former professional football running back who won the
Heisman Trophy while at the University of Southern California,
allegedly screamed ``I'll kill you'' as he slapped and kicked his
29-year-old wife of four years, Nicole, in a pre-dawn New Year's
Day argument.
   In a statement released Wednesday, the Simpsons said the City
Attorney's office had turned the incident into a ``media event and
public crusade at our expense and personal embarrassment.''
   The Simpsons said they wanted to ``set the record straight from
the distortions and misleading news reports that our family has
been subjected to.''
   ``Upon returning home New Year's Eve, we got into an argument
which escalated and the police were called. Fortunately, neither
one of us required medical treatment,'' the couple said. ``The very
next day, we talked about it and took steps to put this behind us.
   ``We have never been separated and our marriage is as strong as
the day we were married, if not stronger.'
</TEXT>
