<FIRST>r a AM-SwindallTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0760 05-24 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swindall Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0760,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swindall Trial Moves Closer To Opening Arguments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with juror questioning finished;
picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Defense attorneys...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The perjury trial of former U.S. Rep. Pat
Swindall moved closer to opening arguments Wednesday as attorneys
finished questioning potential jurors.
   The attorneys next will choose from a group of 33 jurors, and
opening arguments could come Thursday in the trial in which
Swindall stands accused of lying to a federal grand jury
investigating money laundering,
   Forty-seven potential jurors were questioned over two days
regarding their knowledge of the heavily publicized case and their
feelings about the former Republican congressman.
   U.S. District Judge Richard C. Freeman dismissed 14. Thirteen
said they possibly could not put aside their unfavorable
impressions of Swindall and be impartial jurors, and the 14th was a
former law partner of Swindall.
   At least eight of the 33 people in the jury pool said they, too,
had unfavorable opinions about Swindall but could put them aside
and decide the case on the basis of the evidence.
   The potential juror pool also includes one woman, a former
Swindall fund-raiser, who said she ``admires'' Swindall but
promised to be open-minded.
   Defense attorneys have asked the judge to move the trial because
of extensive publicity, but Freeman said he would rule only after
hearing from potential jurors.
   Swindall is accused of lying under oath in early 1988 to a
federal grand jury investigating his dealings with Charles
LeChasney, an associate and now-admitted money launderer, and a
federal agent posing as a money broker for probable drug dealers.
   Swindall was indicted Oct. 17 on 10 counts of lying to a federal
grand jury, each of which carries a penalty of 10 months to five
years in prison on conviction.
   The indictment contends Swindall lied in concealing from the
grand jury his discussions of how to cover up the sources of an
$850,000 loan to be used to pay for his home. Swindall returned
uncashed a check for the first installment of the loan.
   Swindall, a two-term Republican congressman, lost his seat
representing Atlanta's eastern suburbs to Democrat Ben Jones last
November.
</TEXT>
