<FIRST>u w AM-WrightProbe 11thLd-Writethru a0794 05-24 1349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright Probe, 11th Ld-Writethru, a0794,1300</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wright Bargains Over Terms of Resigning Speakership</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES with fresh material on Foley, details of bargaining,
other material</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright, his political career
of 35 years in shambles, bargained through lawyers Wednesday to
resign his leadership post in exchange for the dismissal of some of
the ethics charges confronting him.
   Wright denied that he was considering stepping down and issued a
statement saying he would ``press ahead'' with his defense. Even
so, Democrats were looking beyond his departure to selection of a
succcessor _ and apparently closing ranks behind Majority Leader
Tom Foley of Washington.
   Wright's representatives shuttled through a daylong series of
meetings with key members of Congress in a bid to nail down an
unprecedented agreement stripping him of his post as leader of the
House and second in line of succession to the presidency within a
week. The extraordinary drama of political abdication overwhelmed
normal business at the Capitol, even though it was played out
almost exclusively behind closed doors.
   ``What I know is that negotiations are taking place that deal
with resolving this issue very soon,' said Rep. Bill Richardson,
D-N.M. ``They involve dropping one of the charges in exchange for
the speaker resigning the post, and it's something that will
probably be settled in the next 24 to 48 hours.'' Other sources
suggested it would be next week before the issue was resolved.
   Richardson said he understood Wright would retain his House seat
under the terms of the discussions. But there was no word on
whether the Speaker would seek re-election from his Fort Worth
congressional district in 1990.
   Other sources said the deal involved dropping
conflict-of-interest charges that Wright accepted gifts of housing
and a car and salary for his wife. If those charges were dropped,
Wright could step down as early as next week, the sources said.
   But sources said the committee was not receptive to any
arrangement that would clear Wright of charges that he evaded House
limits on outside income through bulk sales of his book,
``Reflections of a Public Man.''
   One congressman familiar with the talks, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said a majority of the ethics committee favored some
sort of negotiated settlement. But the ethics committee adjourned
late Wednesday until June 1 without acting on Wright's case, and
sources said the negotiations were continuing.
   Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., the panel's chairman met at one
point during the afternoon with Foley to discuss Wright's situation.
   At the same time, the timing of any resignation was uncertain,
and Rep. John Myers of Indiana, the ranking Republican, said, `` I
personally am opposed to any arrangements, deals, plea bargaining.''
   ``It's kind of a dance _ a very tentative kind of dance,'' said
one House member, who spoke only on condition of anonymity.
   In the background, the politics of succession flourished.
   ``There is near unanimity of support for Tom Foley'' as speaker,
said Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont. ``There would be no campaign'' for
the top leadership post, he said.
   Even so, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri was careful not to
dampen speculation that he might seek the speaker's job, and a long
list of contenders was mentioned to take Foley's rung on the
leadership ladder and vie for other spots. The party's whip, Tony
Coelho of California, caucus chairman Bill Gray of Pennsylvania,
deputy whip David Bonior of Michigan, Rep. Lee Hamilton of Indiana
and Gephardt headed the roster of potential candidates.
   House Republican Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., who normally has
avoided comment on Wright's plight, said: ``I guess if I had that
kind of a problem, I wouldn't be around here. If the conditions
were exactly the same and I were dragging my party into the kind of
area that I see .... I'd have no alternative but to step aside.''
   Wright, who spent his day in a serious of meetings with his
supporters and his leadership team, left the Capitol early in the
evening without speaking to reporters.
   The speaker also issued a statement saying: ``I very firmly
believe that my position is right. I hope and trust that the
committee will consider the matter on its merits and dismiss the
charges.
   ``I eagerly await the time and opportunity when my side of this
whole question may be heard clearly by my colleagues and the
American people. To this end, I shall press ahead.''
   Rep. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., a member of Wright's defense
team, met with ethics committee counsel Richard J. Phelan and made
the initial offer, the sources said. The proposal ran into
opposition from ethics committee Republicans and still was being
negotiated, said the sources, who commented only on condition they
not be named.
   The ethics committee _ made up of six Democrats and six
Republicans _ met for much of the day in private, deliberating
Wright's motion to dismiss the two most serious allegations. The
chairman, Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., promised a ``fresh look,''
but there was no indication any of the committee members had been
persuaded.
   Other signs were ominous for Wright, as fellow Texas Democrats
began to talk openly of growing odds against his keeping his post.
   The most serious allegations facing Wright are that he used bulk
sales of an autobiographical book to evade rules limiting outside
income and that he improperly took gifts from a developer friend
who had a direct interest in legislation.
   Earlier Wednesday, entering a luncheon with Texas Democrats,
Wright was asked about widespread speculation that he was
considering stepping aside as speaker until the ethics case is
resolved.
   ``No, I'm not,'' he answered.
   Asked whether his political position was eroding, he said, ``I
don't feel that at all.''
   However, a fellow Texas Democrat in the House, Mickey Leland,
said, ``There is some hint Jim might step aside, at least
temporarily, until this whole thing is resolved.''
   Wright met with Clark Clifford, an elder statesman of the
Democratic Party and a member of Wright's legal defense team, for
1{ hours Wednesday morning, and Torricelli later met with ethics
committee attorney Phelan.
   When asked whether there was a deal in the works to drop some of
the charges against Wright in return for his stepping down, the
speaker's spokesman, Mark Johnson, declined comment.
   ``There's no question the speaker is in serious trouble,'' said
Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas. ``The speaker's problems have
translated into institutional problems for all of us. The
institution is getting a black eye.''
   Stenholm said some of his constituents now are telling him the
evidence against Wright is overwhelming and that ``where there's
that much smoke, Charlie, there's gotta be a spark somewhere.''
   He added: ``There obviously have been some mistakes made, some
rules if not broken, bent severely.''
   ``Public opinion is weighted against him at this time,'' added
Leland. ``I think the die is cast. There is still a glimmer of hope
he might survive. But the cards are stacked against him.''
   Rep. Philip Sharp, D-Ind., who previously called for a
leadership change, embraced the idea of Wright stepping down at
least temporarily and appointing a replacement. ``There is a state
of continuing erosion of public confidence in the House, and I
don't think that's a good state for anybody,'' Sharp said.
   On Tuesday night, Wright had told reporters: ``I want to be an
effective person in America, and I've had that privilege. Most of
all now I want to protect my good name and that of my family and my
wife and my colleagues.''
   The ethics committee's two senior members indicated there was
nothing new in the fiery arguments they heard a day earlier from
Wright's lawyer, Stephen Susman, during a televised hearing.
   ``My mind wasn't changed,'' said Myers, the committee's senior
Republican. ``There were no new points raised, absolutely no new
points.''
   Dixon said, ``I think Mr. Susman indicated in his remarks that
he was not optimistic that any or all of them would be dismissed,
but I do think we have a responsibility to reassess that and give
it a fresh look.''
</TEXT>
