<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Teachers 1stLd-Writethru a0705 05-24 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Teachers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>200 Teachers Strike; Government Given Deadline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 200 teachers went on strike
Wednesday in the first serious display of worker discontent since
January, when the government announced a tough austerity plan to
fight 20,000-percent inflation.
   Educators at two schools split from the national union and gave
the leftist Sandinista government a deadline to answer demands for
pay raises and other improvements.
   The pro-Sandinista National Educators Association of Nicaragua,
known as ANDEN by its Spanish initials, struck a conciliatory note.
The nationwide labor union backed most demands but warned
``pro-imperialist and rightist pseudo-leaders'' against instigating
strikes.
   ``This is the crucial moment to reach our vindication and we
can't lose it,'' said teacher Cesar Cuevas. ``This is the awakening
of the teaching profession.''
   Monthly salaries now range from $21.62 for high school teachers
to $81.08 for college professors.
   Cuevas is a member of the negotiating committee from the Mexico
Experimental Center, one of two schools in Managua that gave the
government until Thursday afternoon to answer the teachers' demands
for better pay and working conditions.
   The Mexico Experimental Center, a high school, has 120 teachers,
while the other school, Maestro Gabriel, has 112 teachers.
   In San Rafael del Sur, a town 30 miles south of Managua, the
entire force of 198 teachers was on ``indefinite strike until our
situation has been solved,'' said Orlando Estrada Garcia, principal
at the Ricardo Morales Aviles elementary school.
   ``Today they came (from the Education Ministry) with an offer
which we didn't think is correct,'' said Estrada. ``The 5,000
cordobas we earn daily doesn't cover anything. You buy a soft drink
and a piece of bread and there goes your 5,000 cordobas.''
   Estrada said the 47 teachers at the school earn an average
150,000 cordobas monthly and they are demanding a tripling of the
salary, ``although even 600,000 cordobas a month would barely cover
a family's basic needs.''
   At the current rate of exchange of 7,400 cordobas to the dollar,
150,000 cordobas equals $20.27 and 600,000 is worth $81.08.
   Olivia Sanchez de Solis, principal of the Jose Ignacio Estrada
high school in San Rafael del Sur, said representatives of the
teachers would meet with government officials on Thursday.
   The government also has been meeting with teachers in Managua to
negotiate a solution, but already it has said that granting pay
raises would undo its anti-inflationary measures.
   Inflation in 1988 reached more than 20,000 percent.
   ANDEN issued a communique saying the teachers had legitimate
grievances but a pay raise would ``make inflation explosive and
would not contribute to the logic of the (government's) economic
measures.''
   Barricada, the official newspaper of the ruling Sandinista
National Liberation Front, accused right-wing politicians and the
U.S. Embassy of trying to ``manipulate'' the teachers' discontent.
</TEXT>
