<FIRST>r a AM-LATeachers     05-24 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Teachers,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negotiators in Teachers Strike Grow Less Inflammatory, More Optimistic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The teachers strike in the nation's
second-largest district went into its 11th day Wednesday without
the inflammatory statements that had prompted state legislators to
admonish negotiators to stop bickering.
   Negotiators for the teachers' union and the school district
expressed optimism about reaching an agreement as they headed into
talks late in the day.
   ``I am hopeful that we will emerge with a contract and people
will go back to work tomorrow,'' school board President Roberta
Weintraub said. ``I think that the time has come for the offer the
board has made to be accepted ... I am very optimistic, I certainly
expect that we'll have some good news.''
   United Teachers-Los Angeles President Wayne Johnson told
reporters that a private meeting both sides had with state
legislators in Sacramento on Tuesday spurred resumption of talks.
   ``I think that it brought a sense of realism to both sides that
... there is serious concern about what is going on in Los Angeles
and the powerful legislators, influential people, want this thing
settled,'' Johnson said.
   Johnson also told reporters, ``I think there is an expectation
that there will be some movement and possibly a settlement
tonight.''
   In another development, a striking teacher was booked Wednesday
on assault charges of throwing a rock at a substitute teacher.
Sheriff's deputies said the rock missed the teacher's car and
struck a 12-year-old girl. She was treated at a hospital for a cut
on her head, said sheriff's spokesman Deputy Dan Cox.
   The teachers are seeking a 26 percent raise over three years.
   School board members have said they boosted their offer to a 24
percent pay raise over three years, with the second year raise
contingent on receiving state surplus funds. Otherwise, it will
drop to 5{ percent.
   Teachers earn between $23,440 and $43,319 a year, depending on
experience and level of education.
   Education in the district has slowed to a crawl since the union
representing 22,000 of the district's 32,000 teachers went on
strike May 15.
   Most classes wind up June 23, but some schools operate
year-round.
</TEXT>
