<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Schechter     05-24 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Schechter,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Executive Producer Of ``Today'' Show Dies With Wife In Car
Wreck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A.A. ``Abe'' Schechter, the first news
director for NBC-TV and the first executive producer of the
``Today'' show, and his wife, Fritzi, died Wednesday in a car
accident. He was 81.
   Mrs. Schechter, who was 82, was driving the couple's car when it
ran off a Long Island highway and struck a tree, Southampton Town
police said.
   Schechter was the author of ``Go Ahead Garrison,'' published in
1940, and co-wrote ``I Live on Air,'' both books describing his
exploits in journalism.
   In the second book, published in 1941, he told of the time he
directed an NBC Radio reporter to set up for what was intended to
be the first broadcast from the base of the Egyptian pyramids at a
time when remote broadcasts were rare and difficult.
   The radio reporter arrived to find a CBS reporter already on the
air from the opposite side of the pyramid. He phoned Schechter for
directions and was told ``then go to the top of the pyramid.'' The
order became a catch-phrase for producers to dramatize the
importance of being first.
   Schechter was born in Central Falls, R.I. He worked at The
Providence (R.I.) Journal and the New York World as a reporter
before he became an editor in New York with The Associated Press.
   In 1932, he was hired by NBC to organize and run the network's
news department, which he did until 1942.
   During World War II, he was attached to the staff of Gen.
Douglas MacArthur, supervising radio and press communications for
war correspondents.
   From 1945-50, he was a vice president of the Mutual Broadcasting
System, which he left to work briefly at Crowell Collier Publishing
Co.
   He then returned to NBC to help create the ``Today'' show and
became its first executive producer.
   He left in 1952 to start a public relations company, A.A.
Schechter Associates Inc., which in 1973 was acquired by Hill and
Knowlton Inc.
   Schechter was a member of the board of directors at Hill and
Knowlton until his 1979 retirement.
   The Schechters, who had homes in Westhampton, N.Y., and Palm
Beach, Fla., are survived by two daughters.
</TEXT>
