<FIRST>r a AM-MalibuTurmoil     05-24 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malibu Turmoil,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless `March on Malibu' Called Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hoards of homeless won't be dispatched in
bus loads to this celebrity beach retreat in spite of actor Martin
Sheen's official welcome for them in his capacity as honorary mayor.
   ``There will not be any buses. Things have spiraled to such a
degree they are out of my control,'' Rush Limbaugh, a nationally
syndicated radio talk show host who had threatened to organize a
homeless ``March on Malibu,'' said Wednesday.
   Sheen's declaration offering Malibu as a nuclear-free, homeless
sanctuary triggered Limbaugh's proposal to arrive Saturday with
busloads of indigents. But the continuing uproar gave Limbaugh
second thoughts.
   ``Call me a coward, call me a wimp, but I am doing what is
right,'' he said in a telephone interview from New York. ``The
bottom line is that I will not be able to guarantee their safety.''
   Limbaugh, a conservative, has been needling Sheen and what he
calls the Hollywood ``left coast'' for years, and Limbaugh had
maintained busing homeless to Malibu was a fair response to Sheen's
declaration.
   But on Wednesday he said, ``I don't have to bring a bunch of
homeless down there to prove my point. The left just loves evidence
that we conservatives are heartless and cold.''
   Olivia Thornton, the Chamber of Commerce president who picked
Sheen as honorary mayor, expressed relief.
   Meanwhile, Los Angeles homeless activist Ted Hayes said
Wednesday he felt Limbaugh had a point.
   ``Why doesn't Martin take them in his house? How can he go
around the country and tell everybody they should do something and
then he has no plan in his own neighborhood?'' he asked.
   The declaration sparking nearly two weeks of turmoil in Malibu
read: ``I hereby declare Malibu a nuclear free zone, a sanctuary
for aliens and the homeless and a protected environment for all
life, wild and tame.''
   Hayes sees a positive side to the Malibu brouhaha, although he
believes Sheen's days as honorary mayor are numbered.
   ``Malibu can set an example for all the other affluent
communities,'' he said. ``I think Martin Sheen was a godsend for
the chamber of commerce. Everyone knows there are homeless, now
it's time for a yes-in-my-backyard campaign.''
   Sheen, who has been in Canada directing Gary Busey and son
Charlie Sheen in the movie ``Count a Lonely Cadence,'' wasn't
available for comment on the latest developments, his publicist
said.
   The actor, who once portrayed a homeless activist himself in a
movie made for television, has said his remarks were misunderstood
and distorted.
</TEXT>
