<FIRST>a a PM-ReligionintheNews Adv26   05-24 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Religion in the News, Adv 26,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs May 26, or thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gospel Missions Serving Widened Range Of Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gospel rescue missions, long a champion
in the inner city for the homeless, are responding to a whole new
range of needs that were practically unthinkable even a decade ago.
   Expansion in the role of these downtown missions was highlighted
at the recent annual convention of representatives of about 300
such missions in cities across the country.
   It long has been a stereotype that they mostly serve older
alcoholics and drug abusers. However, young adults, women and
children are just as likely to seek help these days.
   That has put a growing load on rescue missions to meet needs not
met by state or other agencies.
   ``In the last 10 to 15 years, things have changed drastically,''
said the Rev. Stephen Burger, president of the International Union
Of Gospel Missions. ``We've been called on to do things we hadn't
done before.''
   A look at some of the issues raised at the IUGM's 76th annual
conference here earlier this month tells part of the story: AIDS,
children's nutrition, unschooled minors, battered women, drugs.
   It used to be almost unheard of to have to worry about children
in the missions, Burger commented at the close of the five-day
conference. But women and children now are the fastest growing
proportion of those served, now amounting to about 40 percent.
   Burger, nephew of retired Supreme Court Chief Justice Warren
Burger, in August will become executive director of the non-profit
Protestant organization which oversees some 300 rescue missions in
the United States and Canada.
   He says there has been a vast upheaval in the social fabric of
this country. ``Today there are millions of homeless in America _ a
population that continues to grow and become more diverse,'' he
says.
   No city has been left untouched by the homeless problem, he
notes, suggesting a look at the shuttered up steel-mill towns of
Pennsylvania, or a place like Astoria, Ore. (population 15,000).
   ``I thought of that as a picturebook place and here they were
with the fishing industry falling apart, the lumber industry
falling apart, alcoholism on the rise. And all of a sudden,''
recalls Burger, ``we have a homeless problem.''
   Astoria is one of a number of cities across the country which
have turned to the IUGM in setting up programs for the homeless and
what Burger calls the ``near-homeless,'' or those people whose
whole condition is unstable and regularly move in and out of the
system.
   He says there is agreement on causes of the homeless crisis: the
disintegration of the family, changing values, drug and alcohol
abuse, a changing economy.
   What is not so clear are what the solutions will be.
   But there is reason to hope, Burger says. ``The church has
become awakened to the possibilities.''
   He says there are more volunteers, and churches which over the
years have tended to move away from the inner city are getting more
involved.
   He says one key is to persuade people to pitch in.
   ``Part of the problem is we've challenged but we haven't told
them what to do. You have to provide the vehicle to get people
downtown,'' a formidable task, Burger says, when there are already
so many demands on people's daily lives.
   Another key, he adds, is creating innovative programs to help
those trying to rebuild shattered lives.
   ``Even those of us in this work can get a fortress mentality ..
. and not see the new needs _ the mentally ill, the Hispanics, the
folks being dumped out of hospitals, the elderly being kicked out
of homes being turned into condos,'' Burger says.
   ``Government can provide funding, but it can't get involved with
people on a personal level to help overcome years of abuse,
alcoholism. ...''
   Burger says the thinking now must be: ``How do you get that
person to see, with God's help, what they can do'' as well as
``What are you doing to keep people out of the mission.''
   Under the Bush administration, the homeless could fare better,
he believes.
   ``I think the problem is quite obvious at this point and it
seems (Secretary of Housing and Urban Development) Jack Kemp has a
real commitment,'' Burger says.
   For others out in the communities wanting to commit themselves
to the homeless issue, Burger plans to develop videos of model
programs across the country.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs May 26</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
