<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs May 26, or thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITBY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What was planned as a major ecumenical
affair has terminated in discord.
   For more than two years, planning had gone on for a special
Anglican-Roman Catholic liturgy marking the Church of England's
l6th century closing of the famous abbey here and other monasteries.
   The affair was canceled after Roman Catholic Bishop Augustine
Harris, who had been on the planning committee, withdrew from
participation, saying a celebrative note was being applied to a sad
event.
   Anglican Bishop Gordon Bates said of the cancellation: ``You
can't have a service of reconciliation, penitence and hope for the
future if part won't play ball. It would be a sham.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Of those answering a survey on prayer by the
monthly U.S. Catholic, 92 percent said that they have had specific
prayers answered. Seventy-five percent say they could cite
instances when God answered a prayer that they virtually despaired
of being answered.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KIAMESHA LAKE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the second successive year, the
Cantors Assembly has rejected a proposal to admit women as members,
although several women have earned diplomas as cantors from the
Jewish Theological Seminary of America.
   Unlike last year, a majority of the Cantors Assembly favored
admitting women, 108 to 82, but that still was less than the
two-thirds majority required for passage.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief executive of the Presbyterian
Church (U.S.A.) has urged President Bush to use every ``appropriate
diplomatic means'' to stop the warfare in Lebanon and to restore
its sovereignty.
   The Rev. James Andrews, in a letter to Bush and Secretary of
State James Baker III, cited communications from Lebanese church
leaders and said that country is suffering ``a tragedy of major
proportions.''
   Church statements from Lebanon charge that ``outside interests''
are behind the fighting there, and appeal for withdrawal of
``illegal forces'' as necessary to end the bloodshed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Council for Religious Affairs reports
1,610 new Christian congregations were registered last year, that
937 religious buildings were returned and that l43 permits were
issued for building new churches.
   The figures were much greater than for the year before, when
only 104 registrations of new congregations were reported, 17
buildings returned and 10 building permits issued.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WILMORE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Methodism's evangelical caucus, Good
News, charges that denominational staff members violated church
guidelines by participating in a Washington rally supporting
abortion rights.
   Noting that the denomination's top governing body has rejected
abortion as a means of birth control or gender selection, the
caucus calls for replacement of officials whose conduct continues
to violate church guidelines.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The council of the recently merged Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America recommends that it continue membership
in the U.S. National Council of Churches and the World Council of
Churches.
   The recommendation goes before the denomination's governing
assembly here Aug. 23-30. Such membership has been maintained
tenatively by the 5 million-member denomination until the assembly
acts.
   In the denomination's formation last year, one of the merging
bodies, the American Lutheran Church, did not belong to both
ecumenical bodies, as did a merging partner, the Lutheran Church in
America.
   However, subsequent samplings indicate strong majorities favor
such memberships.
</TEXT>
