<FIRST>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv25   05-24 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 25,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs May 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arming Yourself Against Investment Scams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the legitimate investment world has boomed in
the 1980s, so has its dark underside, where the ripoff artists ply
their trade.
   Stories abound of operations selling ``gold'' that is actually
dirt, penny stocks at pumped-up prices, packages of government
securities that never existed, and tax shelter deals that can't
stand up to the slightest scrutiny.
   Of course, financial scams are just about as old as the history
of money. A lot of the ploys in use today are merely recycled
versions of schemes dreamed up long ago.
   But the volatility of all securities markets in this decade, and
the fast-buck atmosphere it has helped foster, seems to have
created an especially fertile breeding ground for financial phony
business.
   ``We've never been this aware of so many frauds in things such
as penny stocks, coins, gold piles and so forth,'' said Raymond F.
DeVoe Jr., an analyst at the Wall Street firm of Legg Mason Wood
Walker Inc.
   One apparent cause of this, DeVoe says, is the proliferation of
new investment vehicles that Wall Street has devised to offer to
pension fund managers and other sophisticated clients.
   ``Some of the financial creations of the last few years are so
bizarre that even professionals don't completely understand them,''
he observes.
   ``Because the legitimate financial creations are so complex, it
is very hard to tell them from the phony ones.''
   All this leaves many individuals who have money to manage in a
tough spot: How to protect themselves while still attempting to
invest their money productively.
   Harold Finlay at the Cleveland-based investment firm of
Prescott, Ball &amp; Turben suggests three basic rules: ``Beware of
very high yields. Know the person with whom you do business. Don't
make hasty decisions.
   ``It seems laughable that many people spend more time selecting
a necktie or dress than investing their life savings,'' Finley
observed in the firm's monthly publication Investor News.
   A prime tool of the scammer's trade is the telephone. The North
American Securities Administrators Association acknowledges that
many above-board investments are promoted over the phone.
   But it has published a list of tips for dealing with what you
suspect is a ``boiler room'' operation selling questionable or
fraudulent goods.
   Among the association's most compelling recommendations: The
harder a telephone salesperson presses, the wiser it is to resist.
If a caller turns abusive, hang up.
   Don't fall for any claims of spectacular rewards or promised
``guarantees'' until you can verify the legitimacy of the deal and
have a clear picture of all the risks involved. If you can't
understand an investment, don't buy it without the counsel of a
trusted and knowledgeable adviser.
   Never give your credit-card number to a stranger on the phone.
Be especially suspicious of propositions involving delayed delivery
of the investment in question.
   Likewise, look warily at any deal in which the seller proposes
some unusual arrangement to collect your money, such as sending a
messenger to pick up your check. ``Some con artists try to avoid
mail fraud charges by using overnight courier services,'' NASAA
points out.
   A deregulated financial world is also a let-the-buyer-beware
world requiring a good deal of healthy skepticism.
   That means mustering the strongest doubts when the caller's
voice is most persuasive, or when the name of the purported
business is most impressive-sounding. Fly-by-night boiler rooms
have been known to call themselves ``national exchanges,''
``research institutes,'' ``bureaus,'' in fact almost anything but
what they really are.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs May 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv25   05-24 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 25,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs May 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>Housing _ A Time To Buy?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With asking prices below their highs of a few
months ago, with large numbers of unsold houses on the market and
with interest rates falling, an investment opportunity may be
developing in single-family housing.
   While such opportunities are more common in housing than in most
markets, partly because housing is made up of a greater percentage
of amateur versus professional sellers, as in cars, they are
transitory.
   In fact, as soon as such opportunities appear, they begin to
vanish. That's the housing market for you, up and down more sharply
than other markets, and always exaggerating the usual economic
cycle. Bust to boom and back to bust.
   The most important element in the opening for buyers is the
general decline of interest rates, which many forecasters expect
will continue right through the year.
   Interest rates are key, since interest is the biggest housing
expense for those who take out 20-year or 30-year mortgages,
sometimes equalling the total cost of all other factors, including
land and the structure itself.
   When you have a combination of lower rates and relatively softer
prices _ asking prices that are below their earlier highs or that
are negotiable _ you have a buying opportunity. Now add to that a
big inventory of unsold units.
   Earlier this year, the National Association of Realtors
estimated the inventory of unsold homes at more than 2.9 million
units, or a nine-month supply of existing homes and 7.5-month
supply of new houses.
   What that means is a lot of unhappy sellers. While they could
rationalize the inattention given to their offerings during the
winter, when weather and mood keep people from shopping, they are
now in the prime selling months.
   Another factor enters the picture: The news about housing has a
rather dismal cast of late. Just a month or two ago, for example,
sellers and buyers were loudly lamenting the deadly duo of rising
prices and interest rates.
   In many areas those factors have changed _ in some they have
been reversed _but the mood lingers, keeping many potential buyers
from the market. It is, of course, a situation that can change
overnight. It has happened before.
   Still another factor is involved in the potential investment
opportunity. If the price of the house purchased today is to have
greater market value tomorrow, it would help tremendously if future
housing were in short supply.
   There is no proof that such a situation will develop, but it
should be noted that the number of residential building permits
issued in 1989 could be the lowest in seven years. Future demand,
therefore, might not be met.
   The National Association of Home Builders forecasts 1.02 million
single-family housing starts this year, a figure that would make
1989 the weakest homebuilding year since 1983. Lomas Mortgage USA,
a large mortgage lender, estimates new housing permits this year at
1.394 million, 21 percent lower than in 1986.
   Building activity today creates tomorrow's markets, and if
building this year is weak it could tip tomorrow's buyer-seller
balance. Those who buy today, that is, conceivably could find
market values higher a few years hence.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday May 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv26   05-24 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 26,0858</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, May 26 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Count of Women Clergy Doubles In Decade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of American women ordained to the
church's ``full ministry'' _ preaching the word and administering
the sacraments _ has about doubled in the last decade.
   They total 20,730, as statistically projected, nearly twice the
10,470 of 1977. They now constitute 7.9 percent of the clergy in
denominations ordaining women.
   That percentage also has about doubled, from 4 percent, and
seems likely for a further steep increase as indicated by the boom
in women enrollment in seminaries.
   The figures were gathered by Constant H. Jacquet Jr. of the
research office of the National Council of Churches. His report
says women still face some discrimination, but adds:
   ``There has been an increasing acceptance of women clergy in
local church situtations especially by younger people and by those
of higher educational attainment.
   ``Women have also gained acceptance as pastors once they have
been given the opportunity to demonstrate their competence in
preaching and pastoral care at the local level.''
   Among mainline denominations, the Lutheran Church in America
(merged in 1988 into the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America)
had the highest percentage of women heads of local pastoral staffs,
more than half its clergywomen.
   American Baptist also ranked high in this category. Among
mainliners, Lutherans and the United Methodist Church had the
highest perentage of women clergy serving in local congregations
generally.
   Getting on the staff of a local church, particularly as chief
pastor or head of staff, is considered a key measure of acceptance
of women clergy. It also is seen as a common obstacle.
   ``Women clergy appear to be more easily accepted in church
employment outside the local church at various denominational
administrative offices, in ecumenical conciliar positions and in
many institutional roles,'' the report says.
   Among 221 denominations included in the survey, 84 of them
ordain women and 82 do not, with uncertainty about it in 49 others.
Six do not ordain clergy at all.
   The proportion of denominations ordaining women had grown little
since 1977, when 76 ordained women and 82 did not. However, those
ordaining women had now become a slight majority, 84 to 82.
   With totals projected as of 1986, the Assemblies of God led the
field in numbers of women clergy, 3,718 of them, up from 1,572, or
137 percent. Others among the next ranked l0, and their decade's
increase or decrease in women clergy, were:
   Salvation Army, 3,220, up from 3,037, or 6 percent.
   United Methodist Church, 1,891, up from 319, or 496 percent.
   Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.), 1,519, up from 370, or 310 percent.
   United Church of Christ, 1,460, up from 400, or 265 percent.
   Episcopal Church, 796, up from 94, or 747 percent.
   Christian Church (Disciples of Christ), 743, up from 388, or 91
percent.
   Lutheran Church in America, 484, up from 55, or 780 percent.
   International Church of the Foursquare Gospel, 666, down from
804, or 17 percent.
   Southern Baptist Convention, 450, up from 20, or 2,150 percent.
   American Baptist Churches, 429, up from 157, or 173 percent.
   Apart from those numerical rankings, other large percentage
gains in women clergy were by the Reformed Church in America, which
went from one to 42 of them, up by 4,100 percent.
   Also, the American Lutheran Church (now also merged into the
Evanelical Lutheran Church in America), increased women clergy from
18 to 306, or 1,600 percent, while the Menonites went from four to
48, up 1,100 percent.
   In the smaller Mormon branch, the Reorganized Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints, women's ordination was authorized only
in 1984, and since has shot up from none to 860, the report says.
   In some instances, the numbers of women clergy dropped. The
Church of the Nazarene count fell from 426 to 355, a 17 percent
drop.
   Like the Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox Churches, some
larger, conservative Protestant churches do not ordain women,
including the Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod.
   The present fundamentalist administration of the Southern
Baptist Convention opposes women's ordination, but the report shows
the denomination's women clergy, up from 20 to 450, have multiplied
more than 20 times.
   Congregations in that denomination are autonomous and may ordain
without higher approval, but few have hired women pastors.
   Until recent times, the increase in women clergy was relatively
slow. It took 27 years for the 1950 total of 5,591, most of them
among Pentecostals or para-church groups, to double by 1977.
   Now that most mainline denominations ordain women, the totals
have zoomed, doubling again in one decade. The report says:
   ``There is every reason to believe that the percentage of women
ordained will continue to increase ... as women gain wider
acceptance in the various denominations based on demonstrated
performance and on the changing attitudes of those currently
opposing equal roles for women.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, May 26</NOTE>
