<FIRST>r f PM-China-USBusiness Bjt   05-24 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-US Business, Bjt,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most American Companies Reacting Cautiously to Chinese Turmoil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. companies operating in China are reacting
to the tumultuous political events there by delaying visits and
telling expatriate workers to avoid street protests, but few are
taking people out of the country.
   Most companies believe it's premature to even consider
divestment or withdrawal, particularly because the protests aren't
anti-foreign and violence has been rare.
   But many were surprised at how quickly the government's seeming
stability weakened because of the demonstrations for democratic
reforms gripping Beijing.
   ``So much depends on what ultimately happens here,'' Jerome
Cohen, a lawyer and expert on doing business with the Chinese, said
in a telephone interview from his Hong Kong residence.
   ``I'm still holding open the possibility that a new surge of
modernization, a more open China, could come out of this,'' he said.
   Roger Sullivan, president of the U.S.-China Business Council, a
Washington-based association of American companies with interests
in China, said business requests for information have multiplied to
50 or 60 daily since the crisis intensified, vs. two or three a day
ordinarily.
   But Sullivan said he knew of no companies that were rethinking
their long-term plans in China.
   ``There's a lot of hand-wringing going on. But companies are
intelligent enough not to make decisions in that environment,'' he
said. ``Companies don't react to something like this until they see
the longer-term implications.''
   The unprecedented demonstrations come against a background of
broadening U.S. business operations in the world's most populous
country, with ventures as ranging from open-pit coal mining to
nuclear power.
   The United States is a leading foreign investor in China and one
of its most important trading partners. More than 600 U.S.-Chinese
joint ventures have been established since the countries normalized
relations a decade ago.
   Telephone interviews Tuesday with business consultants and
executives in the United States, China and Hong Kong suggested many
visits to Beijing had been delayed until the political crisis
stabilizes.
   Most postponements were attributed to a U.S. State Department
travel advisory and uncertainty over whether the demonstrations
would turn violent.
   ``Everybody is just tentatively rescheduling things,'' Cohen
said.
   Some companies also curtailed Beijing operations.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., for example, closed its
office temporarily over the weekend and offered its 27 U.S.
staffers the option of sending family members out. Spokesman Rick
Wallerstein said it was unclear whether any had left.
   ``We've closed the office just because we don't want our people
coming in to work in light of that situation,'' he said. ``We've
also asked them to stay in their residences as much as possible,
avoid public gatherings and not carry cameras around with them.''
   Among other U.S. companies with offices in Beijing, Bechtel
Group Inc. said three expatriate employees temporarily had left the
country and United Technologies Corp. said one had, partly because
the protests paralyzed traffic in much of the capital, making
ordinary work nearly impossible.
   ``It's really not business as usual there,'' said Larry Miller,
a spokesman for Bechtel. ``So we sent our three non-Chinese
employees to Hong Kong on a temporary basis, until normal business
conditions return to Beijing.''
   Others _ including International Business Machines Corp. and
Chrysler Corp.'s jeep joint-venture _ were said by sources in
Beijing to have evacuated an undetermined number of staffers and
dependents. But spokesmen for those companies said they were
unaware anyone had left due to the crisis.
   Nevertheless, IBM spokesman Tim Sheehy said the computer giant's
50 expatriates in Beijing were taking what he described as prudent
precautions.
   ``We just make sure the employees are using good sense,'' he
said. ``If you can't get to work, don't come to work.''
   Preston Torbert, a partner and Chinese legal expert at the
Chicago-based law firm Baker &amp; McKenzie, which has offices in
Beijing, said he was unaware of any clients withdrawing plans for
investment or business negotiations.
   Torbert also said many business representatives in Beijing were
rooting privately for the protesters' cause of greater freedom and
democracy.
   ``In fact, people are excited to be there,'' he said. ``It's
such an exciting moment. What are you going to tell your
grandchildren, that you left?''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Rick Gladstone, who is enterprise editor for
Associated Press Business News, covered China from Beijing for the
AP from 1983 to 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
