<FIRST>r f PM-Casino'sDemise Bjt   05-24 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Casino's Demise, Bjt,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>As Atlantis Failed, Casino President's Status Went With It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jeanne Hood once could count herself
among Atlantic City's most powerful women, the only female casino
president in this oceanside gaming resort.
   But the president of Elsinore's Atlantis Casino Hotel lost her
status as she presided over the demise of the financially troubled
casino.
   ``Everybody liked her quite a while ago. She seemed like she was
working toward everyone's benefit,'' pit clerk Charles Hersh, one
of more than 1,200 laid-off casino employees, said Tuesday on his
way to the unemployment office.
   ``Everyone used to be fairly well impressed with her intentions,
but in hindsight, everything she did was bad,'' he said.
   The state Casino Control Commission on Monday closed the
Atlantis, which had run up $150 million in debts. Regulators are
considering a bid by developer Donald Trump to buy the Atlantis for
$63 million and convert it into a luxury non-casino hotel.
   About 600 hotel and restaurant employees still on the Atlantis
payroll are anxiously watching the outcome of Trump's purchase
agreement, which is being challenged by the casino's
state-appointed conservator.
   Mrs. Hood wasn't around for the casino's final day of gaming on
Sunday, her 63rd birthday. Atlantis spokesman Robert Arrow said
Tuesday that Mrs. Hood is in Las Vegas. Repeated attempts to reach
her directly or through a spokesman were unsuccessful.
   During the casino's chaotic final two years, Mrs. Hood was a
study in contrasts. She dressed elegantly, but said she drove to
the local mall in a Honda she kept in the Atlantis parking garage.
   During an employee strike in 1987, pickets chanted ``Jeannie
Hood, she's no good'' while faithful workers talked with reporters
inside about her loyalty to the company.
   And though her fondest dream was to see news reports stop
referring to the Atlantis as the ``financially struggling casino,''
Mrs. Hood failed to accomplish just that.
   Marvin B. Roffman, a gaming analyst for Janney Montgomery Scott
Inc. of Philadelphia, said strained relations between Mrs. Hood and
workers often were reflected in the treatment of customers.
   ``Their level of tips was at half the level of the other houses,
but a lot of them stayed because they could not get similar jobs in
other casinos. Most casino jobs in Atlantic City today are
entry-level,'' he said.
   In Mrs. Hood's defense, Roffman said she inherited an
ill-designed and ill-managed casino from her arrival in late 1985.
The three-level casino floor was never popular with customers, and
the Atlantis is burdened with a heavy debt structure.
   The Atlantis also failed at a marketing campaign aimed at
middle-class customers that steered away from high-rollers who pump
money into gaming halls.
   Mrs. Hood succeeded her husband David as president of the Four
Queens Casino Hotel in Las Vegas, Nev., which also is owned by
Elsinore Corp., after his death in 1977. She has said the promotion
was a matter of convenience as employees accepted her as readily as
her popular spouse.
   Mrs. Hood added the job of president of Elsinore's Atlantic City
operations eight years later when the president quit. A month after
her arrival, Playboy Enterprises Inc., a former partner that was
owed money on a promissory note, filed an involuntary bankruptcy
petition against the Atlantis.
   The casino promptly filed for bankruptcy itself, seeking
protection from its 15,000 creditors. Mrs. Hood has candidly
admitted she had no idea what bankruptcy meant at the time.
   In the ensuing years, Mrs. Hood lived full-time at the Atlantis,
returning to her Nevada home occasionally for family visits.
   ``I have the touch and feel of the property,'' she said in a
1988 interview. ``I have my arms around it.''
   But in the casino's final weeks, Mrs. Hood could only watch as
the state handed control to a conservator and then ordered the
Atlantis closed. On one of her final walks through the casino, many
employees called her unflattering names. Mrs. Hood reacted by
smiling and waving.
</TEXT>
