<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-24 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0758</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for durable goods surged 2.9 percent in
April, the biggest advance since December, the government said in a
report that further eased fears of a recession this year but raised
new anxiety about inflation.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that orders for
manufactured goods expected to last three years or more rose to a
seasonally adjusted $129.1 billion last month after a 1 percent
increase in March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The raging dollar's rally eased, reflecting some
profit-taking by money dealers and fresh speculation on what major
central banks might to do stabilize foreign exchange rates.
   Traders surmised Tuesday that the Bank of Japan would soon raise
its discount rate, or the interest it charges on loans to
commercial banks, and that the Fed might ease U.S. rates, both to
stem the dollar's rise.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Federal Reserve official gave no
indication the central bank might ease credit to slow the rise of
the dollar against foreign currencies, saying that curbing
inflation remains the Fed's top priority.
   Fed governor Robert Heller's remarks Tuesday at the National
Economists Club came in response to rapid rise in the dollar's
value, which some economists say has taken pressure off the Fed to
keep interest rates high in order to thwart inflation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four former employees of a now-defunct penny
stock brokerage pleaded guilty in connection with a fraud scheme
that prosecutors say cost customers $67 million.
   The pleas Tuesday in federal district court by the ex-workers in
F.D. Roberts Securities Inc. came against the background of an
avowed federal crackdown on penny stock scams that prosecutors say
is a major part of white-collar crime.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Great Western Financial Corp. accused federal
regulators of unfairly thwarting a plan by the nation's No. 3
savings &amp; loan to leave the thrift industry's federal insurance
fund.
   The lawsuit filed Tuesday against the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board reflected the anger felt by managers of healthy S&amp;Ls who
blame sloppy or dishonest rivals for the crisis in the fund that
insures customers' deposits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines gave America West Airlines one
more day to arrange financing commitments for America West's
proposed $415 million purchase of strike-crippled Eastern's
lucrative Northeast shuttle.
   Eastern attorney Harvey Miller told a federal bankruptcy court
hearing Tuesday that America West had until 5 p.m. Wednesday to
secure commitments, or Eastern _ which already has agreed to a $365
million offer from developer Donald Trump _ would treat the America
West bid as withdrawn.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's political upheaval has prompted many
U.S. companies to postpone visits or evacuate some staff and
dependents until the crisis eases, although none yet appear to be
rethinking long-term strategies for doing business there.
   ``There's a lot of hand-wringing going on. But companies are
intelligent enough not to make decisions in that environment,''
Roger Sullivan, president of the U.S.-China Business Council, said
Tueslday. ``Companies don't react to something like this until they
see the longer-term implications.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic steelmakers, with Congress appearing
certain to extend restrictions on steel imports, still have
questions about the duration and strength of the protection program.
   As steel executives head for their annual conference beginning
Wednesday in Washington, the industry is in the third year of
financial recovery that makes it difficult to look as downtrodden
as steelmakers did when President Reagan imposed five-year import
limits in late 1984.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain has improved soil moisture conditions in
the central and southern Great Plains and has slowed field work in
the eastern Corn Belt and the Delta region, the government said.
   Despite the rainfall in parts of the plains, the outlook for
winter wheat in much of the region continues to be poor, the Joint
Agricultural Weather Facility said Tuesday. Harvest is under way in
several states, including Texas and Oklahoma.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks fell Tuesday over concern about the dollar's strength and
the pace of economic growth. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials fell 24.01 points to 2,478.01.
   Bond prices also eased.
   The dollar turned mixed.
   Gold and silver strengthened slightly. Grain and soybean futures
were mostly lower, livestock prices were higher and pork futures
mixed, and energy prices climbed.
