<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest-PanAm     05-24 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest-Pan Am,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company's Plans for Joint Bid For NWA, Pan Am Questioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. isn't taking seriously a
statement by a New York man who says he heads a group formulating a
proposal to acquire Pan Am and NWA Inc. simultaneously for $4.9
billion.
   The printed statement released in New York on Tuesday said a
company called Trans Global Holdings Inc. was in the final stages
of creating an investor group that might bid up to $130 a share for
NWA and up to $7 per share for Pan Am for the $4.9 billion total.
   In addition, the company would acquire up to 300 new aircraft
for more than $22 billion, the statement said.
   Michael Stern, who was identified as chairman of Trans Global,
declined to elaborate but said in a telephone interview that the
announcement was not a hoax.
   Jeff Kriendler, a Pan Am spokesman, said Stern has shown
previous interest in acquiring Pan Am but has not made a legitimate
bid.
   ``He never has been able to demonstrate any financial support
and in view of that history we would not view this proposal as
being credible either,'' Kriendler said.
   NWA, parent of Northwest Airlines, has been contacted by Stern
but has not received a bid from him, said Kevin Whalen, a spokesman
for the nation's fourth-largest carrier.
   To limit the impact of the Trans Global announcement and provide
time for traders to review it, the New York Stock Exchange halted
trading in shares of the two airlines for about 25 minutes Tuesday
afternoon.
   NYSE spokeswoman Sharon Gamsin later termed Stern's news release
as appearing ``somewhat less than credible.''
   NWA stock closed up $2.12{ at $106 a share. Pan Am rose 37{
cents to $4.75.
   The Trans Global statement said further information could be
forthcoming by next week, but did not indicate who would finance
the plan.
   The statement said a ``major Wall Street investment banking firm
and a major domestic banking institution had indicated an interest
in participating'' in the joint bid. But Stern declined to identify
the institutions and would not provide details about himself when
questioned by telephone.
   The news release described Trans Global as a ``privately held
New York-based holding company.''
   The release said a former senior official of the U.S.
Transportation Department, who was not identified, had expressed
interest in acting as the group's legal adviser. It also stated the
bid would include up to $600 million of equity and would not result
in the breakup of either airline.
   Northwest, which has been a takeover target since late March,
has invited interested buyers to submit bids by May 30. Pan Am
announced May 9 that it might submit an offer, but it was
continuing to seek financing.
   Mike Hamilton, an airline industry analyst for Piper Jaffray &amp;
Hopwood Inc. of Minneapolis, said he never had heard of Trans
Global.
   Curt Kruse, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association at
Northwest, said he had no information on the Trans Global bid.
   ``There's a lot of little outfits coming out of the woodwork
here to try to get their moment in the sun,'' Kruse said. ``(Trans
Global) could be the sultan of Brunei for all we know.''
</TEXT>
