<FIRST>r f PM-Southmark     05-24 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Southmark,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southmark To Sell Integon Insurance Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debt-laden Southmark Corp. has agreed to sell its
largest insurance subsidiary for $135.5 million as it pares down
its holdings and looks for cash.
   Southmark, which is in violation of agreements with holders of
about $1.1 billion in bonds, said Tuesday it had reached agreement
in principle to sell its 89 percent stake in Integon Corp. for
$5.21 a share to a partnership of Jupiter Industries Inc. in
Chicago and Head Insurance Investors LP.
   Integon's other stockholders will receive no less than $22.72
million, or $7 a share, for their holdings under the agreement.
   In addition, Southmark also will receive $30 million in
preferred stock in exchange for the $35 million in preferred stock
it currently holds in Integon.
   Southmark has been shopping Integon, based in Winston-Salem,
N.C., and its other insurance holdings since January when its two
top officers were ousted by outside directors.
   ``The proposed sale of Integon is another step in our efforts to
downsize Southmark through selective asset sales,'' said Chairman
Arthur G. Weiss, brought in to run the company after Chairman Gene
E. Phillips and Vice Chairman William S. Friedman were forced out.
   Southmark spokeswoman Susan Seiter said the sale will help the
company's cash flow, but will not bring it into compliance with net
worth provisions of the outstanding bonds.
   Southmark said two weeks ago stockholders' equity had fallen
from $701 million on June 30, 1988 to a negative $428 million on
March 31. Although the change opens the door for creditors to begin
proceedings to force Southmark into bankruptcy, they have not done
so and Southmark says it can continue to pay interest on the bonds
for some time.
   The sale is subject to further discussions among the parties,
including obtaining fairness opinions and regulatory board approval
of the various companies.
   Integon, with assets of more than $1.4 billion, last week
reported first-quarter income of $4.89 million, compared with last
year's $580 million loss in the first quarter.
   The company markets a diversified line of life insurance and
annuity products, especially property and casualty insurance and
private mortgage insurance through nine subsidiaries. Although most
operations are in the Southeast, it is licensed in 47 states and
the District of Columbia.
   The sale also comes in the midst of a bitter fight for control
of Southmark, which two weeks ago announced a $1.04 billion
quarterly loss due primarily to an $829 million writedown of its
real estate assets.
   Herbert Parks, a Greensboro, N.C., developer and real estate
investor, is leading a proxy fight to win three seats on
Southmark's seven-member board of directors.
</TEXT>
