<FIRST>r f PM-Steel Bjt   05-24 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel, Bjt,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Producers Anxious To See Bush Import Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Conference scheduled to begin at 10 a.m.; Lead prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steelmakers are trying hard not to look
prosperous as they wait for President Bush to unveil his plan for
extending restraints on steel imports.
   Prices are up, but not as high as they were when President
Reagan established five-year quotas on steel imports in late 1984,
domestic producers say as they gather in Washington for their
annual meeting starting today.
   Supplies of certain products are tight, but not because of
Reagan's Voluntary Restraint Agreements. The market is working as
it should, they say.
   ``And they probably made $3 billion last year, so it's kind of
hard to claim injury,'' said Charles Bradford, steel analyst for
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   ``Under the trade rules, they have to be injured'' by imports to
get trade protection, he said.
   ``They have a real problem,'' Bradford said. ``But since Bush
promised, you'd better believe they are going to get it.''
   An extension of Reagan's VRAs was a last-minute campaign promise
by Bush, and during their meeting steel executives are expected to
call on the president to fulfill his pledge promptly.
   Legislation enabling the president to enter another round of
quota agreements with steel-producing nations has 57 co-sponsors in
the Senate, nearly twice the number who sponsored the 1984 quota
bill. The American Iron and Steel Institute counts 231 House
members as co-sponsors.
   With the broad support in Congress for renewal of VRAs, the
industry's big questions concern the duration and strength of the
Bush program, not whether there will be another round of quotas.
   Among options being discussed in Washington is a two-year
version of Reagan's five-year plan. Another option is a four-year
plan that would relax restraints on individual countries as they
eliminate unfair trade practices, according to Richard Bryers,
legislative director for U.S. Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa. No version has
emerged as the most popular.
   Bush is expected to unveil his quota plan as early as June.
   There is little debate that the industry has healed during the
last 4{ years, although some authorities argue the turnaround was
less the result of import quotas as of industry streamlining,
equipment upgrading and the weakening of the dollar.
   Average employment edged higher by about 6,000 jobs to 168,900
workers in 1988, the first yearly increase since 1979, according to
the American Iron and Steel Institute.
   Following losses of $12 billion from 1982 to 1986, the industry
had operating profits of $1 billion in 1987 and $3 billion in 1988.
   Exports are rising, reviving an outlet that was largely closed
to U.S. producers for much of the 1980s.
   The improvement is largely a result of a swing in the value of
the dollar compared with other currencies. When the dollar was
strong against other currencies, U.S. goods were more expensive
overseas and imports were cheaper in the United States.
   Bethlehem Steel Corp., the second-largest U.S. producer, this
month agreed to raise wages and benefits in a tentative agreement
with the United Steelworkers that is being criticized on Wall
Street as too generous.
   The agreement also could set a pattern for talks between the USW
and other steelmakers. Just two years ago, Bethlehem explored its
options under a possible bankruptcy filing.
</TEXT>
