<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Fall Sharply, But Off Lows By Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were sharply lower but recovering
from an earlier plunge by midday Wednesday as the bearish effect of
a rise in British interest rates was offset by indications economic
growth has slowed.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was off 26.7
points, or 1.2 percent, at 2,124.9, by about 12:15 p.m. in London.
It was above the morning low of 33.3 points down, which came a few
minutes after the Bank of England signaled a rise in base rates to
14 percent from 13 percent.
   The central bank prompted the interest rate hike after the
recent plunge in the pound started to threaten the British
government's anti-inflationary strategy.
   But the late-morning news that British retail sales volume fell
a surprising 1.4 percent in April gave some comfort to the market,
suggesting that previous measures to slow the economy were having
the desired effect.
   Paul Walton, an equity analyst at the London investment firm
Warburg Securities, said 14 percent base rates probably would be
sufficient to counter inflation, without denting corporate profits
too much.
   ``This will be the final turn of the screw,'' Walton said.
   Volume came to 306.9 million shares by midday, compared with 245
million shares at the same time Tuesday.
