<FIRST>r f PM-ITTReductions     05-24 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ITT Reductions,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>ITT To Cut International Rates to 27 Countries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International telephone rates for the
first minute to 27 countries will drop by as much as 9 percent on
June 1, ITT Communications Services has announced.
   The rate reductions will apply during the standard daytime
period, which covers the hours of business for the country being
called, Amy Arutt, a company spokeswoman, said Tuesday.
   Calls from the continental United States will fall 9 percent for
the first minute to Germany, Guatemala and Panama.
   Telephone service will be reduced 8 percent for the first minute
to Chile, Colombia, Costa Rica, the Dominican Republic, Ecuador, El
Salvador, Finland, France, Guam, India, Ireland, Japan, Monaco, The
Netherlands, Peru, the Phillipines and Venezuela.
   A 7 percent cut will be in effect for calls to Australia,
Singapore and Taiwan, while rates drop 6 percent to Argentina,
Denmark, Sweden and the United Kingdom.
   Ms. Arutt said the lower rates were in line with similar
telephone decreases elsewhere in the industry, and would be used to
increase international calling by customers.
</TEXT>
