<FIRST>r f PM-Prop103-Aetna     05-24 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prop 103-Aetna,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aetna to Resume Writing New Policies Following Prop. 103 Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aetna Life and Casualty officials say the
company will resume writing new property and casualty insurance
policies in California.
   The announcement follows a moratorium on new policies that began
after the California Supreme Court upheld most of Proposition 103
two weeks ago.
   The Hartford-based insurance company reversed itself because the
Department of Insurance is interpreting the measure in a way
``consistent with the court ruling, which clearly permits a fair
return on our business and permits us to petition for relief from
Proposition 103 rate rollbacks,'' said Aetna spokesman Jason Wright.
   Aetna was the only insurer to stop writing new policies after
the court ruling. It continued to renew policies of existing
customers.
   The court ruled that the 20 percent rate rollback imposed by
Proposition 103 is constitutional but it said insurers must first
be allowed to earn a ``fair return'' on their investments.
   The Department of Insurance has since issued a detailed form
that insurers must complete by June 3 if they want to be exempted
from the rate cut. Insurance Commissioner Roxani Gillespie has
promised that decisions will be made by November.
   Aetna is the ninth-largest property and casualty insurer in
California. Auto insurance makes up a small portion of the
company's business.
</TEXT>
