<SECOND>PM-Steel Talks,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Close To Labor Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Steel Corp. and the United
Steelworkers say they are nearing a tentative agreement on a new
labor contract.
   ``They're getting real close,'' said Robert Toothman, spokesman
for the nation's sixth largest steelmaker.
   ``We were close with Bethlehem too, but everybody went back
home,'' said union spokesman Don Dalena.
   Dalena agreed, however, that the negotiators are close to a
settlement to replace a contract that expires July 31.
   The presidents of union locals at National's three plants are
scheduled to meet at 7 p.m. today, presumably to review contract
terms.
   A settlement at National would be the second among four major
producers whose contracts expire this year. Results of a
secret-ballot vote by the 20,500 USW members at No. 2 Bethlehem are
due this week.
   National employs about 7,300 union members at plants in St.
Louis, Portage, Ind., and Ecorse, Mich.
