<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   05-24 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Gives America West Extra Time To Line Up Financing</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS 2 grafs at end to UPDATE with Eastern president's remarks;
No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America West Airlines has been given a deadline
to line up financing commitments for its proposed $415 million
purchase of Eastern Airline's lucrative Northeast shuttle or see
its offer fail.
   Eastern on Tuesday gave America West until 5 p.m. today to
arrange the financing or Eastern would treat the offer as
withdrawn. Strikebound Eastern already has agreed to a $365 million
offer for the shuttle from developer Donald Trump.
   Eastern attorney Harvey Miller announced the deadline during an
abbreviated hearing before U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland.
All parties in Eastern's bankruptcy case _ including the airline's
unions and creditors _ were expected to discuss the competing
offers for the Washington-New York-Boston shuttle.
   But Tuesday's court session lasted 20 minutes, and followed a
brief hearing Monday when Miller told Lifland that Eastern still
had questions about America West's financing for the shuttle
purchase.
   The parties were to return to court Thursday morning. If America
West has arranged its financing commitments by this afternoon's
deadline, Lifland must determine whether they are satisfactory
before both offers for the shuttle are considered further. Lifland
must approve any sale of Eastern assets.
   America West also must win approval from the Port Authority of
New York and New Jersey as a tenant at LaGuardia Airport. The Port
Authority's board of governors is scheduled to meet Thursday
afternoon.
   If America West is unable to line up financing, the parties will
consider only the Trump offer, Miller said.
   Trump's agreement with Eastern expires at midnight Friday and he
said Monday he would not raise his bid or extend the offer past the
deadline.
   America West, based in Phoenix, is offering Eastern $415 million
for the shuttle and $336 million for 10 Boeing 757s. Alternatively,
America West would buy only the shuttle's gates and landing slots
in the three airports for $375 million, without 21 Boeing 727s that
are included in Trump's deal.
   The 21 727s, which are older than the 757s, have an estimated
value of up to $80 million.
   Eastern filed for Chapter 11 protection from its creditors after
the Machinists union struck the airline March 4. Pilots and flight
attendants are honoring the walkout, forcing Eastern to cut back
its flight schedule by 90 percent.
   Two investor groups, one headed by Chicago commodities trader
Joseph Ritchie and the other led by former Piedmont Airlines
chairman William Howard, have submitted formal bids for the entire
airline.
   Chicago-based Midway Airlines Inc. on Tuesday indicated it had
contacted Eastern to express its interest in buying certain
properties, including facilities at the Philadelphia airport and
Eastern routes from Philadelphia to Montreal and Toronto.
   The unions want the airline sold as one entity. But Texas Air
Corp., Eastern's parent, wants to sell $1.8 billion of the
airline's assets and operate as a smaller carrier.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes said today in Atlanta the carrier
must become streamlined before it can be saved, and said pilots who
walked out in sympathy with striking Machinists may not have jobs
when the airline recovers.
   Bakes told a group of travel industry representatives that while
there are no plans to liquidate Eastern, the airline would need to
part with the $1.8 billion in assets to become financially solvent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
