<FIRST>r f BC-AutoIncentives     05-24 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Incentives,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Offers Rebates on Continental; Bigger Ones on Small Cars</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Only version planned.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. confirmed Wednesday it had
notified dealers to offer Lincoln Continental buyers $1,000 rebates
to fight a move by General Motors Corp. on its Cadillac luxury cars.
   The incentive ``is purely a competitive action,'' Ford spokesman
Ray Windecker said. The offer, the first time Ford has had rebates
on the Continental, took effect last week. The company has a 56-day
supply of Continentals on hand, which is not unusual, he added.
   GM has been offering $1,000 or $2,000 rebates on some of
Cadillacs since May 17. Those incentives expire May 31, a week
before other GM offers run out.
   The Continental rebates continue indefinitely, while other Ford
incentives expire at month's end. Other incentives give buyers the
choice of cash or low-interest financing.
   Meantime, Ford also said Wednesday that rebates for some of its
smaller cars, including the Ford Escort and Festiva and the Mercury
Tracer, will be increased by at least $100 each.
</TEXT>
