<FIRST>r f PM-Motorola-Patents 1stLd-Writethru   05-24 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Motorola-Patents, 1st Ld-Writethru,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Commission to Investigate Patent-Infringement Claim</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf with 2 grafs of comment from Tandy, Nokia.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. International Trade Commission
plans to investigate a cellular telephone patent-infringement
complaint filed by Motorola Inc. against Tandy Corp. and Nokia
Corp., Motorola officials say.
   ``We are gratified by the ITC's action and its continued concern
for intellectual property rights,'' Robert N. Weisshappel, a
Motorola vice president said Tuesday. ``We look forward to a quick
resolution of these proceedings.''
   In April, Motorola filed a complaint with the ITC against Nokia
and Tandy, seeking to stop imports into the United States of
cellular phones that Motorola contends infringe seven of its
patents.
   Motorola has asked the ITC to stop Nokia and Tandy from
importing the disputed telephones, primarily from South Korea.
   Motorola officials said they expect the ITC to hold hearings on
their request for preliminary relief in July, and further hearings
on their request for permanent relief in December.
   Motorola, based in this northwest Chicago suburb, also filed a
complaint in U.S. District Court in Chicago seeking a permanent
injunction and unspecified monetary damages, citing patent
infringement.
   Named in the ITC action are Nokia Corp. of Helsinki, Finland;
Nokia-Mobira Oy of Salo, Finland; Nokia, Inc. of Basking Ridge,
N.J.; Nokia-Mobira Inc. of Largo, Fla.; Tandy Mobira Communications
of South Korea, and Tandy Corp. and A&amp;A International, both of Fort
Worth, Texas.
   ``The ITC's vote is no indication of infringement, but to
proceed with the investigtion,'' Jim Sheets, a deputy general
council for Tandy, said today.
   ``We claim that what they say is without foundation,'' said
Nokia spokesman Dave Scott. ``We are confident our cellular
telephones do not infringe on any of Motorola's patents, and will
vigorously defend ourselves against their claims.''
   Motorola is one of the world's leading manufacturers of
electronics equipment, systems and components for world markets.
Its products include two-way radios, pagers, cellular telephone
systems, defense and aerospace electronics, and equipment for
processing and handling information.
</TEXT>
