<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     05-24 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose Wednesday against all key
currencies except the British pound in nervous European trading.
Gold prices fell.
   Currency dealers said the dollar steadied in late trading after
fluctuating over a broad range throughout the day.
   After concerted central bank intervention Tuesday and overnight
dollar-selling by the Bank of Japan, no central bank besides the
Bank of England was sighted in the European open market Wednesday.
   ``It's been very confusing today,'' said a trader at a major
U.S. bank in Frankfurt, West Germany. ``It's been up and down, up
and down. It's hard to figure what's going on.''
   The British pound, which has lost 14 percent in value against
the dollar this year, edged up to $1.5695 from $1.5675 late Tuesday
after the Bank of England hiked the base lending rates from 13
percent to a four-year high of 14 percent.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.05 Japanese yen to a closing 143.00 yen,
a 19-month high. Later, in London, it eased to 142.78 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Tuesday:
2.0115 West German marks, up from 2.0079; 1.7887 Swiss francs, up
from 1.7820; 6.8250 French francs, up from 6.7865; 2.2670 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.2570; 1,455.75 Italian lire, up from 1,451.50;
and 1.1985 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1975.
   Gold bullion fell in London to a late bid of $362.75 a troy
ounce from $364.25 bid late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold fell to
$362.60 an ounce from $364.25 bid late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose five cents to a closing bid of
$364.02 an ounce.
   Silver bullion lost most of Tuesday's gains, dropping to $5.18 a
troy ounce from $5.26.
</TEXT>
