<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0029 05-24 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0029,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Share Prices Close Lower After British Interest Rate Hike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with closing prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell sharply Wednesday on the London
Stock Exchange following a rise in key British lending rates.
   But the market finished near its highest levels of the day as
the pound strengthened and traders speculated that Thursday's
British trade report wouldn't bring any bearish surprises.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 18.9
points, or 0.9 percent, to close at 2,132.7, slightly below its
best level of the day.
   The index plunged as much as 33.3 points shortly after the Bank
of England signaled the rise in interest rates in the morning.
British banks raised their base lending rates by 1 percentage point
to 14 percent.
   The Financial Times 30-share index fell 13.4 points to 1,774.0,
and the Financial Times 500-share index fell 9.68 points to close
at 1,214.97.
   Volume fell to 468.3 million shares from Tuesday's 557.5 million
shares.
   The rise in British interest rates came after the recent plunge
in the pound had started to threaten the British government's
anti-inflationary strategy. The 100-share index has lost 72 points,
or 3.3 perent, since the beginning of the week on worries that
rates were about to go higher.
   ``The currency markets have really forced it (the rate rise)
upon us,'' one London equities dealer said.
   The market found some comfort, however, in news that British
retail sales volume fell an unexpected 1.4 percent in April,
suggesting that previous measures to slow down the economy were
already having the desired effect.
</TEXT>
