<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     05-24 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Three Sales Up 2.3 Percent in Mid-May</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version expected by 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three automakers reported sales of cars
and light trucks rose 2.3 percent in mid-May compared with the same
period last year.
   Sales during the latest mid-May period were helped by incentives
programs by General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp.
The Big Three's incentive plans expired just as the mid-May period
began a year ago.
   The companies said they sold cars and trucks at an average daily
rate of 37,126 during the May 11-20 period this year, compared with
an average daily rate of 36,299 during the same time last year.
   Car sales rose 2.3 percent and sales of light trucks were up 2.2
percent.
   On May 11, 1988, large portions of the Big Three's incentive
packages expired. The selling rate during the first 10-day period
of May 1988 was stronger than what proved to be the annual rate,
partly because people accelerated their buying plans to take
advantage of the incentives.
   This year, the Big Three initiated incentive programs in late
March or early April. Ford's expires May 31 and GM's June 5.
Chrysler's incentive program runs indefinitely.
   So far this year, the Big Three have sold cars and trucks at an
average daily rate of 34,501, down 5.3 percent from the rate of
36,412 during the period last year.
   Between New Year's Day and May 20, car sales have fallen 7.7
percent and truck sales have dropped 1 percent on a year-to-year
comparison.
   Cars sold by Ford at an average daily rate of 7,616 during the
period this month, compared with 7,410 last year, a 2.8 percent
increase. Car sales so far this year were running 0.5 percent
behind last year's rate. Ford's mid-May truck sales were 6.1
percent higher than the rate during the period last year and, for
the year, were running 2.9 percent behind last year's pace.
   GM said its cars sold at a daily rate of 11,895 during mid-May
this year, up 2.6 percent from the daily rate of 11,592 during the
period last year. GM's year-to-date car sales were down 9.6
percent. Truck sales in mid-May were up 4.6 percent and down 0.1
percent for the entire year.
   Chrysler said its cars sold in mid-May at a daily rate of 3,378
this year, or 0.2 percent ahead of the 3,372-car-per-day rate
during the period last year. So far this year, the No. 3
automaker's car sales were running 15.6 percent behind last year's
rate. Truck sales were off 6.4 percent in mid-May and 0.4 percent
ahead of the pace during the same time last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
