<DOCNO> AP890524-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Stocks-Economy Bjt   05-24 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stocks-Economy, Bjt,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Cheery Message From Wall Street?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you believe the optimists of Wall Street, the
stock market is sending out a happy message for the American
economy these days.
   The crash of 1987 is fading fast into history, without having
caused much trouble outside the world of Wall Street itself.
   And the economy, which hasn't suffered an official recession in
seven years, appears to be sailing into the 1990s with its momentum
intact and no slump in sight.
   But the six-month-old rally in stock prices that has helped
engender this kind of enthusiasm still has its skeptics. In fact,
they maintain, investors in the securities markets have drifted
into a dream world that could be setting them up for another rude
shock.
   From the middle of November through the end of last week, the
Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose almost 23 percent,
surpassing the 2,500 level for the first time since a week before
the Black Monday crash of Oct. 19, 1987.
   The average, which is the oldest and best known measure of
market trends, has moved within striking distance of the high of
2,722.42 it reached on Aug. 25, 1987.
   By some gauges that include dividends as well as the level of
stock prices, the market already has recouped all its 1987 losses
and has reached new peaks, maintains Norman Fosback, editor of the
investment advisory letter Market Logic in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   Any way it's measured, it has been a remarkable comeback _
especially considering that it took stocks 25 years to recover from
the crash of 1929.
   The rally has drawn support from a spreading belief that the
Federal Reserve Board has found a way to steer the economy safely
past the threat of rising inflation without causing any serious
slump in production, consumption or investment.
   It also has bolstered the case of ``new wave'' economists who
believe that the system, for a variety of reasons, is now able to
withstand the forces that used to drive it into a cyclical decline
every four years or so.
   ``The new wave is on a roll,'' declares one of its most
prominent proponents, Edward Yardeni at the investment firm of
Prudential-Bache Securities.
   ``Of course, inflation is still a problem. But there are many
recent developments that should help to offset such business cycle
pressures as high capacity utilization and low unemployment, which
in the past pushed inflation higher.''
   Meanwhile, corporate earnings, a primary long-term determinant
of stock market trends, have risen sharply in the past couple of
years.
   ``The market has far firmer foundations now than when it last
moved to this general level in mid-1987,'' Fosback says.
   But a vocal group of dissenters calls this kind of reasoning not
only dubious but dangerous.
   ``Players in the stock market are dancing to a tune only they
can hear,'' says Erich Heinemann, chief economist at Ladenburg,
Thalmann &amp; Co.
   ``When tight money bites in earnest, repercussions will ripple
through the entire economy. In many ways, the atmosphere in Wall
Street reminds us of the summer of 1987, just prior to the market
meltdown.''
   Says Raymond F. DeVoe Jr., an analyst at Legg Mason Wood Walker
Inc.: ``The slowdown in the economy currently under way is supposed
to make a `soft landing' without going into recession.
   ``Several new bull market scenarios call for `the nicest
recession you've ever seen' that would lower interest rates and
cause foreign money to come surging into the U.S. stock market.
   ``In our view this all sounds like `deja voodoo' _ the best of
all possible worlds. There is a recession out there somewhere in
time and all the `new era' or `new wave' rhetoric won't make it go
away.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Chet Currier has covered the stock market for The
Associated Press since 1974.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
