<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-24 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Market Drifts Lower As Growing Conditions Improve</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean future prices drifted lower
Wednesday in moderate trading on the Chicago Board of Trade as
rainfall in growing areas improved the prospects for good crops.
   ``The price of the new crop corn and soybeans were reflecting
enhanced soil moisture,'' said Ted Mao, an analyst for Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Soybean futures suffered as some private forecasts suggested
that the National Weather Service 6- to 10-day outlook will
indicate above-normal rain in crop areas.
   But wheat prices were up on news from exporters that Egypt
bought about 300,000 metric tons of U.S. soft red winter and soft
white wheat.
   Corn prices were mostly lower, but up from the day's low because
of technical support and spillover from a rally in soybean futures.
   ``As is the case in general, the market tends to overdo
itself,'' Mao said. ``We went from inflated levels to levels low
enough that we assume we will have an above average crop. The
growing season is still a long one.''
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents lower to 3} cents higher with
the price for delivery in July at $3.92\ a bushel; corn was 3\
cents to 5} cents lower with delivery in July at $2.61}; oats were
1 cent to 2 cents lower with July at $1.73{ a bushel; soybeans were
2 cents to 8 cents lower with July at $6.96{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
