<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   05-24 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mid-May Sales Up Slightly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and truck sales rose a modest 2.7 percent in
mid-May from the same period last year, manufacturers reported
Wednesday, although analysts noted the sales compared with a
year-earlier period that may have been slower than usual.
   During the May 11-20 period, sales of cars and light trucks made
by the eight major U.S.-based automakers rose to a rate of 39,360 a
day from a pace of 38,334 during the same period last year.
   Last year many buyer incentives expired May 11, prompting some
consumers to hasten purchase plans in order to take advantage of
the deals. That effectively borrowed purchases from later sales
periods.
   In the May 11-20 period this year, wide-ranging incentive
programs by General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co., Chrysler Corp.
and some of the other major automakers were in effect.
   But analyst Mary Anne Sudol of Fitch Investors Service Inc. in
New York said consumers seemed to be ignoring the bait.
   ``I don't know what it's going to take to bring customers back
to the showrooms,'' she said. ``I think demand is just tired at
this point.''
   Tom Webb, a senior economist with the National Automobile
Dealers Association in McLain, Va., said: ``Basically, what sales
have shown is that the underlying demand is less than what most
people expected. Given those sales, there's going to have to be
some further (production) cuts. They would be modest, though.''
   Automakers have been trimming their inventories by offering
incentives to spur sales and by cutting production.
   Ford spokesman Bill Carroll said that on May 31, when the
company's current incentive program expires, he expected another,
more limited incentive package to be announced.
   GM's program ends June 5 and Chrysler's continues indefinitely.
   The incentive programs were prompted by slower-than-anticipated
sales during the first three months of the year.
   Through May 20, car and truck sales by the eight makers were 3.6
percent behind the pace during the same period last year, which was
the second-best in automotive history. Car sales were down 5.4
percent and truck sales were down 0.3 percent.
   Ford sold cars at an average daily rate of 7,616 during May
11-20 this year, up 2.8 percent from the 7,410 rate a year earlier.
Car sales for the year to date period were 0.5 percent behind last
year's rate. Ford's mid-May truck sales were 6.1 percent higher
than the rate during the period last year and, for the year, were
running 2.9 percent behind last year's pace.
   GM cars sold at a daily rate of 11,895 during mid-May this year,
up 2.6 percent from 11,592 during the year-earlier period. GM's
year-to-date car sales were down 9.6 percent. GM truck sales in
mid-May were up 4.6 percent and down 0.1 percent for the year to
date.
   Chrysler said its cars sold in mid-May at a daily rate of 3,378
this year, up 0.2 percent from the 3,372 daily rate during the
year-earlier period. For the year to date the No. 3 automaker's car
sales were 15.6 percent behind last year's rate. Truck sales were
off 6.4 percent in mid-May and 0.4 percent ahead of the year to
date pace a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890524-0308 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-GreenStampBlues Adv26   05-24 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Green Stamp Blues, Adv 26,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Friday, May 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Green Stamps Hope to Lick Falling Popularity With High-Tech Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gladys Stern held a peanut butter
jar in one hand and in the other she clutched the notice that
Publix Super Markets Inc. was abandoning green stamps. She took it
hard.
   Stern was on the front lines of making Fort Lauderdale the top
green stamp redemption area for Sperry and Hutchinson Co. since the
mid 1980s. For years, Stern had been turning S&amp;H green stamp books
into toasters, a breakfast set and dozens of other gadgets and
knickknacks.
   ``And now no more? Are they serious? Who decided this?'' she
said.
   The decision by S&amp;H's largest customer to drop green stamps from
its South Florida stores this Saturday reflects the troubles and
transitions at the 94-year-old trading stamp stalwart, which is
banking on high-technology ventures such as plastic shopper ID
cards to adapt to changing consumer habits. They say the days of
pasting stamps in saver books may be numbered.
   In the past two decades, green stamps have gone the way of the
beauty shop-groomed housewife. They now are largely a symbol of
nostalgia.
   In 1969, more than 77 percent of supermarkets and 20 percent of
service stations gave out green stamps. Today, the sticky green
strips are available in less than 7 percent of check-out lines and
in less than 1 percent of the gas stations.
   ``People just don't go home and lick stamps anymore,'' said Bill
Schroter, spokesman for Publix, which accounted for 35 percent of
green stamp sales nationwide last year. ``There's been a steady
decline in interest in green stamps.''
   Publix, the nation's ninth-largest supermarket chain with 361
Florida stores, cut green stamps in 1986 from its southwest Florida
stores and followed suit in northern Florida the following year.
The high concentration of elderly green stamp loyalists in South
Florida kept the program going until this month, said Schroter.
   ``Many of our younger customers didn't even know what green
stamps were,'' he said. ``It's a thing of the past that doesn't fit
in well anymore.''
   Like other supermarkets around the country, Lakeland-based
Publix have been experimenting with other shopper incentives, such
as a frequent-buyer award system the using a credit card-type
device to log visits.
   Market researchers at New York-based S&amp;H agree their traditional
following has been eroded by the popularity of discount coupons and
an increase in working couples too busy to deal with stamp books.
   Since the heydays of the late 1960s, when stores paid more than
$360 million for the postage-size presents, there are now less than
2,000 supermarkets, truck stops and other outlets that pay to carry
the stamps, and S&amp;H's revenue is down to $130 million, according to
published reports.
   S&amp;H declines to give figures on sales and jealously guards
details about its new projects.
   ``It's no secret we've been losing stores. The question is how
are we going to react,'' said a senior S&amp;H executive who spoke on
the condition of anonymity.
   The New York-based holding company Leucadia National Corp.
acquired S&amp;H in 1986 along with its purchase of PHLCORP Inc.,
formerly Baldwin United Corp.
   With little change in operations since the last century _ with
the exception of self-adhesive stamps in 1986 and the addition of
upscale items to its catalog _ the company plans to make startling
changes perhaps has early as this year.
   Shoppers across the nation may soon see S&amp;H cards with magnetic
strips to record purchases. The points will be tendered for gifts
of cash. A full green stamp book is currently worth $1.20.
   In a recent article in Advertising Age magazine, S&amp;H marketing
director George Simpson said 95 percent of customers at Weis
Markets in Pennsylvania accepted the plastic cards, and 87 percent
used them to build points for rebates or items.
   Also, the company is studying use of a sophisticated data base
to record the type of items purchased or garner demographics, such
as sex and age.
   ``We're going electronic,'' the S&amp;H executive said. ``We're not
standing still.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Friday, May 26</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
