<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold Bjt   05-24 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, Bjt,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Up In New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar resumed its climb against all key
currencies except the British pound and Swiss franc Wednesday,
breaking the 143-yen level overseas and hitting a 1{-year high vs.
the Japanese currency in domestic trading.
   ``It's like a train. You can't step in front of it or you'll get
run over,'' said one investment banker, Jay Goldinger of Beverly
Hills-based Capital Insight Inc.
   Meanwhile, gold prices were up domestically after losing in
Europe and rising in Hong Kong. Republic National Bank of New York
said the late bid for a troy ounce of gold was $362.40, up 55 cents
from Tuesday's close.
   Currency dealers said trading was volatile here and overseas,
with the dollar starting out weak after a mixed performance Tuesday
but ending stronger in the absence of significant central-bank
intervention or signs of policy changes geared toward stabilizing
exchange rates.
   The British government boosted interest rates, which helped the
sagging pound. But dealers said there was no indication that either
West Germany or the United States would change their rates, and
they said that helped strengthen the dollar.
   Traders said the dollar firmed after reports of West German
Bundesbank officials dismissing speculation that they would hold an
emergency policy-setting meeting to possibly raise interest rates
to support the mark.
   Further helping the dollar, they said, were President Bush's
comments that he was concerned about the dollar's rise but remained
confident exchange rates could stabilize through coordination
between the Group of Seven. The G-7 includes the United States,
Britain, Germany, France, Japan, Italy and Canada.
   The dollar has risen sharply in recent days for several reasons,
including the comparably high U.S. interest rates, growing
inflation overseas and perceived weakness among the G-7 in
foreign-exchange policies.
   After concerted central bank intervention Tuesday and
dollar-selling by the Bank of Japan on Wednesday, no central bank
besides the Bank of England was evident in the European open market
Wednesday.
   The British pound, which has lost 14 percent in value against
the dollar this year, edged up to $1.5695 from $1.5675 in London
late Tuesday after the Bank of England hiked a key lending rate
from 13 percent to a four-year high of 14 percent.
   Sterling fetched $1.5700 in New York, up from $1.5645.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.05 Japanese yen to a closing 143.00 yen,
a 19-month high. It eased to 142.78 yen in London, and closed at
142.775 yen in New York, up from 142.30 Tuesday. Traders said the
New York close was the highest since October 1987.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday,
included: 2.0137 West German marks, up from 2.0110; 1.7855 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7915; 1.20845 Canadian dollars, up from
1.19945; 6.8225 French francs, up from 6.8100; and 1,459.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,457.50.
   Dollar rates in Europe compared with late Tuesday: 2.0115 West
German marks, up from 2.0079; 1.7887 Swiss francs, up from 1.7820;
6.8250 French francs, up from 6.7865; 2.2670 Dutch guilders, up
from 2.2570; 1,455.75 Italian lire, up from 1,451.50; and 1.1985
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1975.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $364.50 a troy ounce from $363.80 Tuesday.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $362.75 an ounce from
$364.25 late Tuesday. It fell in Zurich to $362.60 an ounce from
$364.25.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose five cents to a closing bid of
$364.02 an ounce.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex silver bullion for
current delivery rose marginally to $5.178 a troy ounce from $5.173
Tuesday. Silver bullion lost most of Tuesday's gains in London,
dropping to $5.18 a troy ounce from $5.26.
</TEXT>
