<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-24 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Rise As OPEC Meeting Nears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices climbed Wednesday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, reflecting increased confidence that the OPEC
nations will agree on production quotas for later this year.
   On other markets, grain and soybean prices drifted lower,
precious metals finished mixed, and livestock and pork prices
plunged.
   There had been speculation in the energy market that the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would be unable to
agree at its June meeting on production quotas for the second half
of the year. There is greater confidence now, reflected in prices,
that an agreement will be reached, said Robert Baker, an energy
analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 44 cents to 62 cents
higher with the contract for delivery in July at $19.66 a barrel;
heating oil was 1.75 cents to 2.11 cents higher with June at 49.61
cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was 1.13 cents to 2.59 cents
higher with June at 66.83 cents a gallon.
   Baker said the sharp rise in energy prices also can be
attributed to a report from the American Petroleum Institute that
total oil stocks in the United States are down 9 million to 10
million barrels.
   Traders also reacted to reports that Norwegian helicopter pilots
servicing Norway's North Sea oil platforms could go on strike. A
prolonged strike would cut deeply into Norway's 1.5 million barrel
daily North Sea oil production, Baker said.
   Grain and soybean futures drifted lower on the Chicago Board of
Trade as rain continued to fall in growing areas.
   ``The price of the new crop corn and soybeans were reflecting
enhanced soil moisture,'' said Ted Mao, an analyst for Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Soybean futures suffered as some private forecasts suggested
that the National Weather Service 6- to 10-day outlook will
indicate above-normal rain in crop areas.
   Wheat prices were up with news from exporters that Egypt bought
about 300,000 metric tons of U.S. soft red winter and soft white
wheat.
   Corn prices were down, but up from the day's low because of
technical support and spillover from a rally in soybean futures.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents lower to 3} cents higher with July at
$3.98} a bushel; corn was 3 cents to 5} cents lower with July at
$2.62; oats were 1{ cents to 2 cents lower with July at $1.73{ a
bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 7{ cents lower with July at $6.97\
a bushel.
   Precious metals prices were up a fraction in fairly quiet
trading on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   ``The precious metals market is still concerned about the
strength of the dollar,'' said Fred Demler, a metals analyst with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   ``The market is oversold, but the feeling is prices will
continue on the down side,'' Demler said.
   Gold settled 20 cents to 60 cents higher with June at $364.70;
silver was unchanged with June at $5.181.
   Copper, which has given up nine cents this week, was down again
Wednesday .50 cent to .70 cent with May at $1.08 a pound.
   Increases in exchange inventories, high world-wide production
and low industrial consumption is pushing down copper prices,
Demler said.
   Livestock futures were sharply lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   The drop in the cattle market was caused by stop-loss selling
and computer fund liquidation, said Paul Hare an analyst with
Linnco Futures Inc. in Chicago.
   The drop was assisted by a weak cash market outlook.
   Pork futures reacted negatively to heavy movement of bellies
into storage and heavy hog marketings this week.
   Live cattle settled .10 cent to 1.10 cents lower with June at
69.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .65 cent lower
with May at 76.72 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to .62 cent
lower with June at 48.45 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
1.17 cents to 1.70 cents lower with July at 33.10 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
