<FIRST>u f AM-Avon 2ndLd-Writethru   05-24 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avon, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon Shares Bid Higher on Report of Possible New Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after lead, ADDS 5 grafs to end with congressman
asking FTC to investigate Avon stock purchases; EDITS to conform; No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock speculators renewed their interest in Avon
Products Inc. Wednesday, bidding the cosmetics company's shares
higher in response to a report that Avon may be the target of a
hostile takeover attempt.
   Separately, a congressman asked the Federal Trade Commission to
investigate Avon stock purchases prior to a failed bid by Amway
Corp. on grounds that investor Irwin L. Jacobs and Amway executives
may have sought to skirt antitrust laws.
   Avon stock closed up $1.37{ to $35.87{ in composite trading on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 3.13 million shares changing
hands. Composite trading volume in Avon stock on Tuesday amounted
to 962,100 shares.
   The catalyst for the heavy trading appeared to be a report
published in USA Today that said Jacobs and an unidentified ``major
company'' plan to launch a joint bid for Avon at $40 a share.
   A secretary in Jacobs' office in Minneapolis said he was out of
town and unavailable to comment.
   The newspaper said Jacobs and the company are in the process of
completing financing and other details of the hostile offer.
Jacobs' partner was said to be a company other than Mary Kay Corp.,
a Dallas-based cosmetics seller that reportedly has expressed an
interest in Avon.
   Jacobs owns 10.3 percent of Avon's common stock through a
partnership with Amway. Amway, an Ada, Mich.-based direct selling
firm last week withdrew its $39-a-share offer for Avon after Avon's
board rejected the proposal.
   USA Today said if Jacobs and his partner prevail over Avon,
Jacobs would meld part of Avon's business into his Watkins Products
Inc., which sells vitamins, beauty products and foods door-to-door.
   Avon spokesman John Cox said the company had no comment on the
report.
   One Wall Street arbitrager said the report was treated with some
skepticism and didn't trigger as much buying as it might have if
the memory of the losses sustained when Amway withdrew its proposal
weren't still fresh in speculators' minds.
   Avon stock surged to a 52-week high of $41.25 shortly after
Amway's May 10 bid amid hope that the bid might be increased. When
Amway pulled out the stock sank.
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce Committee, on Wednesday asked the FTC to investigate Avon
stock purchases by Jacobs and Amway executives prior to Amway's bid.
   Antitrust laws require that a proposed merger must be reported
if the acquirer holds 15 percent or more of the target's voting
stock.
   ``In the case of the attempted Avon takeover, Mr. Jacobs and
Amway appear to have sought to avoid this requirement by arranging
for the purchase of Avon stock in the name of the A-J
Partnership,'' Dingell wrote in a letter to FTC Chairman Daniel
Oliver.
   A-J Partnership was the vehicle used by Jacobs and Amway to
launch their takeover bid.
   Jacobs and Amway have said there was nothing illegal or improper
about their stock transactions.
</TEXT>
