<FIRST>u f AM-AircraftOrders Bjt   05-24 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aircraft Orders, Bjt,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>All Nippon, American Eagle Announce Aircraft Purchases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   All Nippon Airways Co. Ltd. has ordered 10 Boeing jetliners and
taken options to buy 10 more in a deal estimated at $1.5 billion,
while regional carrier AMR Eagle Inc. said separately Wednesday it
plans to buy up to 100 Saab turboprop commuter aircraft in an
agreement analysts valued at $750 million.
   All Nippon, Japan's largest carrier and the eighth-largest in
the non-communist world, said in Los Angeles it was ordering and
taking options on Boeign 767-300 jetliners.
   The airline, which sets up its 767-300s to carry about 275
passengers, plans to use the planes for medium-range foreign and
domestic flights, said spokesman Tim Winship.
   The first plane is scheduled for delivery in 1990, with
deliveries through 1995, said Winship.
   In February, ANA ordered 20 Boeing 747-400s worth about $3.2
billion.
   The value of the latest order would reach $1.5 billion if all 10
options are exercised and engines and spare parts are included, the
airline said.
   AMR Eagle, the regional airline partner of Ft. Worth,
Texas-based American Airlines, AMR Eagle Inc., on Wednesday
announced plans to purchase up to 100 Saab 340B turboprop aircraft.
   AMR Eagle placed 50 firm orders and took options for another 50
Saab 340Bs, which can carry 34 passengers each on trips of 700
statute miles or more.
   Also in the agreement with the Saab Aircraft Division of
Saab-Scania AB are 50 options for the Saab 2000, a 50-seat
aircraft. Deliveries would extend into the 1990s.
   ``These aircraft will meet our needs well into the next century
and provide our passengers with the finest plane of its size
available,'' Robert E. Martens, president of AMR Eagle, said in a
prepared statement.
   The company announced the agreement at a news conference at AMR
headquarters. Terms of the deal were not released.
   Industry analysts estimated the agreement for the 100 Saab 340Bs
at about $750 million and AMR Eagle itself indicated earlier this
month it was about to order 100 new commuter aircraft in a deal
worth several hundred million dollars.
   The acquisition is the fourth major purchase by the American
Airlines system this year.
   AMR will receive its first 15 Saab 340Bs in January 1990. They
initially will be based at the airline's Nashville and
Raleigh-Durham hubs. More deliveries are scheduled for 1991, when
the airline will receive 24 planes, and in 1992, with a shipment of
11 aircraft.
   Delivery is scheduled in 1992 and 1993 for the 340Bs on option,
while the Saab 2000 options are scheduled between 1994 and 1997.
   Martens described the aircraft as fuel efficient and said they
are an important part of American Eagle's internal expansion plan.
With the purchase, American Eagle becomes the largest single
purchaser of Saab 340Bs in the world.
   With the first delivery of 50 Saab aircraft, American Eagle's
fleet will total just under 200. The American Eagle network carries
6.5 million passengers annually to 137 destinations in the United
States and the Caribbean.
</TEXT>
