<FIRST>r f AM-MCorp-FirstCity     05-24 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MCorp-First City,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>First City to Bid On MCorp Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First City Bankcorp of Texas plans to submit a
bid for the 20 former MCorp banks taken over by the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. earlier this year.
   First City Chairman A. Robert Abboud said his institution has
financial agreements in place to make the purchase should the FDIC
accept the offer.
   ``We are going to submit a bid,'' Abboud said Tuesday. ``I
think, as well as anyone, we know the mechanics and the fragilities
of presenting such a bid. We will be competitive.''
   Abboud led a group that completed a $1.6 billion purchase and
restructuring of Houston-based First City last year that included a
pledge to raise $500 million of private capital to go with $970
million of FDIC assistance.
   Federal officials seized 20 of MCorp's 25 banks in March,
claiming they were insolvent. The FDIC wants to sell the banks.
   Abboud said First City also has made a ``rudimentary
examination'' of National Bancshares of Texas and Texas American
Bancshares. Although he did not rule out bidding on those two
banks, he said First City is concentrating on MCorp.
   The 20 former MCorp banks, with assets of $13.09 billion, now
operate as Deposit Insurance Bridge Bank. MCorp holds the five
other banks and is operating them under protection of Chapter 11
bankruptcy.
   Abboud said he understands that May 31 is the deadline for
making bids on the Dallas-based bridge bank. The sale is expected
by July 4.
</TEXT>
