<FIRST>r f AM-IMF-Philippines     05-24 0109</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF-Philippines,0115</SECOND>
<HEAD>IMF Approves $1.2 Billion in Loans to Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippines, which has debts of more than
$30 billion, has been offered another $1.17 billion in loans by the
International Monetary Fund, officials said Wednesday.
   The offer was approved Tuesday at a closed door meeting of the
board of executive directors, representing the 151 member
governments that own the fund.
   Officials said $819 million will be available over three years.
Disbursement of each installment depends on the country fulfilling
promises about the management of its economy.
   Another $351 million will be available in case the Philippines
suffers a drop in its earnings from exports.
</TEXT>
