<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2006EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Coleco-Hasbro     05-24 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coleco-Hasbro,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coleco Nearing Sale to Hasbro</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bankruptcy court hearings on a proposal
to allow Hasbro Inc. to buy most of ailing Coleco Industries Inc.
for more than $85 million were adjourned for one week, a Coleco
lawyer said Wednesday.
   Daniel Golden said all pending matters will be taken up in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in New York next Wednesday.
   He declined to discuss details of a hearing Wednesday or the
proposal, citing an agreement on a news blackout reached last month.
   A Hartford newspaper reported this week that details of the plan
in Avon-based Coleco's 10-month-old bankruptcy case were still
being negotiated. John O'Neill, Hasbro's chief financial officer,
declined Wednesday to discuss the plan, but said he expected an
announcement would be made soon.
   ``We continue to work inside the bankruptcy court,'' he said.
``We would imagine that something will happen soon. However, we do
not anticipate at this point making an announcement.''
   Coleco officials did not return telephone calls seeking comment.
   On Tuesday, an estimated $200,000 of Coleco's surplus furniture,
office machines and manufacturing equipment was auctioned off,
symbolizing the demise of the company that introduced Cabbage Patch
Kids dolls.
   The sale, conducted by a New York auction house in a warehouse
adjacent to Coleco's Avon offices, was held to help the foundering
toy manufacturer reduce its equipment in storage and raise cash to
stay alive.
   But unnamed sources told The Hartford Courant the plan to sell
most of Coleco's assets to the Pawtucket, R.I.-based Hasbro will
likely mean the disappearance of Coleco and loss of the remaining
150 jobs.
   The Courant said the deal would involve selling most of Coleco's
assets to Hasbro, ending Coleco's 57 years as an independent
company.
   Sources told the newspaper Coleco's committee of unsecured
creditors would drop a $71 million lawsuit against the company's
largest creditors, New York businessmen Isaac Perlmutter and
Bernard Marden. Perlmutter and Marden, in turn, would reduce their
$80 million claim against Coleco.
   The lawsuit contends that Perlmutter and Marden cheated Coleco
out of millions of dollars through a complex scheme of trading
television advertising time for products.
   Coleco grew to be one of the nation's largest toy companies in
the past decade but demand for its Cabbage Patch Kids dolls wanted
and new products didn't make up lost sales. Coleco had debts of
$540.3 million when it filed for bankruptcy last July.
   Coleco's first reorganization plan, filed in January, was
rejected by the creditors' committee.
   In March, Coleco said it was considering selling the company
outright. But several weeks later Coleco said it would instead
propose a new reorganization plan offering a larger repayment to
creditors.
   The company had not filed that new plan when creditors announced
April 19 they had negotiated a deal to sell most of Coleco to
Hasbro for more than $85 million in cash.
</TEXT>
