<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CNW-Japonica     05-24 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CNW-Japonica,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>CNW Defers Action On Japnonica, Sets Deadline for Bids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CNW Corp. urged its shareholders Wednesday to
delay selling stock to Japonica Partners while the railroad company
searches for other potential buyers.
   A committee of CNW directors set a June 2 deadline for
submitting bids for the company, which operates the Chicago and
Northwestern Transportation Co., a 6,000-mile railroad serving nine
states.
   Japonica, a New York-based investment group, has offered
$44-a-share for outstanding CNW stock and already owns 8.8 percent
of the company.
   The CNW committee said it will not take a position on Japonica's
hostile takeover attempt while it talks with other potential
bidders.
   ``We decided not to take a position on Japonica's tender offer
at this time because we are continuing to investigate whether there
are alternatives ... that would maximize stockholder value,'' said
C.J. Gauthier, chairman of the directors' committee.
   ``The committee is also seeking more information on Japonica's
ability to finance its tender offer,'' he said.
   The committee's financial advisers are having discussions with
other potential bidders, as well as with Japonica.
   ``We expect to know more about where matters stand after the
deadline for bids has expired,'' Gauthier said. ``We urge
stockholders to defer acting on the Japonica tender offer until the
committee has made a further announcement.''
   Shareholders re-elected CNW directors on Tuesday by a nearly
2-to-1 margin, but management's recommendation for an executive
incentive plan was rejected.
   Japonica had urged shareholders at last week's annual meeting to
reject both the incentive plan and management's slate of directors.
</TEXT>
