<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Lorenzo 1stLd-Writethru   05-24 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Lorenzo, 1st Ld-Writethru,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorenzo Says Shuttle Sale Gives Boost to Eastern Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 10th graf to DELETE extraneous word `Air'; picks up 11th
graf pvs bg'ng, ``He (</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines boss Frank Lorenzo said
Wednesday the imminent sale of Eastern's prized Northeast shuttle
was critical to his plan to restructure the strikebound carrier and
would give the plan further momentum.
   ``Without the shuttle sale, you can forget about our
alternatives,'' Lorenzo said in an interview with The Associated
Press shortly before a federal bankruptcy judge approved a deal to
sell the shuttle to developer Donald Trump.
   ``The shuttle is the most easily salable, separable asset of
Eastern Airlines,'' said Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent
Texas Air Corp.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland approved in principle
Trump's $365 million offer for the shuttle.
   Earlier, America West Airlines withdrew a higher offer for the
New York-Washington-Boston shuttle after deciding it couldn't meet
a 5 p.m. deadline set by Eastern to arrange financing for the
purchase.
   Miami-based Eastern filed for Chapter 11 protection from its
creditors on March 9, five days after its Machinists union struck.
Pilots and flight attendants have honored the walkout, forcing
Eastern to cut back its flight schedule by around 90 percent.
   The federal bankruptcy court must approve any sale of Eastern
assets.
   The shuttle was Eastern's only consistently profitable operation
before the strike.
   Eastern's unions wanted the airline sold as a single entity. But
Texas Air sought to sell the shuttle and another $1.4 billion or so
of the airline's assets separately and rebuild as a smaller carrier.
   Lorenzo said the sale of the shuttle would give momentum to his
plan to reshape Eastern. He said he believes Lifland _ who has
repeatedly urged that Eastern resume flying at full strength _ is
leaning toward approving the restructuring plan.
   ``He (Lifland) is now gradually ... realizing that nobody out
there is going to invest the hundreds of millions of dollars that
are now necessary to bring this airline up'' in its original form,
Lorenzo said.
   Under Eastern's plan, Lorenzo said, Eastern would be rebuilt as
a smaller carrier ``that is concentrated on more protected
markets'' such as Atlanta and destinations in the Northeast.
   Several potential suitors have approached Texas Air about buying
all of Eastern, but the company has not received any proposals it
considered viable.
   Lorenzo indicated Trump had an edge over America West in the
shuttle fight, partly because the Trump deal was ``certainty''
while details of the America West bid such as financing remained up
in the air up through the deadline.
   Lorenzo also called Trump the logical owner for the shuttle
because he was ``willing to pay for the franchise value.''
   ``The shuttle is a diamond,'' he said.``Anybody who's willing to
look at the Plaza Hotel and pay the price for that as a diamond, is
going to look at our Plaza Hotel, which is the shuttle.''
   Trump bought the landmark Manhattan hotel for $395 million about
a year ago.
   ``If somebody were to buy (the shuttle) just based on earnings,
you would have a hard time with $365 million,'' he said.
</TEXT>
