<DOCNO> AP890524-0326 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 2153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Southmark     05-24 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Southmark,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Investor Named To Board, Ending Proxy Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southmark Corp., saddled with $1.1 billion in debt
and struggling to avoid bankruptcy, reached agreement with a
dissident investor Wednesday that ended a proxy fight.
   Southmark agreed to add Herbert Parks, a Greensboro, N.C.,
developer and real estate investor, and two associates to an
expanded board of directors.
   Parks had first sought to gain control of the company from
chairman Arthur G. Weiss. He had complained that Weiss was
incapable of managing the troubled financial services company as it
tried to recover from losses suffered mainly because of Texas' real
estate depression and thrift troubles.
   Although Parks had first sought to replace Southmark's entire
seven-member board with his own nominees, he was forced to cut back
to three nominees because of federal regulations governing thrifts
owned by Southmark.
   ``Our concern from the start has been to ensure that Southmark
is managed for the best interest of all its shareholders,'' said
Parks, who owns about 4.5 percent of the Dallas-based company's
outstanding common stock.
   ``This agreement satisfies us that that will be the case,''
Parks said in a joint statement with Weiss.
   The three nominees will be seated immediately on Southmark's
board, which will be expanded from seven to 10 members. The
management team will remain unchanged.
   Parks also agreed not to seek control of the company or to
participate in a proxy battle for at least two years. In return,
Southmark agreed to reimburse the Parks Group an unspecified amount
for certain expenses.
   Southmark last month reported a $1.04 billion quarterly loss,
due mainly to an $829 million writedown of its real estate assets.
The company said the loss left the company with a negative $428
million in stockholders' equity and placed it in default on $1.1
billion worth of mainly high-yield bonds issued to build up its
portfolio.
   Bondholders could begin proceedings to force the liquidation of
the company, but so far have declined to do so. Weiss said the
company will begin meeting with bondholders June 7 to discuss the
company's restructuring.
   Southmark pays about $30 million in interest on the bonds each
quarter and so far has made all its payments, spokeswoman Susan
Seiter said. The next payment is due July 15, and Ms. Seiter said
Southmark's board has not decided whether it will be able to make
that payment.
   On Tuesday, Southmark announced an agreement in principle to
sell its 89 percent interest in Integon Corp., its largest
insurance subsidiary, for $135.5 million.
   In the past few months, the company also has sold off other
holdings for a total of $167 million, all but $7 million in cash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
